<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) -- A major business organization asked  
the government Wednesday to bar from the country a U.S. labor 
activist who has campaigned against alleged abuses in Honduran 
clothing factories. 
</P>
<P>
	Eduardo Facusse, president of the Honduran Private Enterprise  
Council, accused Charles Kernaghan of spreading falsehoods abroad 
about mistreatment of workers in assembly plants. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the third time that Honduran businessmen have tried to  
have Kernaghan banned from the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Kernaghan, head of the nonprofit National Labor Committee in New  
York City, has called for boycotts of companies that exploit 
workers in poor countries. He arrived Monday in Honduras to visit 
factory workers. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) -- President Luis Gonzalez Macchi, who  
assumed power when his predecessor stepped down amid a political 
crisis this year, can remain in office through 2003, Paraguay's 
Supreme Court has ruled. 
</P>
<P>
	The high court on Tuesday said Gonzalez Macchi will not face an  
election and will be able to serve out the term of former President 
Raul Cubas, who resigned in March after the assassination of Vice 
President Luis Argana. 
</P>
<P>
	The court also ruled that elections to seat a new vice president  
will be held Nov. 21. Gonzalez Macchi has said he would support an 
opposition candidate for the post. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Relatives of the man known as Carlos  
the Jackal have praised a letter of solidarity sent to the 
convicted terrorist by Venezuela's president. 
</P>
<P>
	President Hugo Chavez has insisted that the letter, sent soon  
after his election in February, was meant to show ``human 
solidarity'' not ``political solidarity'' with Ilich Ramirez 
Sanchez. He is serving a life term in a Paris prison for the 1975 
murders of two French investigators and a Lebanese man. 
</P>
<P>
	In the letter, Chavez addressed the Venezuelan-born Carlos as  
``Dear compatriot'' and, according to press reports, signed the 
missive ``with profound faith in the cause and the mission, now and 
forever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carlos's brother, Vladimir Ramirez, told reporters Tuesday that  
the letter was ``a beautiful gesture of solidarity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Once one of the world's most wanted terrorists, Carlos was  
linked to the 1975 seizure of OPEC ministers in Vienna, Austria, 
and the 1976 hijacking of an Air France jet to Uganda. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- French automaker Renault on Wednesday  
laid the cornerstone of a $120 million engine plant in southern 
Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	The new factory will be built in the city of Curitiba, 217 miles  
southwest of Sao Paulo, next to an auto plant Renault inaugurated 
in December. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant is expected to be concluded by early 2000 with an  
initial annual output of 57,000 engines, the automaker's press 
office said. By 2002, the factory will produce 280,000 units a 
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
