<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Threatens Veto of Y2K Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The administration has threatened a veto of  
Senate legislation that would curb lawsuits arising out of Year 
2000 computer problems, contending the measure would make it easier 
for defendants to avoid their legal responsibilities. 
</P>
<P>
	The veto warning further endangered a bill already rewritten  
many times. Proponents contend only federal action can stop an 
economically calamitous wave of Y2K litigation while critics 
believe the bill would undermine basic legal rights. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill on the Senate floor this week, sponsored by Sens. John  
McCain, R-Ariz., and Ron Wyden, D-Ore., would give businesses 90 
days to fix computer problems before suits could be filed, 
encourage mediation and cap punitive damage awards in some lawsuits 
at $250,000. It also discourages class action lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration, in a statement, said it ``strongly opposes''  
the bill because it would ``decrease the incentives organizations 
have to be ready and assist customers'' in assuring their computers 
are Y2K-compliant. Without changes, it said, the attorney general 
would recommend a presidential veto. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration objects to capping punitive damages and  
language limiting plaintiff liability to their proportional share 
of damages. 
</P>
<P>
	Proportional liability is sought by businesses who say lawyers  
go after companies with deep pockets regardless of their 
involvement in a legal problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Wyden said the administration was ``simply off base'' in its  
criticisms. He noted that the bill only would apply to Y2K issues 
and expire after three years, and that it had been modified so that 
there would be no punitive damage caps when a business or 
individual acts in bad faith. 
</P>
<P>
	The McCain-Wyden bill was also under attack on at least three  
other legislative fronts to avert what many experts say could be up 
to $1 trillion in litigation resulting from breakdowns from 
computers that misread the year 2000 as 1900. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Christopher Dodd., D-Conn., one of the Senate's leaders on  
the issue, has proposed a substitute that would limit punitive 
damage caps to individuals and small businesses, remove all 
liability caps on business directors and officers and retain state 
laws on the degree to which a defendant must prove the plaintiff 
acted willfully in injuring them. 
</P>
<P>
	Sens. John Kerry, D-Mass., and Charles Robb, D-Va., would remove  
consumers from the equation. They would make the bill apply only to 
commercial contracts, and take out all provisions capping punitive 
damage awards. The administration said it supported this version. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain and Wyden also had to beat back an effort by Sen. Edward  
Kennedy, D-Mass., to use the Y2K issue as a vehicle to bring the 
minimum wage debate to the floor. 
</P>
<P>
	The Y2K problem could arise when computers that use only two  
digits to read dates mistake the year 2000, or ``00,'' as 1900, 
resulting in computer systems putting out wrong information or 
breaking down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
