<HEADLINE> Pan Am Plans Flights From 5 Cities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTSMOUTH, N.H. (AP) -- Pan American Airlines Inc., once an  
industry giant but now a small charter service, plans to begin 
scheduled flights from Portsmouth and four other cities in June. 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning June 8, Pan Am will offer one flight a day from Pease  
International Tradeport here to Orlando, Fla., continuing to San 
Juan, Puerto Rico, said Hal East, a regional manager of sales and 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	Pan Am also will begin service the same day from Orlando,  
Philadelphia, San Juan and Aguadilla, Puerto Rico, East said. 
</P>
<P>
	Once an international airline, Pan Am filed for bankruptcy  
protection in 1991. A group of investors bought the Pan Am name and 
tried to revive the airline as a discount carrier, but were forced 
into Chapter 11 bankruptcy reorganization last year. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline was bought last June by Guilford Transportation  
Industries Inc., a regional freight rail company. Pan Am's seven 
planes are based at Pease and have only flown charters to date. 
</P>
<P>
	Pan Am hopes to add two more scheduled flights out of Pease by  
year's end, possibly to Atlanta and Philadelphia, East said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
