<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kodak Betting on Premium Products </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Eastman Kodak stands ready to wage any war on  
price with Fuji, but the photography giant is betting on premium 
products with premium prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Still basking in the afterglow of a strong profit report earlier  
this month, Kodak officials said Tuesday they hope to extend that 
financial rebound with innovations such as a new paper that makes 
photographs five times more durable. 
</P>
<P>
	A roll of film developed on the new paper, called DuraLife, will  
cost $2 more than pictures printed on existing Kodak paper. 
</P>
<P>
	But when it comes to preserving memories, many consumers are  
willing to pay more, officials said, noting that nearly half of 
last year's volume of film sales came from premium-priced Max film 
and Advantix digital film. 
</P>
<P>
	Likewise, Kodak plans to pursue the digital end of the market  
aggressively, hopefully driving new demand with enhanced services 
such as photo CDs and Internet-delivery of pictures. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our strategy has been to create more value for our consumers,  
to push products that truly differentiate Kodak,'' said chief 
executive George Fisher, standing by forecasts for annual growth of 
10 percent or better in earnings-per-share. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite a better-than 25 percent rebound in Kodak's share price  
since the start of April, when the stock nearly fell below $60, 
Fisher complained that Wall Street still undervalues the company. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe Kodak shares are still a great bargain,'' Fisher  
said, noting the company's aggressive strategy for repurchasing 
shares in the market. ``The grid extends beyond $100 per share, 
where we are still buying.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kodak has been trading recently in the $77 range, roughly 13  
percent below the peak of $88.93 3/4 set nearly a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Looming behind the renewed optimism, however, is the  
ever-present threat of continued price wars with Japanese rival 
Fuji. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most people in the industry understand that we're serious  
about not losing market share,'' said Kodak president Dan Carp. 
``Our last resort will be to deal with competition through pricing, 
but we will deal with pricing if we have to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carp also emphasized that in addition focusing on innovation,  
the company ``can't take the eye off the cost ball,'' even 
two-thirds of the way through a work force reduction that's slated 
to eliminate about 20,000 jobs by year-end. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
