<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Execs Convicted of Trade Espionage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YOUNGSTOWN, Ohio (AP) -- A federal jury on Wednesday convicted  
two Taiwanese executives of paying a researcher at Avery Dennison 
Corp. to hand over adhesives industry trade secrets. 
</P>
<P>
	The case was the first to reach trial under the 1996 Economic  
Espionage Act, which banned the theft of trade secrets. 
</P>
<P>
	Pin Yen Yang, 72, president of Four Pillars Enterprise Co. Ltd.,  
and his daughter, Hwei Chen ``Sally'' Yang, 40, were each found 
guilty of two counts of economic espionage. The jury also found 
Four Pillars guilty of the same charges. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yangs and their company were acquitted on a mail fraud  
charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities say the Yangs received secrets about adhesives used  
in products such as self-stick postage stamps, name labels, diaper 
tape and battery labels. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorneys immediately filed for a mistrial, arguing that  
federal prosecutors did not prove their case. U.S. District Court 
Judge Peter Economus did not immediately rule on the motion and did 
not say when he would make a decision. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yangs face a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison. No  
sentencing date was set. The company will be fined according to how 
much Economus determines Avery Dennison lost because of the spying. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Yangs were arrested in 1997, the FBI estimated the  
company lost as much as $200 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Neal, Avery Dennison's president and chief executive,  
released a statement saying he was ``extremely pleased'' with the 
verdicts. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokeswoman for Four Pillars had no immediate comment.  
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan-based Four Pillars is an adhesives maker that competes  
with Avery Dennison, based in Pasadena, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Yang and his daughter paid about $160,000 over  
eight years to Avery Dennison researcher Ten Hong ``Victor'' Lee, 
who worked at a laboratory east of Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee, a Taiwanese native, testified he struck a deal to pass  
information to the Yangs while on a trip to his homeland in 1989. 
Lee said he worked with the Yangs until 1997, when he was caught. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee pleaded guilty to wire fraud and began cooperating with the  
FBI. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors' case hinged on a secretly record FBI videotape  
showing a September 1997 meeting between the Yangs and Lee, in 
which Sally Yang cuts the ``confidential'' stamp off an Avery 
Dennison report. Pin Yen Yang then instructs Lee to dispose of the 
clipping. 
</P>
<P>
	But in closing arguments, defense attorneys said Avery Dennison  
indiscriminately marked documents as confidential. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yangs originally were charged with 21 counts each but  
Economus dismissed 18 of them before the jury began deliberating. 
The jury worked for three days before delivering a verdict. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
