<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nissan To Reduce Size of Board </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Nissan Motor Co. will slash the number of its board  
members to 10 from 37 as part of efforts to overhaul its management 
structure and speed up decision-making, the company said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 10 board members will include three executives from France's  
Renault SA, which is taking a 37 percent capital stake in Nissan. 
</P>
<P>
	Yoshifumi Tsuji will step down step as Nissan chairman and  
become an adviser. The changes are expected to be approved at a 
shareholders meeting in late June. 
</P>
<P>
	Nissan President Yoshikazu Hanawa announced earlier this month  
that the board would probably be cut. 
</P>
<P>
	And Nissan's truck-making subsidiary, Nissan Diesel Motor Co.,  
said it will slash the number of its board members to 7 from 14 as 
part of an overhaul of its management structure. 
</P>
<P>
	Alain Dassas, currently corporate finance director at Renault  
SA, will become a part-time director at Nissan Diesel, the 
truck-maker said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dassas' appointment follows Renault's decision in March to take  
a 22.5 percent stake in Nissan Diesel. 
</P>
<P>
	The changes are expected to be approved at Nissan Diesel's  
shareholders meeting in late June. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Renault agreed to pay $5.4 billion for a 36.8  
percent stake in Nissan. Nissan hopes to use the cash infusion to 
help pay off its massive debt load. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
