<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Site Helps With Travel Complaints </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Dissatisfied airline passengers have a Web site  
that lets them complain directly to airlines and the U.S. 
Department of Transportation. 
</P>
<P>
	The site, http://www.passengerrights.com, forwards the complaints to  
airline e-mail addresses not available to the general public and 
follows up on the complaints with faxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Complaints can also be sent to cruise ship companies, car rental  
agencies, hotels, resorts and tour operators. 
</P>
<P>
	The site includes details on travelers' rights, information  
about proposed legislation to protect travelers and a section for 
airline employees to anonymously report wrongdoing in the industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Randy Warren, who set up the site, said it received about 100  
complaints the first day it was active. It debuted last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Fewer than 6,000 airline service complaints were made last year  
to the DOT. But Warren told USA Today that that number is not 
representative of travelers' dissatisfaction ``because so few 
people know how to go about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, US Airways spokesman Rick Weintraub told the newspaper  
that the airline's consumer affairs number is listed in the 
in-flight magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	Warren's site suggests electronic complaints may be simpler. It  
promises to forward e-mail to ``the people who make the decisions, 
have the authority to make changes and most importantly, to solve 
your problem.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
