<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Gretzky Drops Puck in Edmonton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- Edmonton's favorite adopted son -- Wayne  
Gretzky -- returned to the scene of his greatest triumphs Tuesday 
and was greeted by more than 17,000 screaming, towel-waving Oilers 
fans. 
</P>
<P>
	Gretzky, who won four Stanley Cups with the Oilers in the 1980s,  
dropped the ceremonial first puck prior to the start of the 
Dallas-Edmonton playoff game. 
</P>
<P>
	It was his first return to Skyreach Centre since he tearfully  
retired from the NHL earlier this month. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of like home for me,'' Gretzky said in a television  
interview during the game. ``I had a lot of great years here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His appearance was kept a secret until he walked to center ice  
to a thunderous standing ovation. Players from both teams pounded 
their sticks on the ice in tribute to No. 99. 
</P>
<P>
	Dressed in a black suit, white shirt and gold tie, Gretzky  
dropped the puck between Oilers captain Kelly Buchberger and the 
Stars' Joe Nieuwendyk. 
</P>
<P>
	He waved to the crowd as they chanted ``Gretzky, Gretzky!''  
Dallas stars Mike Modano and Brett Hull came over to shake his 
hand. 
</P>
<P>
	Then with a final wave, Gretzky walked off. He was on ice for  
all of two minutes. The standing ovation followed him back through 
the tunnel but the man who has always said he doesn't want to be 
bigger than the game didn't return for an encore. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a lot of great memories with some great teams and some  
nice championships but, more importantly, I have a lot of friends 
here and it's nice to come back to Edmonton,'' Gretzky said. 
</P>
<P>
	He was invited to the game by Oilers general manager Glen  
Sather, whom Gretzky cited as one of the key influences on his life 
when he retired. 
</P>
<P>
	``Glen came all the way to New York for my last game and he  
said: `You know, you've got to come to Edmonton for a game.' ...I 
promised I'd come up for a game and I'm happy to be here.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
