<DOCNO> APW19990428.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 10:05:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Booksellers Meet To Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	On the eve of its annual national convention, the bookselling  
business has never seemed more like a business. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past 12 months, the German conglomerate Bertelsmann AG  
completed its purchase of Random House, Barnes &AMP; Noble Inc. 
announced it would buy the world's largest wholesaler, the Ingram 
Book Group, and Bertelsmann and Barnes &AMP; Noble announced a joint 
investment in the on-line seller barnesandnoble.com. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, as big business gets bigger, smaller business simply  
disappears. Since the early 1990s, bookseller membership in the 
American Booksellers Association has dropped from 5,200 to less 
than 3,500, much of that almost surely the result of superstore 
expansion. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps a few parties, and some California sun, will make it all  
go away. Booksellers, publishers, agents and authors are gathering 
at the Los Angeles Convention Center for this year's BookExpo 
America. The three-day exhibition and trade show, which starts 
Friday, ends May 2. 
</P>
<P>
	``The book business has never been more difficult nor more  
uncertain than it is now,'' said Richard Howorth, ABA president and 
owner of Square Books in Oxford, Miss. ``While it's still a 
wonderful occupation, it's awfully scary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, about 25 percent of adult book purchases were made at  
Barnes &AMP; Noble and other chains while just over 17 percent were 
made at independent stores. In 1991, independents received 32.5 
percent of sales and chains 22 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Online book sales are expected to account for 10 percent of all  
transactions by 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	BEA won't turn that around, but for a few days it gives  
independent sellers a chance to meet, commiserate and plan. One 
proposed change is to reduce the ABA's board of directors, from 20 
to nine. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're trying to make the board more responsive, more nimble  
and able to react quickly,'' said Howorth, ``because everything is 
changing so fast.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Losing customers both in cyberspace and in their neighborhoods,  
independents are fighting back any way they can. The ABA is suing 
Barnes &AMP; Noble and Borders for antitrust violations and is among 
those opposing the proposed Ingram sale, which the Federal Trade 
Commission is reviewing. The booksellers association is also 
creating its own on-line selling site, BookSense.com, scheduled to 
be ready by late summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is all being done out of necessity. You can't just sit  
around and be a guy in the shop and think life is going to go on 
the way it's been,'' Howorth said. 
</P>
<P>
	Publishers face a problem directly related to the convention:  
introducing their fall books, their main reason for coming to 
BookExpo. Because of scheduling conflicts at the Convention Center, 
this year's meeting will take place a month earlier than usual. Not 
everyone is ready. 
</P>
<P>
	``Frankly, we haven't seen enough of our manuscripts to really  
feel comfortable,'' said Laurie Brown, vice president of marketing 
for Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. ``We're cataloguing books we're not 
even sure are going to be ready on schedule.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But once in Los Angeles, there will be plenty of time for  
promotions, parties and seminars. And, at least around meal times, 
the industry will pause and let the writers talk. Featured speakers 
include Nobelist Elie Wiesel, Pulitzer Prize winners Frank McCourt 
and Jorie Graham, as well as Robert Stone, Ward Just, David 
Guterson and Nikki Giovanni. Salman Rushdie, on his first 
full-fledged book tour since being sentenced to death 10 years ago 
by Iran's Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, is expected to appear. 
</P>
<P>
	But Rushdie is likely the only writer who will draw as big a  
crowd as the weekend's most quotable ``author,'' Bill Murray, the 
undoubtedly proud papa of ``A Cinderella Story: My Life in Golf.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Those looking forward to seeing the merry Murray bear-hugging  
the sad-eyed Wiesel will be disappointed. Murray will not share the 
dais with Wiesel or any Pulitzer winners. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, his fellow breakfast speakers will include Frances  
Mayes, a California-based poet who writes about Italy, and a 
celebrity whom Dan Aykroyd, Murray's ``Saturday Night Live'' 
co-star, once parodied so well, Julia Child. 
</P>
<P>
	Bon appetit.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 05:46:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reported Mir Deal Not Finalized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Russia's main space agency is skeptical about an  
alleged deal in which a British businessman has reportedly agreed 
to pay $100 million to fly on the Mir space station. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's space industry has been desperately trying to find  
private funding for the 13-year-old orbiting space station, or else 
the station will probably have to be abandoned around August. 
</P>
<P>
	The RKK Energia corporation, which runs the Mir, claimed Tuesday  
that businessman Peter Llewelyn had agreed to invest at least $100 
million to finance the Mir's operations. In return, he would get to 
fly to the Mir for one week in August, according to Energia 
spokesman Sergei Gromov. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tel Aviv, Llewelyn said Tuesday he was not paying to go on  
Mir. He claimed his trip would be part of a fund-raising effort for 
a 2,000-bed children's hospital he plans to build in Karalauf, 25 
miles outside of Moscow. 
</P>
<P>
	``This report is totally incorrect,'' he told The Associated  
Press. ``The shuttle is going up to pick up astronauts and I'm just 
hitching a ride.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``People are going to sponsor me so much money per mile in  
space,'' he said. ``The money raised will be used for the hospital 
and nothing else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Llewelyn said two years ago his son was born with a heart  
problem. ``A surgeon saved my son's life. I made a promise that I 
would build a hospital,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sergei Gorbunov, a spokesman for the Russian Space Agency, said  
the Energia announcement was premature because the deal was far 
from final. 
</P>
<P>
	``All of us will be very happy if they find an enthusiast eager  
to finance the Mir, but I think it's too early yet to celebrate,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gromov noted that several previous negotiations with other  
would-be financiers had broken down. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not clear if Llewelyn even had the money. Two years ago,  
Llewelyn faced five counts of theft for allegedly swindling $38,000 
from a business partner in Pittsburgh, Pa. He paid the money back 
and the case was dropped. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0044 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 05:51:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  House Heads for Showdown on Balkans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Republican-led Congress is ready to double  
President Clinton's request for $6 billion to help pay for the 
conflict with Yugoslavia, but a showdown looms on the House floor 
over his authority to widen the military campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton planned to meet at the White House today with lawmakers  
from committees that deal with defense and military spending to 
discuss costs of the escalating battle. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, a measure backed by House Speaker Dennis Hastert,  
R-Ill., and other Republican leaders to require Clinton to receive 
congressional approval before deploying ground forces in Yugoslavia 
awaits a floor vote today. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is the only thing that is likely to pass,'' said House  
Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other proposals, one demanding withdrawal of U.S. troops  
from the region, the other for a declaration of war against 
Yugoslavia, were expected to be rejected. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration opposes the Republican advance-approval  
measure as an unnecessary restriction, even though it has said it 
does not plan to dispatch ground troops. The ground option is being 
reviewed by NATO's military commanders, however, and the United 
States is sending more troops and equipment to the region. 
</P>
<P>
	House and Senate Republicans readied legislation Tuesday that  
would double Clinton's $6.05 billion request to pay for the 
military action. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Appropriations Committee planned a vote Thursday on a  
$12.9 billion package for the fighting, refugees and worldwide 
Pentagon needs, including a 4.4 percent pay raise for troops. 
Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, was 
drafting a similar measure totaling nearly $12 billion that his 
panel might vote on next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pentagon announced Tuesday it will call 33,102 reservists to  
active military duty, beginning immediately with 2,116 members of 
the Air Force Reserve and Air National Guard to help in aerial 
refueling of NATO warplanes. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott ended talks  
in Moscow on Tuesday with Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov and Viktor 
Chernomyrdin, the Russian mediator for the Balkans. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Russians did not indicate any major changes in their  
position,'' State Department spokesman James P. Rubin said. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO insists that Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic must  
withdraw his Serb-led forces from Kosovo, permit the return of 
ethnic Albanians to the province and accept an armed international 
force of peacekeepers. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia strongly objects to NATO's bombing campaign and to the  
idea of a NATO-led peacekeeping force. 
</P>
<P>
	At a Pentagon news conference, Defense Secretary William Cohen  
indicated little interest in putting a peacekeeping force, in the 
event one is formed, under the command of the United Nations. 
</P>
<P>
	``There must be an international peacekeeping force that is  
NATO-led and, at the core, NATO must be involved in its 
management,'' Cohen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Administration officials were encouraged that representatives of  
the International Committee of the Red Cross had a second, longer 
visit with three U.S. soldiers being held in Belgrade as prisoners 
of war. The three were examined by a doctor, but the results were 
not made public. 
</P>
<P>
	Against the administration's advice, a delegation of U.S.  
religious leaders led by the Rev. Jesse Jackson planned to leave 
today for Yugoslavia to meet with the three Americans and try to 
secure their freedom. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration contends it needs no congressional approval  
to prosecute the military campaign against Yugoslavia, which began 
March 24. Many lawmakers contend the conflict violates the War 
Powers Act of 1973, which requires the president to obtain 
congressional approval if he keeps troops in combat for more than 
60 days. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are at war,'' Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., said, ``and  
Congress has not declared that. And that is unconstitutional.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The House International Relations Committee voted 30-19 on  
Tuesday against a resolution by Campbell requiring Clinton to bring 
troops engaged in the military campaign home in a move that set up 
a showdown on the House floor today. Campbell invoked a provision 
of the War Powers Act that requires a vote by the full House. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 05:51:02 </DATE_TIME>
