<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Entertainment Highlights in History  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Entertainment highlights during the week of May 2-8:  
</P>
<P>
	70 years ago: ``Bulldog Drummond'' made Ronald Colman one of the  
early stars of sound films. Colman also starred in the sequel, 
``Bulldog Drummond Strikes Back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	65 years ago: John Barrymore and Carole Lombard starred in  
``Twentieth Century,'' one of the first ``screwball comedies'' 
written by Ben Hecht and Charles MacArthur. The film was directed 
by Howard Hawks. 
</P>
<P>
	And Clark Gable, William Powell and Myrna Loy starred in  
``Manhattan Melodrama.'' 
</P>
<P>
	55 years ago: Bing Crosby and Barry Fitzgerald starred in  
``Going My Way.'' Crosby and Fitzgerald won Oscars. The film also 
won Oscars for best picture and best director. 
</P>
<P>
	And Charles Boyer and Ingrid Bergman starred in ``Gaslight.''  
Bergman won an Oscar. 
</P>
<P>
	50 years ago: Ten years after ``The Story of Vernon &AMP; Irene  
Castle,'' Fred Astaire and Ginger Rogers were together again for 
``The Barkleys of Broadway.'' 
</P>
<P>
	45 years ago: Johnnie Ray's ``Such a Night'' was banned by the  
BBC, even though it had topped the British chart. Listeners 
complained the song was ``suggestive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	40 years ago: The first Grammy Awards were given out by the  
National Academy of Recording Arts and Sciences. The Champs, the 
Kingston Trio and Henry Mancini were among the winners. 
</P>
<P>
	35 years ago: The Moody Blues were formed in Birmingham,  
England. 
</P>
<P>
	20 years ago: ``Quadrophenia,'' the film based on The Who's  
album of the same name, opened in London. To celebrate the film's 
debut, the band played its first concert with new drummer Kenney 
Jones, who had replaced the late Keith Moon. 
</P>
<P>
	10 years ago: Edward R. Murrow and Bill Cosby were voted into TV  
Guide magazine's ``TV Hall of Fame'' for their lasting 
contributions to television. 
</P>
<P>
	Five years ago: Director Steven Spielberg accepted a certificate  
of appreciation from the Defense Department for his World War II 
film, ``Schindler's List.'' Spielberg was praised by Defense 
Secretary William Perry for ``harnessing the power of motion 
pictures to focus on a time we must never, never forget.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One year ago: Director Martin Scorsese received a standing  
ovation at the Film Society of Lincoln Center's 25th annual Gala 
Tribute in New York City. Robert De Niro, Joe Pesci, Winona Ryder 
and Ellen Burstyn were among the actors offering testimonials. 
</P>
<P>
	Geraldo Rivera taped the final episode of his daytime talk show,  
giving it up as part of his agreement to take on a larger role at 
NBC News. Family and friends raised glasses of champagne after 
Rivera introduced tapes of the past 11 years. 
</P>
<P>
	And ``Tonight'' show host Jay Leno couldn't repeat as America's  
top car buff. Winners of the Collector Car Hobby Person of the Year 
award were two organizers of the Pebble Beach, Calif., Concours 
d'Elegance, a car show dubbed the Oscars of vintage automobiles. 
Quipped Leno: ``I was kind of hoping I would be the first person to 
win the award twice, but it didn't go that way. So instead they 
chose two men to do the job of one.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken five years ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's important that kids see someone who came from a  
similar situation -- on welfare, no father figure -- who went on to 
make something of himself.'' -- Actor Robert Townsend. 

</P>
<P>
	Spoken one year ago:  
</P>
<P>
	``I had my own transvestite-in-a-trailer-park era. Then I looked  
around and realized it was just untenable. I couldn't look in the 
mirror. I needed to feel good about going to work. So we turned the 
program around. We sacrificed some ratings points but we gained 
enormously in terms of self-respect.'' -- Talk-show host Geraldo 
Rivera. 

</P>
<P>
	``I took my daughter to the Grand Ole Opry a couple of years  
ago, and as we were listening to the country music there, it dawned 
on me that the themes of country music are totally consistent with 
the themes of talk shows.'' -- Talk-show host Jerry Springer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 15:05:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> School Security Business Booming </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Garrett Metal Detectors is awash in new orders  
as principals and teachers across the country try to shake feelings 
of vulnerability in the wake of the Columbine High School massacre. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales to schools have grown from almost nothing four years ago  
into the largest share of the company's business -- surpassing 
orders for airports, prisons and courts, said Jim Dobrei, vice 
president of marketing for Garrett, the nation's largest maker of 
metal detectors. 
</P>
<P>
	Schools now account for up to one-quarter of the Garland,  
Texas-based company's sales, Dobrei said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I kept expecting it to slow down,'' he said. ``Now I'm  
convinced it's not going to slow down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Metal detectors -- which range from about $150 for a hand-held  
detector to $2,500 for the walk-through variety -- are only one of 
many safety devices schools are buying to try to protect staff and 
students. In interview after interview, experts said the school 
safety industry, which scarcely existed a few years ago, has become 
a major part of the $38 billion U.S. security business. 
</P>
<P>
	Even before the attack on Columbine High, demand was growing, as  
weapons and gangs spread to suburban and rural schools, and down to 
junior high and elementary levels. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have been doing school safety training for 15 years, and  
Littleton, Colo., has elevated school safety and concern to an 
entirely new level,'' said Ronald Stephens, executive director of 
the National School Safety Center in Westlake Village, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	``This incident not only involved, in essence, a conspiracy  
among assailants, not only high-powered weapons and semiautomatic 
weapons, it also introduced a new factor: explosive devices.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And the explosions are echoing through school halls nationwide.  
The Bibb County School District, which includes Macon, Ga., is 
applying for grant money to buy two bomb-sniffing dogs. 
</P>
<P>
	In Las Vegas, the Clark County schools are considering  
installing night-vision cameras for campus parking lots. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan schools are sampling software similar to that used by  
the Department of Defense to find weak spots in security. RiskWatch 
Inc. in Annapolis, Md., developed a version for schools that asks 
350 questions, weighs security priorities and evaluates the most 
cost-effective solutions. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, school fatalities have been declining since 1992. Even  
with the 15 deaths last week in Colorado, this school year's total 
of 24 homicides and suicides is well below last year's 43 -- when 
the shootings at Jonesboro, Ark., Edinboro, Pa., and Springfield, 
Ore., pushed the numbers higher. 
</P>
<P>
	What is on the rise are the numbers of spectacular,  
multiple-victim attacks that seize the headlines. And safety 
experts say no preparations could have totally deterred determined 
killers like Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold. 
</P>
<P>
	A week before the massacre, Columbine High held a staff crisis  
training session as part of the school district's effort to update 
its security. The updated report was due at the end of the school 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	The decision to spend previous dollars on safety devices is a  
tough one for school districts that need new textbooks, more 
teachers and better computers. And superintendents strive to 
provide protection without imposing a rigid, confining environment 
that interferes with learning. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Dorn, chief of the Bibb County Board of Education Campus  
Police, says the investments in security are worth it. 
</P>
<P>
	With an annual police budget of about $2.5 million, roughly 2  
percent of the district's budget, he runs one of the nation's most 
extensive safety programs. Bibb County's five high schools, five 
middle schools and 30 elementary schools are secured by 27 armed 
police, five community officers, one crime analyst, metal 
detectors, surveillance cameras and a gun-sniffing dog. 
</P>
<P>
	At 7 a.m., when buses pull up to the schools, officers board  
buses randomly for weapons checks. Surprise inspections are also 
carried out in classrooms and lockers. The officers additionally 
watch school grounds from unmarked cars and occasionally search 
campus perimeters for buried weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	The results: with less than two months to run in this school  
year, the district has recorded two weapons violations, compared to 
18 a decade ago when it began strengthening security. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet, Dorn says, ``We know, no matter what we do, weapons will  
still come on campus.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In a survey of urban and suburban schools last May by Security  
Magazine, almost three-quarters of respondents said they had 
security officers and one-third of them are armed. About 55 percent 
have closed-circuit televisions trained on corridors, exterior 
doors and parking lots. 
</P>
<P>
	William Ogg, marketing director for Sentry Technology Corp., has  
recently been fielding about 50 calls a week from schools looking 
for closed-circuit TVs, up from about 10 calls a week this time 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Sentry, based in Hauppauge, N.Y., started marketing to schools a  
year ago. Today, schools account for 5 percent to 10 percent of the 
company's $30 million in annual sales, and Ogg expects the school 
business to double this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Closed-circuit cameras, which cost about $1,600 for a simple  
black-and-white model and up to $20,000 for a top-of the line, 
16-camera rig, have been a very effective crime-stopper, school 
administrators say. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have seen a decline in vandalism at many of our schools, a  
decline in negative behavior and visitors,'' said Sydney Franklin, 
assistant superintendent for the Clark County School District in 
Las Vegas and school police supervisor. 
</P>
<P>
	Clark County has 28 high schools, 34 middle schools and 148  
elementary schools. The district is no stranger to violence. In 
1982, a teacher was killed. In 1992, a student was shot. 
</P>
<P>
	The district now spends $6 million a year on security, just over  
1 percent of the budget. That covers a 105-member police force, 
gang abatement specialists, and a hot line for tips and counseling. 
</P>
<P>
	After Columbine, Franklin said, ``I am going to look at probably  
better camera equipment so we can deal with night situations much 
better,'' he said. 



</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
