<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pacers Stall As NBA Playoffs Near </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- This is a confused and frustrated team. The  
Indiana Pacers, a team with championship aspirations, are proving 
to be a club that loses close games when it can least afford to. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pacers practiced together daily for months during the NBA  
lockout, anticipating a payoff once the season began. Home-court 
advantage throughout the playoffs was one goal, but that's now 
mathematically impossible. 
</P>
<P>
	Home-court advantage throughout the Eastern Conference playoffs  
is a long shot. The Pacers enter their final four games of the 
regular season struggling to hold first place in the Central 
Division. 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana's lead over second-place Atlanta was cut to a half game  
with Tuesday's 88-87 loss to Orlando, and then the Hawks tied the 
Pacers on Wednesday by beating the New York Knicks 76-73. 
</P>
<P>
	Three of Indiana's final four games are at home, but that  
apparent edge seems minimal since the Pacers have lost three of 
their last six home games. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year when we needed to win at home, we won,'' Antonio  
Davis said. ``This year we can't put together a bucket, a stop, a 
win, when we really need it. It's scary because we just can't get 
it done and we don't know why.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana is 1-6 in games decided by one point and four of the  
losses have been at Market Square Arena. Failure to protect leads 
late in the game and inability to make game-saving stops have 
become common. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was a very tough loss with the same story on a different  
day and the same ending,'' Jalen Rose said after the loss to 
Orlando, which cost the Pacers home court advantage with Orlando if 
the teams finish the regular season in a tie. ``We must stop this. 
I think we're thinking about it too much and just haven't gotten 
into the rhythm to pull out these games when we need to be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Larry Bird has stressed the importance of home-court  
advantage in the playoffs since the lockout ended. But the team is 
now in danger of not having home advantage past the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami, the Atlantic Division leader, holds a 2 1/2-game lead over  
Indiana and would likely win the tiebreaker if the two teams 
finished the season with identical records. The teams split their 
four games this season, and the second tiebreaker would be 
conference record. Miami has a three-game lead over Indiana in 
conference games. 
</P>
<P>
	The first tiebreaker in determining home-court advantage is  
head-to-head games and Pacers have lost the season series to 
Orlando and Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as winning the East, catching Miami, is probably out of  
reach,'' Dale Davis said. ``You have to put it behind us ... and 
keep pecking away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana is 6-8 in games decided by three or fewer points and is  
only 12-14 against teams with winning records. 
</P>
<P>
	``A majority of these games, we shouldn't have been in this  
position ... where it's so tight,'' Dale Davis said. ``As a team, 
we have to step it up and put teams away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The time to do that starts Thursday when Charlotte comes to  
town. Indiana makes its last road stop of the regular season on 
Friday at Atlanta and finishes at home with New York on Sunday and 
Cleveland on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just being in that position is a little bit discouraging for a  
team like us,'' Davis said. ``It's still not over. We still have 
time to correct some things, and make this a championship squad.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``If we don't watch out, we won't have any home court,'' Bird  
said. ``Losing like this is tough on everybody and it's tough to 
bounce back, but somehow we have to find a way.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
