<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Books and Authors: Antebellum Family </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Henry Wiencek was writing about old family  
homes when he first happened upon Cooleemee, an antebellum 
plantation home on North Carolina's Yadkin River. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Peter Hairston, Cooleemee's owner, introduced Wiencek to  
Squire Hairston, whose grandfather was the slave of Peter's 
grandfather. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was shocked when those two men shook hands,'' Wiencek said  
in a telephone interview. ``Here are two men with the closest 
possible connection to slavery. ... It hinted that a private 
reconciliation had occurred in this family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That moment launched Wiencek on an eight-year exploration of  
slavery in America as seen through the prism of one family. The 
upshot is ``The Hairstons,'' a well-plotted, crisply written hybrid 
of biography and good detective yarn published by St. Martin's 
Press. 
</P>
<P>
	``What fascinated me was when you look at the history of  
slavery, the question in my mind is what happened next? How did 
those families deal with what they had done?'' said Wiencek. 
</P>
<P>
	Wiencek traces the rise and the fall of the two houses of  
Hairston -- the rise of the white plantation-owning Hairstons and 
their decline with Reconstruction, and the slow, painful rise of 
the family's black branch. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was the destiny of the white Hairstons to enact the  
downfall of the Old South,'' Wiencek wrote. ``And, for their part, 
it was the destiny of the black Hairstons to enact the exodus 
embedded in our national story -- the miraculous, astounding rise of 
the African-Americans from the dust of slavery. Slavery could not 
crush them, nor anything thereafter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wiencek, 46, a Boston native and Yale University graduate now  
living in Charlottesville, Va., has published two books on Southern 
architecture and several books for Time-Life. He is also the author 
of ``Old Houses,'' essays on the histories of 18 American homes and 
the families that built them. His research for that book brought 
him to Cooleemee and introduced him to the Hairstons. 
</P>
<P>
	He interviewed scores of Hairstons and studied plantation  
archives, slave rosters, public records, accounts by slave traders 
and Quakers who helped runaway slaves. All the while, he hunted for 
a common ancestor of both the black and white Hairstons. 
</P>
<P>
	He wrote that at times he ``felt all the moral confusion of a  
spy. I was a Northerner adrift in the heart of the old Confederacy, 
an honored visitor in stately homes whose legacy I found deeply 
troubling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Facts emerge: a white Hairston slave owner who on his deathbed  
signed over his holdings to his common-law wife, a slave; 
lynchings, murders; extraordinary kindnesses; destitute Hairston 
women after the Civil War taking seeds out of dolls and planting 
them; black Hairstons becoming teachers, lawyers, farmers, 
ministers and entertainers. 
</P>
<P>
	The first Hairston, ``Peter the Immigrant,'' was a Scot who  
settled along the Dan River of Virginia in the 1700s. Through 
careful intermarriage, his descendants built an empire of 45 
tobacco and cotton plantations worked by 10,000 slaves in Virginia, 
North Carolina and Mississippi. Cooleemee, located south of 
Winston-Salem, is one of the last remnants. 
</P>
<P>
	Slavery enriched the white Hairstons and others in Southern  
aristocracy, but eventually, as in a morality tale, it would bring 
down their empires. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seemed that the moral blindness of these slaveholders was  
total,'' Wiencek wrote. They clung to the irrational belief that 
blacks were inferior, ``even as they grew more and more dependent 
on the skills of the black people, saw the growth of the 
generations in their black family, and felt the stirrings of 
emotion when one of them died.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He relates the story of Robert Hairston, who freed several of  
his slaves in 1832. Alienated from his Virginia family, he migrated 
to Mississippi and took a slave as his common-law wife. On his 
deathbed, he willed her all of his possessions and set her free. 
</P>
<P>
	``He had turned the world upside down -- a slave girl was now one  
of the richest women in the United States,'' Wiencek wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	But relatives tied up the will in court, and she never got the  
inheritance or her freedom. 
</P>
<P>
	In the interview, Wiencek said slave owners pushed the Southern  
states to pass restrictive laws that prevented owners like Robert 
Hairston from setting their slaves free. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the Southern states had not passed such restrictive laws  
about freed slaves, we probably would have seen a gradual 
emancipation of the slaves coming from within the South itself,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	During the war, 83 white Hairstons served in the Confederate  
Army. Their cousins included Confederate Gens. Jeb Stuart and Jubal 
Early. Of the black Hairstons, Thomas served as a bugler in the 3rd 
U.S. Colored Cavalry. 
</P>
<P>
	After the war, life was different for both Hairston clans. For  
many white Hairstons, Reconstruction brought economic ruin. For 
their black counterparts, there were lynchings and kangaroo courts 
and raw poverty. Then came the institutional injustices and horrors 
of the Jim Crow era that continued into World War II, when black 
volunteers were badly treated in the armed forces, and beyond. 
</P>
<P>
	The civil rights era brought a ``patchwork of reconciliation''  
among the Hairstons, Wiencek said. ``They made a start. I hope the 
next generation will do even better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1978, Peter Hairston invited the black Hairstons to Cooleemee  
to celebrate its new National Historic Landmark status. He 
delivered a speech in which he called Cooleemee a sacred place, 
``the altar that represents the result of the struggle of your race 
and mine.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
