<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> High-Tech Workers for Sale on Online </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Available via auction: 16 cybergeeks who  
work together well and know how to assemble an Internet server. 
Asking price: $3.14 million. 
</P>
<P>
	In a novel listing posted on eBay, a team of managers and  
engineers for an Internet service provider has gone straight to the 
online auction house that usually sells Beanie Babies and 
autographed baseballs. 
</P>
<P>
	They're selling themselves -- and their experience assembling  
high-tech computer systems. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they're shipped via UPS,'' quips one Internet response  
to the auction posting. 
</P>
<P>
	But it's no joke. When the auctioning period closes May 8, the  
highest bidder will be bound to buy the team, eBay said. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people think it's a joke, but I'm totally serious  
with this,'' a spokesman for the group calling itself ``ispteam'' 
said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The 16 workers -- including a director, two managers, three  
engineers and five administrators -- claim they currently work, 
unhappily, for a Silicon Valley company. They're keeping their 
employer secret for fear of getting fired. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were just sitting around talking, watching our company  
disintegrate and watching all these great people leaving,'' he 
said. They had been working together for years, and hated the idea 
of splitting up. 
</P>
<P>
	Recalling a spoof in which a seller tried to auction off a  
16-year-old girl -- eBay yanked the listing -- and real bids for 
dinner with venture capitalist Steve Jurveston (the $10,000 winning 
bid went to charity), someone in the group jokingly suggested 
auctioning themselves off as a team on eBay. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're like, 'Wait a minute. That's not a bad idea. That'll  
work!''' said the spokesman, a 23-year-old software engineer. 
</P>
<P>
	He offered to take the initiative -- and posted the listing  
Tuesday night in the computers category. 
</P>
<P>
	``Team of 16 employees from major ISP willing to leave as a  
group,'' the item reads. ``Group formed major ISP presence in 
Silicon Valley/US and is now looking for other challenges and 
requires an opportunity with a major player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The selling price reflects salaries, including $200,000 for the  
director and $190,000 for each engineer. ``That would give us all 
raises,'' the spokesman said. ``That's one of the benefits of 
putting this on the auction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They've also got some requirements: a $320,000 signing bonus,  
401(k), stock options. And the company must be based in Silicon 
Valley or San Francisco. eBay would get a commission of $39,260. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nowhere else in the world could this happen,'' said Jean  
Bagileo, vice president at the Silicon Valley headhunting firm 
David Powell, Inc. ``It's provocative, it's humorous, you kind of 
think it can't be true, but go figure. Evidently they're trying to 
avoid us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By Wednesday evening, they had two bids that had met the $3.14  
million asking price. And some ``big, cool companies'' -- major 
names in the e-commerce world -- have already e-mailed asking for 
resumes, the ispteam spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	eBay has its share of odd auction items. But this is the first  
selling people, said Kevin Pursglove, a spokesman for San 
Jose-based eBay, which has almost 2 million items for sale today. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is certainly one of the more interesting items we've  
had,'' he said. ``It could be the start of something really big.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It beats dealing with headhunters, the ispteam spokesman said.  
</P>
<P>
	``At the very minimum it stirred up a lot of frustration and  
could scare the company I'm working for,'' he said. ``And I think 
it's a cool idea.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0053 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 05:41:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> S. Korean Conglomerates Under Fire </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- President Kim Dae-jung is threatening  
new action against South Korea's five largest conglomerates, saying 
they are not instituting reforms quickly enough. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim met with the heads of the business giants over dinner  
Tuesday night and threatened to put their firms under court 
receivership unless they sharply reduced their size and debts. 
</P>
<P>
	Restructuring the nation's family-run conglomerates is the  
centerpiece of reforms being pushed by Kim to revive the crisis-hit 
South Korean economy. 
</P>
<P>
	It wasn't the first time Kim has threatened the conglomerates,  
known here as chaebol, but it came only days after two of the five 
groups announced new and extensive restructuring plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``There still is an atmosphere of half-belief, half-doubt among  
the public about promises of reform by chaebol,'' Kim told the 
heads of Hyundai, Samsung, Daewoo, LG and SK. 
</P>
<P>
	Only last week, Daewoo and Hyundai said they planned to shed  
dozens of affiliates through sales and mergers by the end of the 
year and concentrate on a handful of core businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	That is exactly what the president has been demanding for more  
than a year, but the restructuring announcements by Daewoo and 
Hyundai didn't deter him from threatening them again. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many people -- I believe even the president -- think that  
chaebol are extremely slow in reforming,'' said Lee Jae-shik of the 
Financial Supervisory Commission, the nation's corporate watchdog. 
</P>
<P>
	The president told the five chaebol leaders that unless they  
comply with his demands, their firms could wind up under control of 
the banks holding their debt or in court receivership. 
</P>
<P>
	``The government will provide support for those who make  
self-rescue and self-reform efforts,'' Kim said. ``But we cannot 
but take strong actions against those which do not.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The top five conglomerates promised last year to halve the  
number of companies they control and raise a total of $5.8 billion 
to improve their financial positions. 
</P>
<P>
	Government officials said most of those commitments lag behind  
schedule and that some conglomerates have even gotten bigger and 
further in debt. 
</P>
<P>
	``What chaebol have been doing is mostly announcing plans that  
are unlikely to work. I seriously doubt that they can find buyers 
for their assets so soon,'' said Lee Ji-soon, an economics 
professor at Seoul National University. 
</P>
<P>
	For decades, South Korean conglomerates thrived on cozy  
relations with military governments. A single chaebol controls 40 
to 60 subsidiaries, making everything from computer chips to cars 
and ships. 
</P>
<P>
	One unofficial survey estimates that the five biggest chaebol  
control roughly 30 percent of all financial resources in South 
Korea. 
</P>
<P>
	About a dozen smaller chaebol collapsed in 1997, forcing South  
Korea to turn to the International Monetary Fund to bail out its 
economy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
