<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Mostly Higher / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures advanced Wednesday on  
the Chicago Board of Trade amid reports the Clinton administration 
plans to ease some sanctions against foreign buyers. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices rose after President Clinton moved to exempt food and  
medicine from future sanctions, a decision that could significantly 
boost export demand for beleaguered American farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new policy, commercial licenses to sell agricultural  
and medicinal products under existing U.S. sanctions -- against 
Cuba, Iran, Iraq, Libya, North Korea and Sudan -- will be reviewed 
on a case-by-case basis. 
</P>
<P>
	Futures prices also rose amid continued uncertainty about  
weather conditions in Midwest growing regions. The National Weather 
Service is calling for normal temperatures and above-normal 
rainfall over the next week, while some private forecasters say 
showers will only be scattered. 
</P>
<P>
	The answer will determine whether farmers will be able to  
proceed with fieldwork already delayed by heavy recent rains. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 3 1/2 cents to $2.63 1/2 a bushel; July  
corn fell 1/4 cent to $2.19 1/2 a bushel; July oats rose 1/4 cent to $1.20 
a bushel; July soybeans rose 2 cents to $4.89 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures were mixed, while pork bellies advanced on the  
Chicago Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle fell .10 cent to 63.57 cents a pound; May  
feeder cattle fell .22 cent to 71.65 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
rose 1.33 cents to 59.05 cents a pound; July pork bellies rose 2.7 
cnets to 59.55 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
