<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Aetna Stock Soars on Earnings Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Aetna Inc.'s stock jumped more than 12  
percent Wednesday after posting a better-than expected 15 percent 
jump in first quarter profits. 
</P>
<P>
	The health insurance giant cited its success curbing rising  
medical costs and increasing premiums as a big reason for its 
financial success. 
</P>
<P>
	Aetna's operating earnings in the first quarter were $168.2  
million, or $1.08 a share, compared to $146.6 million or 90 cents a 
share in the same period a year ago. Results beat Wall Street 
forecasts by 7 cents, according to First Call. 
</P>
<P>
	Earnings for Aetna U.S. Healthcare rose 33 percent, excluding  
Year 2000 costs, to $133.5 million compared to the prior-year 
period. The company said it has done particularly well at lowering 
prescription drug costs to below current industry trends. HMO drug 
costs have been rising at about 13 percent in the past year. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, shares of Aetna rose $10.12 1/2 to $92 in trading on  
the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Rising medical costs have hurt profits for most managed care  
firms in the past two years. 
</P>
<P>
	The amount Aetna pays of each premium dollar in medical costs, a  
key indicator of financial health, fell to 82 percent, compared to 
82.7 percent a year ago. In the Medicare market, the proportion 
fell to 90.1 percent from 92.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Total revenues for the nation's largest health insurer grew 23  
percent increase, from $5.7 billion to $4.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Total HMO membership increased by nearly 1.9 million members  
over the prior-year period, reflecting the addition of NYLCare, as 
well as business growth. Commercial HMO membership rose 5 percent 
from year end, as enrollment grew in every region of the country. 
</P>
<P>
	The company added 62,000 Medicare HMO members since year end,  
resulting in a net increase of 11,000 Medicare members after 
exiting selected markets. The company announced last fall it was 
exiting the Medicare HMOs in six states. 
</P>
<P>
	Aetna Retirement Services, which markets a wide array of  
retirement and investment products to nonprofit organizations, 
government entities, small businesses and individuals, reported a 
30 percent increase in operating earnings of $53 million, compared 
$40.8 million in the same period last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
