<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Noon EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Outspoken Yugoslav Official Is Ousted  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The Yugoslav deputy premier who  
urged his government to compromise with NATO was fired today, state 
media said. The ouster came just three days after Vuk Draskovic 
said the Serb leadership should recognize that ``we cannot defeat 
NATO'' and must respect the ``reality'' of facing a world united 
against it. A report by the Tanjug news agency said Draskovic was 
sacked because of his ``public statements which were contrary to 
the government stands.'' Draskovic was once the main opposition 
leader before joining Slobodan Milosevic's government three months 
ago. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovars Flee to Albania  
</P>
<P>
	MORINI, Albania (AP) -- More than 2,000 ethnic Albanian refugees  
fled into Albania today, telling of a new Serb campaign to clear 
villages in southwest Kosovo. In neighboring Macedonia, the U.N. 
refugee agency warned that camps packed beyond capacity were ``on 
the verge of rioting'' because of tensions. The refugees said Serb 
police had ordered them out of their villages. Albania has taken in 
more than 360,000 Kosovo refugees, and a further 142,000 are in 
Macedonia. Hundreds of thousands more are said to be displaced 
within Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Envoys Head to Moscow To Talk Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Diplomatic efforts to resolve the Kosovo conflict  
intensified today, with Russia's envoy announcing plans to go to 
Yugoslavia and Germany for talks tomorrow. Russia has been a vocal 
opponent of NATO airstrikes on Serb targets. Germany has also been 
in the forefront of Kosovo diplomacy, partly because anti-war 
sentiment is growing. Russia's talks with Yugoslavia reportedly are 
centering on what kind of international force could eventually move 
into Kosovo. NATO insists that any such force be a military one, 
which Belgrade rejects. 

</P>
<P>
	3 Teens Eyed in Colo. Shootings  
</P>
<P>
	GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) -- Police say they want to interview for a  
second time three teen-agers who said they were acquainted with the 
young men who carried out the deadly shooting at a Colorado high 
school. The Jefferson county sheriff says the three teens, who were 
detained and questioned last week during the attack, knew the names 
of the gunmen before that information had been announced. The three 
youths were wearing combat gear and clothing similar to what the 
shooters wore. Officials said the three were associated with the 
``Trenchcoat Mafia,'' as were gunmen Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold. 

</P>
<P>
	Casino, Lottery Moratorium Urged  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A sharply divided panel studying gambling in  
America today recommended a nationwide moratorium on the spread of 
casinos, lotteries and slot machines. The commission's report will 
contain a call for ``a pause'' in the spread of legalized gambling 
and encourage state and local governments to form their own 
gambling study commissions. The nine-member panel split over the 
language, particularly the use of the word ``moratorium.'' Five 
commissioners approved the wording, while four voted no. 

</P>
<P>
	Many Films Show Substance Abuses  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. drug officials released results today of  
a study that says people were depicted doing drugs, drinking or 
smoking in 98 percent of the top movie rentals and 27 percent of 
the most popular songs in 1996 and 1997. The study was commissioned 
by the Department of Health and Human Service, which wants to know 
if the depictions encourage America's youth to use and abuse 
alcohol, drugs and cigarettes. Drugs were associated with wealth or 
luxury in 20 percent of the songs. A spokesman for the Motion 
Picture Association of America declined comment. 

</P>
<P>
	Site Helps With Travel Complaints  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Dissatisfied airline passengers have a Web site  
that lets them complain directly to airlines and the U.S. 
Department of Transportation. The site, www.passengerrights.com, 
forwards the complaints to airline e-mail addresses not available 
to the general public and follows up on the complaints with faxes. 
Complaints can also be sent to cruise ship companies, car rental 
agencies, hotels, resorts and tour operators. Fewer than 6,000 
airline service complaints were made last year to the DOT, but the 
web site operator said the number is not representative because so 
few people know how to register a complaint. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 28  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before noon EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 28.63 to 10,860.34. Gainers on the New York Stock Exchange led 
losers 1,495-1,187. The Nasdaq was down 18.95 to 2,583.46. 

</P>
<P>
	49ers QB Arraigned on Rape Charge  
</P>
<P>
	CHRISTIANSBURG, Va. (AP) -- San Francisco 49ers backup  
quarterback Jim Druckenmiller was booked today on a charge that he 
raped a student at Virginia Tech during a return to his alma mater. 
Druckenmiller was released on a $10,000 bond. A trial is set for 
July 19. Druckenmiller plans to plead innocent, and his lawyer said 
the quarterback and his accuser had consensual sex. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
</P>
</TEXT>
