<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rebecca Pidgeon Builds U.S. Career </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Skim through Rebecca Pidgeon's press clippings  
and you'll find husband David Mamet's name in almost every story. 
That's understandable. For almost a decade, she has been cast in 
supporting roles in his plays and films. 
</P>
<P>
	Reading various interviews, it becomes clear that Pidgeon wants  
to establish herself in the United States as an actress, singer and 
songwriter -- not as Mrs. Mamet. The stories indicate a certain 
resistance -- even bristling -- at the mention of his name. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet it is only mildly surprising when Pidgeon refers to ``my  
husband'' when talking about her role in Mamet's new film, ``The 
Winslow Boy.'' After all, Pidgeon's name and face are more familiar 
to American audiences since her starring role in Mamet's 1998 film, 
``The Spanish Prisoner,'' opposite Steve Martin. 
</P>
<P>
	Pidgeon left a successful career in London after her marriage to  
Mamet in 1991. She disbanded her British band Ruby Blue for a solo 
career in America and began auditioning for acting roles. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked if it was ``very intense'' to work with her husband  
on ``The Winslow Boy,'' Pidgeon shook her head and smiled: ``Not 
really. Actually, it's fun and comfortable.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mamet wasn't the only relative on the set. Pidgeon's brother  
Matthew plays one of her brothers in the film. ``Working with my 
brother was great,'' she said. ``It was his first film.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Did working with his accomplished sister intimidate him?  
</P>
<P>
	``Oh gawd, no, no, no,'' replied Pidgeon. ``We had a laugh.''  
</P>
<P>
	``The Winslow Boy,'' set in 1910, was adapted by Mamet from  
Terence Rattigan's play. The film is based on the real-life story 
of a young naval cadet (Guy Edwards), who is accused of stealing a 
five-shilling postal order. Together with their father (Nigel 
Hawthorne), Pidgeon tries to persuade England's leading lawyer to 
take the case in her brother's defense. 
</P>
<P>
	With little hope for success, the family's comfort is sacrificed  
in pursuit of the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Pidgeon plays a suffragette, ``I did not do factual  
research because I wanted it to be sort of alive and in the moment, 
our own interpretation, and I think everybody came to it with that, 
nobody came to it with an academic perspective.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She described the film as a ``movie about personal interactions  
more than a historical document, and actually, you know, it came 
very easily to me. I had brilliant actors to work with. And it was 
a joy, it was just a joy. And we sat around and gabbed. I went to 
the same drama school as Gemma Jones, so we had a lot to talk about 
with that, and we became like a little family unit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Besides Hawthorne (``The Madness of King George,'' ``Amistad'')  
and Jones (``Sense and Sensibility''), the film stars Jeremy 
Northam (``Emma,'' ``Amistad'') as the lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	``My heart was beating slightly faster when I first met Nigel  
and Gemma because they are both rather heroes of mine,'' Pidgeon 
said. ``Nigel is one of the first members of the theater in 
Britain. He's a very, very respected actor, he's like royalty, in 
fact, he just got knighted, I think. And also Gemma, she's so 
beautiful and she's so great. So when you meet these idols, you 
tend to get a little bit weak-kneed at first.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pidgeon, 33, was born in Cambridge, Mass., where her British  
father was employed at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. 
When she was 5, her family moved to Edinburgh, Scotland. She was 
trained at the Royal Academy of Dramatic Art in London. 
</P>
<P>
	She and Mamet live in Cambridge and Vermont. On a brisk, spring  
day in New York, while on a media tour to promote ``The Winslow 
Boy,'' Pidgeon looked remarkably rested and composed for a woman 
who has a newborn son and a young daughter at home. 
</P>
<P>
	What would she like audiences to take away from the film?  
</P>
<P>
	``I want them to enjoy it. It's such a compelling story. And  
kind of a universal theme, I think, because it's about fighting for 
principles, and at what point do we decide that fighting for 
principles has become arrogant and do we just get on with our 
lives? 
</P>
<P>
	``It's also about a happy family with this outside, unforeseen,  
out-of-the-blue event that comes along, just like financial 
reversal or death. These things do crop up in our lives, our lives 
are not in our control, and so how does the family respond and what 
happens to them? It's such food for thought. It's complex.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her theater work includes Mamet's ``Oleanna'' with William H.  
Macy in New York. Earlier in her career, she appeared in Mamet's 
``Speed-the-Plow'' in London. 
</P>
<P>
	She also had supporting roles in Mamet's ``The Water Engine,'' a  
1992 television movie, and ``Homicide,'' a 1991 action thriller. 
</P>
<P>
	Does Pidgeon have a preference for stage or film?  
</P>
<P>
	``Not really, I find them so vastly different. The discipline is  
so different with each.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pidgeon will star in Mamet's new play, ``Boston Marriage,''  
scheduled to premiere at the American Repertory Theatre in 
Cambridge June 4-27. 
</P>
<P>
	``... Hopefully we'll take that to London,'' she said. ``I want  
to get back to my old stomping ground and get back into the theater 
there. It would be thrilling for me to do that, and it's such a 
wonderful play. I miss the theater, with that kind of culture 
there, which we don't have in America.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pidgeon paused. ``Although you know, some of the best stage  
actors I've ever worked with were in America actually, like William 
H. Macy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She added, ``We just did 'The Old Neighborhood' on Broadway with  
Peter Riegert and Patti LuPone. Patti LuPone, I think, is one of 
the great actresses of our time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Would she ever consider moving to Hollywood?  
</P>
<P>
	``No, I don't trust myself,'' she laughed. ``It's not that I  
think that I'm better or good in a specific way. I feel that I 
would become addicted in a way that could detract from the things 
that I find are really important to me. Hollywood life is 
all-consuming. It's breakfast, lunch, dinner and the party you go 
to that night. So I prefer to dip in and out of it. I find it 
exciting in bits and pieces.'' 
</P>
<P>
	How does her music work into the equation?  
</P>
<P>
	``Music is on hold at the moment. But it's trying to filter back  
in.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
