<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 49er Arraigned on Rape Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHRISTIANSBURG, Va. (AP) -- San Francisco 49ers backup  
quarterback Jim Druckenmiller was booked today on a charge that he 
raped a student at Virginia Tech during a return to his alma mater. 
</P>
<P>
	Druckenmiller, the Hokies' quarterback at the height of their  
football success, was released on a $10,000 bond after an 
arraignment in Montgomery County Circuit Court. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Ray Grubbs scheduled a jury trial for July 19. He told  
Druckenmiller he understood he planned to plead innocent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Is that your understanding?'' Grubbs asked the defendant.  
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, your honor,'' Druckenmiller replied.  
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-4, 240-pound quarterback had no comment as he and his  
attorney entered the courtroom, but when he left the county jail 
after being processed, he said, ``I am innocent and that's all I've 
got to say right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Druckenmiller is accused of raping the student on March 4  
between 3 a.m. and 4 a.m. at a house during a visit to Blacksburg. 
The woman testified before a grand jury on April 13 and the 
indictment was unsealed on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Druckenmiller has said he is certain he will be vindicated and  
confident he will be available to play this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	An attorney for Druckenmiller, David Neufeld, said last week  
that Druckenmiller had been aggressively pursued by his accuser. 
Neufeld said Druckenmiller and the woman had consensual sex and 
that Druckenmiller later took and passed a lie-detector test about 
the incident. 
</P>
<P>
	Druckenmiller, a strong-armed passer, was the 49ers' top pick  
and the 26th selection overall in the 1997 draft. Coach Steve 
Mariucci proclaimed him the team's quarterback of the future, but 
he has played little. 
</P>
<P>
	As a rookie, Druckenmiller played in four games, one as a  
starter, and completed 21 of 52 passes for 239 yards and one 
touchdown. But he also threw three interceptions, two inside the 
opponent's 20-yard line. 
</P>
<P>
	Last season, he lost the No. 1 backup quarterback job to Ty  
Detmer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
