<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Headlines $14M GOP Fund-Raiser </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The last Republican president is helping the  
GOP raise $14 million to try to win back the White House, and the 
beneficiary may be his son, Texas Gov. George W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Former President Bush was the big draw at the Republican  
National Committee's annual black-tie gala Wednesday night, which 
party officials said would set a fund-raising record. 
</P>
<P>
	The younger Bush is the front-runner for the GOP presidential  
nomination, and a financially flush Republican Party would be a 
boon to whomever is the nominee. 
</P>
<P>
	``I believe it is essential that we put a Republican in the  
White House,'' the former president told the crowd. ``We have good 
people who are running.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``An energized party is going to help Republicans all across the  
country,'' said Governor Bush's campaign spokeswoman, Mindy Tucker. 
</P>
<P>
	The governor did not attend the gathering because he was in  
Austin for the Texas legislative session. But Republican 
presidential hopefuls Lamar Alexander, Elizabeth Dole, Sen. Bob 
Smith of New Hampshire and Sen. John McCain of Arizona all 
attended. 
</P>
<P>
	They were among the 1,200 guests who dined on crab cakes and  
herb-crusted tenderloin of beef and heard Senate Majority Leader 
Trent Lott, R-Miss., say, ``I'm counting on you to win the 
victories that we need to win for our country in the next four 
years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Corporate tickets to the event were $2,000. Individuals and  
political action committees paid $1,500. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year's gala brought in $11 million. Republican National  
Committee Chairman Jim Nicholson attributed this year's expected 
larger payday to the GOP's hopes of recapturing the White House in 
2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a growing zeal to win back the White House,''  
Nicholson said in an interview. ``This party is really coming 
together with an ardent desire to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nicholson said some of the money the party is raising now may be  
used during the presidential campaign next year to air issue 
advertisements touting the Republican message. 
</P>
<P>
	``After the nominee becomes apparent, which will be in  
mid-March, we can assist our nominee in getting the message out to 
the American people,'' Nicholson said. ``Whoever is the nominee 
will be broke. I don't want our party broke. We can then start 
advertising the Republican message to the people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both the Republicans and Democrats aired millions of dollars in  
issue ads during the 1996 campaign on behalf of their presidential 
candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Election Commission auditors recommended last December  
that President Clinton repay $7 million and Republican nominee Bob 
Dole pay back $17.7 million in federal funds that went to their 
1996 presidential bids, saying both illegally benefited from the 
ads. But the commission threw out the recommendation. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's fund-raiser did not sit well with a watchdog  
organization. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a continuation of the trend of the trend of these mega  
fund-raisers,'' said Donald Simon of Common Cause, a group that 
favors changing the campaign finance laws. ``In one night, a party 
will raise millions of dollars, much of it in money that is 
supposed to be illegal under federal law.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Simon was referring to ``soft money,'' the unregulated donations  
from corporations, unions and individuals that do not fall under 
federal rules and aren't supposed to be spent directly on federal 
campaigns. The event also raises ``hard money'' contributions that 
fall within giving limits. 
</P>
<P>
	The income from the fund-raiser is in addition to $19.7 million  
the RNC raised through March 31, including $7.4 million in soft 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	Construction company executive Alexander G. Spanos gave the  
party $250,000 last month, while real estate developer Lawrence 
Kadish gave $150,000 and MCI WorldCom contributed $125,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee also received a  
$250,000 donation last month, from the Communication Workers of 
America, according to its FEC report. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic National Committee is not scheduled to report its  
fund-raising figures until July. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
