<HEADLINE> Eastman Chemical Acquires Inkmaker </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KINGSPORT, Tenn. (AP) -- Eastman Chemical Co. plans to acquire  
inkmaker Lawter International for $400 million in cash. 
</P>
<P>
	Eastman will also assume about $100 million in Lawter's debt.  
</P>
<P>
	Eastman spokesman Rod Irvin said the company wants Lawter to  
help it expand its specialty chemicals business, including 
coatings, inks and resins. Lawter will become a division or 
subsidiary of Eastman, and Lawter's name and employees should 
remain in place, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawter, based in Pleasant Prairie, Wis., employs about 600  
people and reported sales of $213 million in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Eastman, based in Kingsport, Tenn., employs about 16,000 people  
in more than 30 countries and had 1998 sales of $4.48 billion. 

</P>
</TEXT>
