<DOCNO> APW19990428.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 22:22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Raisin Drying Method Succeeds / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MADERA, Calif. (AP) -- Whether it's winter pruning or the fall  
harvest, the Simpson Vineyards acreage is strangely quiet. 
</P>
<P>
	Even at the busiest times of the year, raisin grower Lee S.  
Simpson III needs fewer than 10 people working on his 160-acre 
ranch. 
</P>
<P>
	But then, this is not a typical raisin farm.  
</P>
<P>
	Simpson, a former civil engineer from the San Francisco Bay  
area, is on the cutting edge in raisin-growing technology. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Simpson, 56, admits he's far from perfecting the  
method, his dried-on-the-vine raisins are reaping record yields per 
acre while cutting down costs, most notably on labor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I get about 30 percent return on capital investment. Most  
people are lucky to get 5 percent,'' Simpson said. ``I'm getting 
the kind of returns Microsoft and Intel get. You just don't find 
that in the raisin industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DOV raisins are nothing new. Farmers in the San Joaquin Valley  
have been experimenting for years to find ways to dry the fruit 
before harvesting it. However, in most vineyards, farmers still 
need to hire scores of workers during harvest to hand-pick the 
fruit and lay it on paper trays. 
</P>
<P>
	After a few days, laborers are needed again to turn over the  
grapes to help them shrivel up into raisins, which takes about 
three weeks. But a slight rain can damage the crop with mold, and 
dirt can be trapped inside the folds and wrinkles of each raisin. 
</P>
<P>
	Simpson has solved most of these problems with his DOV method.  
</P>
<P>
	His Fiesta grape vines stand more than 6 1/2 feet tall. Alongside  
the vines are metal stands, which anchor a system of wire trellises 
covering the entire field. 
</P>
<P>
	The canes from each vine are grown on top of the wire, creating  
a canopy of leaves and grapes that hang down. 
</P>
<P>
	When the fruit is ready for drying, workers simply cut the canes  
and leave the fruit hanging on the wires. It takes twice as long 
for DOV raisins to dry, but growers don't have to worry about rain 
since water will simply drip to the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	When the raisins are ready, Simpson uses a small crew with a  
pair of modified tractors that knock the raisins into bins. 
</P>
<P>
	Simpson estimates he has reduced his harvest cost from $220 per  
ton to about $28 per ton. 
</P>
<P>
	Although his methods have impressed growers all over the San  
Joaquin Valley, where most of the nation's raisins are grown, 
switching is not an option for most, some say. 
</P>
<P>
	``The average age of a raisin grower is in his early 60s. He's  
not going to tear out vineyards to put in an elaborate system,'' 
said Don Nielson, 62, third-generation raisin farmer in south 
Fresno County. 
</P>
<P>
	Sun-Maid, the largest raisin cooperative in the United States,  
has patented its own version of DOV called south-side drying. This 
method places poles along existing vines with two metal rods that 
point toward the sky on either side of the pole at a 45-degree 
angle. 
</P>
<P>
	Metal wires run connect the rods and the canes hang on top of  
them. 
</P>
<P>
	The south-side raisins also dry on the vine after the canes are  
cut, and the fruit is harvested by a machine. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
