<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 07:25:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Troubled Thai Bank Taken Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- Thailand's troubled, family-owned  
Nakornthon Bank announced Wednesday that Standard Chartered Bank 
PLC will take control of the institution. 
</P>
<P>
	Britain-based Standard Chartered beat out offers by Singapore's  
United Overseas Bank in negotiations for Nakornthon, the third Thai 
bank taken over by a foreign institution since the onset of Asia's 
economic crisis in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The terms announced by Nakornthon said that Standard Chartered  
will inject $172 million to take an initial 68.4 percent stake, 
after a write-down of existing equity from the current 27 cents to 
0.0027 cents. 
</P>
<P>
	Thai authorities will then inject $368 million in a swap of  
government bonds for preferred shares to cover negative equity. 
Funds from Standard Chartered will raise the initial 
recapitalization to a total of $194 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition is the second Standard Chartered has made of an  
Asian bank in the past week. Earlier it agreed to take a 20 percent 
stake in Bank Bali and assume management control of the Indonesian 
institution. 
</P>
<P>
	About half of Nakornthon Bank's loans were delinquent, a problem  
shared in much of the Thai financial system since the Asian crisis 
sent the economy into recession two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	ABN Amro of the Netherlands took control of Bank of Asia last  
year, and Singapore's DBS Bank took over 50 percent in Thai Danu 
Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest takeover lifts Nakornthon out of the hands of the  
powerful Wanglee family, which founded the small bank in the 1930s. 
The family has large finance and building industry interests, and 
one member is president of Thai Airways International. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
