<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two Lightly Raced Colts Make a Run </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- History is against Desert Hero or Valhol  
winning the Kentucky Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	Each goes into the grueling 1 1/4-mile race Saturday with just  
three career starts, all this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The last Derby winner not to have raced as a 2-year-old was  
Apollo in 1882. Valhol also would become only the eighth gelding 
and the first since Clyde Van Dusen in 1927 to win a Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do have the feeling that this horse is good enough to  
overcome the obstacles,'' said Richard Mandella, trainer of Desert 
Hero, winner of a maiden race and the San Rafael and third in the 
Santa Anita. 
</P>
<P>
	He was talking about Desert Hero's inexperience, the demanding  
distance of the race and a full field of 20 3-year-olds. 
</P>
<P>
	Valhol, who faces the same obstacles, also had to overcome a  
legal barrier just to get into the Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	Valhol won the Arkansas Derby on April 11 at Oaklawn Park for  
his first win. However, the purse distribution had been held up 
pending an investigation into whether winning jockey Billy Patin 
had an electrical device during the race. A hearing is scheduled 
for May 5. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, an Arkansas judge ruled the first-place money of  
$300,000 from the Arkansas Derby should be awarded to owner James 
Jackson. Without the money the gelding would not have been able to 
get into the Derby, limited to 20 starters based on money earned in 
graded stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	Willie Martinez will ride Valhol in the 125th edition of the  
Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	``Vindication is yet to come,'' Jackson said after the hearing.  
``The horse did no wrong, and we were being penalized.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think the horse will embarrass us,'' trainer Dallas  
Keen said Wednesday from Churchill Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	Valhol, who was gelded before he ever raced, didn't start as  
2-year-old because of shin problems. Desert Hero was supposed to 
make his debut last fall, but he couldn't because of a minor foot 
problem. 
</P>
<P>
	The son of 1993 Kentucky Derby winner Sea Hero won his first  
start Feb. 7 and followed with a neck victory over Prime Timber in 
the mile San Rafael on Feb. 28 at Santa Anita. Prime Timber is one 
of two colts with whom trainer Bob Baffert will try to win a third 
straight Derby. The other is Santa Anita Derby winner General 
Challenge. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert also entered the filly Excellent Meeting, but it was  
possible she could start Friday in the Kentucky Oaks for which she 
also was entered. Should she be scratched from the Derby, there 
would be only 19 starters because there is no also-eligible list. 
</P>
<P>
	After Desert Hero won the San Rafael, his owner, Prince Ahmed  
Salman of Saudi Arabia, took him from trainer Wally Dollase and 
gave him to Mandella. Philosophical differences were cited for the 
switch. 
</P>
<P>
	Desert Hero finished seven lengths behind General Challenge and  
3 3/4 lengths behind Prime Timber in the 1 1-8-mile Santa Anita Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was mediocre race by all standards,'' Mandella said. ``He  
didn't get much out of it. But it was only his third race, so he 
had a right to get mixed up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mandella said he would have liked to get another start for  
Desert Hero. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I had had the horse long and had been more confident of  
running him and not hurting him,'' said Mandella, who will be 
trying to win his first Derby in his fourth try. ``I didn't want to 
take the chance of using the horse too much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although Desert Hero is inexperienced, Mandella is encouraged.  
</P>
<P>
	``He is a good horse,'' he said. ``Good horses have a way of  
making things happen.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
