<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 14:55:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Publishers Urged To Move Faster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Newspapers need to invest much more in research  
and new ventures if they are to succeed in the world of the 
Internet, three Wall Street analysts told publishers Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Newspapers need to move faster,'' Lauren Rich Fine, a first  
vice president and managing director at Merrill Lynch in New York, 
told publishers at the newspaper Association of America annual 
conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Gruneich, a senior managing director at Bear Stearns in  
New York, told publishers to stop moving ``so cautiously'' and to 
aggressively reinvest their capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Other industries and markets are moving while interest rates are  
low and capital is plentiful, but newspapers have been oddly quiet, 
said Gruneich said. ``It seems like this is the year of the pin 
drop in the newspaper industry,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Newspapers should reinvest much more than the 2 percent of  
excess capital they historically put into research and development, 
Gruneich said. They also should invest in newspaper-Internet 
cross-promotions, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fine recommended big pushes for circulation, and to get readers  
to value and pay more for local content. 
</P>
<P>
	Newspapers' assets include penetration of their local markets,  
unique content, editing talent and local databases of subscribers, 
the analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Penetration is going to be the most important thing you have  
to sell off of,'' as media becomes more fragmented, said William 
Drewry, a vice president at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette in 
Atlanta. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, Wall Street hasn't rewarded newspapers with higher  
valuation for investing in Internet ventures, the analysts said. 
</P>
<P>
	Drewry and Fine suggested newspapers with strong online brands,  
such as The New York Times and The Wall Street Journal, spin off 
and sell stakes in their Internet businesses to capture some of the 
``funny money'' investors are betting on Internet ventures. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wall Street is willing to underwrite those efforts,'' Fine  
said. ``You should go for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The analysts' other observations included:  
</P>
<P>
	--If Congress lifts restrictions on cross-ownership of newspaper  
and broadcast media, Wall Street will become a ``raging bull'' 
toward newspaper stocks. TV and newspapers would consolidate to own 
local markets and save costs by pooling 24-hour reporting 
capabilities. 
</P>
<P>
	--New media threaten to hire away newspaper editorial talent, one  
of the industry's major assets, said Fine, who also advocated 
consolidating with TV stations in order to gain their talent pool. 
``One of the greatest values you all have today is your 
journalists, and I would hang onto them,'' Fine said. 
</P>
<P>
	--Newspapers differ from Intel and other volatile, high-tech  
companies because newspapers have proprietary content that is 
expensive to produce. ``Work hard to protect that,'' Drewry said. 
</P>
<P>
	--Newsprint prices are likely to stay flat for some time, the  
analysts said, because the lag in Asia's recovery has depressed 
demand there, and conversions to narrower, 50-inch webs on printing 
presses will reduce demand in the United States. But publishers 
shouldn't hope for prices to stay too low, too long, because that 
would prompt producers to cut capacity and costs would rise over 
the long run, Drewry said. 
</P>
<P>
	--Analysts expect to see continued mergers among newspaper  
companies as long as the market continues to favor stocks of larger 
companies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 15:15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tricon Posts Big Rise in Earnings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Tricon Global Restaurants Inc.'s earnings  
nearly doubled in the first quarter led by a sales surge at Pizza 
Hut restaurants where a New York-style pizza was being introduced. 
</P>
<P>
	The fast-food restaurant company earned $106 million, or 66  
cents a share, in the three months ended March 20 compared to $54 
million, or 35 cents a share, a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenue fell 6 percent to $1.8 billion from $1.9 billion a year  
earlier, due mainly to store closings and the sale of company-owned 
stores to franchisees. 
</P>
<P>
	But systemwide sales including sales at restaurants owned by the  
company and by franchisees rose 5 percent to $4.81 billion from 
$4.56 billion a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales at Pizza Hut restaurants open at least a year rose 14  
percent as the chain introduced The Big New Yorker pizza. Sales at 
Taco Bell and KFC restaurants open at least a year rose 4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrall Pearson, Tricon's chairman and chief executive, said new  
pizza was ``the most successful new product launch'' in Pizza Hut's 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest earnings included 12 cents a share from the sale of  
restaurants to franchisees. Excluding that, operating earnings per 
share was 54 cents, a penny higher than the 53 cents a share 
expected by analysts surveyed by First Call. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Barish, restaurant analyst for BancBoston Robertson  
Stephens, said all three restaurant brands ``are showing 
improvements and it's looking like that will continue into the 
second quarter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a combination of good operations, good promotions and  
new product offerings. When you get all three of those aligned, it 
tends to have good results,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	KFC's higher same-store sales were driven in part by demand for  
Honey Bar-B-Que Wings, Extra Crispy chicken and the promotion of 
Popcorn Chicken during the NCAA basketball tournament, the company 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Taco Bell's sales growth stemmed in part from the promotion of  
its popular talking Chihuahua plush toy and expansion of its 
Gorditas line. 
</P>
<P>
	Tricon's also reported robust sales abroad.  
</P>
<P>
	Pearson predicted continued strong performance in the second  
quarter as the company unveils promotions tied to the new Star Wars 
movie. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, Tricon shares closed down $3.12 1/2 at $66 in trading  
on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Tony Howard, restaurant analyst at Hilliard Lyons, said the drop  
in Tricon's stock was due in part to a perception that the 
company's net earnings may not be as robust in coming months. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of hard to duplicate 100 percent growth,'' he said.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
