<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded  
heavily Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange, Nasdaq Stock 
Market, and American Stock Exchange. 

</P>
<P>
                             	 *NYSE    	

</P>
<P>
	DuPont Co. rose 4 3/8 to 73 1/2.  
</P>
<P>
	The Wilmington, Del.-based scientific products company's board  
approved a plan to spin off its energy unit Conoco, a day after 
DuPont reported a slight decline in earnings. 

</P>
<P>
	Unum rose 6 3/16 to 53 3/4.  
</P>
<P>
	The Portland, Maine, insurance holding company said it plans to  
exit from the reinsurance business after taking a $101.1 million 
pretax charge in the first quarter. 

</P>
<P>
	Steris Corp. fell 7 3/4 to 16 1/8.  
</P>
<P>
	Although earnings rose for the Mentor, Ohio-based medical  
equipment company, BT Alex. Brown downgraded its rating on the 
stock. 

</P>
<P>
	Lawter International rose 3 1/16 to 12.  
</P>
<P>
	Chemical and plastics maker Eastman Chemical, of Kingsport,  
Tenn., announced it will buy Pleasant Prairie, Wisc.-based Lawter 
International, which makes ink-related products. The deal is valued 
at $500 million. 

</P>
<P>
 *Republic Services Inc. rose 2 1/8 to 19.    	
</P>
<P>
	An offering of 100 million common shares was priced at $16.88  
each through underwriters led by Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. 

</P>
<P>
                              *NASDAQ   	

</P>
<P>
	Scios Inc. fell 5 7/8 to 3 13/16.  
</P>
<P>
	The Mountain View, Calif.-based company reported an earnings  
loss, a day after the Food and Drug Administration refused to 
approve the company's new drug application for Natrecor. 

</P>
<P>
	Walbro Corp. rose 7 1/4 to 19 9/16.  
</P>
<P>
	The Auburn Hills, Mich.-based engine fuels company has agreed to  
become a subsidiary of TI Group PLC, a London engineering 
conglomerate. 

</P>
<P>
	Razorfish Inc. rose 12 7/8 to 46 3/8.  
</P>
<P>
	The Web-site-design shop continued to rise after more than  
doubling Tuesday, its first day of trading. The company's new 
shares were priced at $16. 

</P>
<P>
 *Medi-Ject Corp. rose 5 1/16 to 6 3/8.    	
</P>
<P>
	The FDA approved the marketing of Medi-Ject's ``Choice'' brand  
insulin injector as an over-the-counter product. 

</P>
