<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> India Premier Assails Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- India's acting prime minister began his  
campaign for re-election Wednesday by assailing opposition groups 
for toppling his government and harming the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hindu nationalist-led government lost a confidence vote in  
parliament April 17, setting off nine days of political turbulence 
before President K.R. Narayanan called elections -- the third in as 
many years. 
</P>
<P>
	Atal Bihari Vajpayee, who is serving as a caretaker prime  
minister until a new government is formed, went on nationwide 
television Wednesday to accuse his opposition of plunging the 
nation into a major economic crisis. A stock market drop during the 
political turmoil cost investors $11.7 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Vajpayee's criticism came a day after the main opposition  
Congress Party said its leader, the Italian-born Sonia Gandhi, will 
run for parliament, her first bid for public office. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gandhi has not said whether she will seek the seat once  
held by her assassinated husband, Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi. 
</P>
<P>
	After the confidence vote, the Congress -- the second largest  
group in Parliament -- failed to win enough support from smaller 
parties to replace Vajpayee. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Vajpayee pledged to continue the economic reforms  
that were ``rudely halted'' when his Bharatiya Janata Party lost 
the confidence vote by one ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	``The worst victim of this power game has been the economy and  
India's image abroad,'' he told businessmen at the Confederation of 
Indian Industry. ``The loss suffered by the country is both 
measurable and intangible. Perhaps the costliest loss is the loss 
of time, since time is the most precious of all resources.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Elections must be held by October, but the date has not been  
set. Vajpayee was pushing for a vote as early as June, while 
Congress wants to delay the vote until September, giving itself 
more time to prepare. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gandhi's decision to run for parliament has already shifted  
the campaign focus to her ancestry. The BJP has noted that Mrs. 
Gandhi retained her Italian citizenship for 16 years after she was 
married. 
</P>
<P>
	Referring to the requirement in most countries that the head of  
state be a natural-born citizen, the BJP has asked voters if any 
Indian could become prime minister of Italy. 
</P>
<P>
	The BJP has said that if Mrs. Gandhi becomes prime minister,  
India will be under ``Rome Raj,'' a term used to refer to the rule 
by British colonialists. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Gandhi is likely to counter the BJP's attack by emphasizing  
her ties to the family that provided three generations of prime 
ministers -- Jawaharlal Nehru, his daughter Indira Gandhi and her 
son Rajiv. 
</P>
<P>
	The Congress said it will focus its campaign on the instability  
of the coalition governments that followed the decline of the 
once-monolithic Congress party that governed India for 45 of its 52 
years as an independent nation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
