<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 15:15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Minnesota Coaches' Trip Probed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL (AP) -- A questionable ``business'' trip to Las Vegas by  
Minnesota men's basketball coaches in 1997 was more than a one-time 
visit, a school auditor said. 
</P>
<P>
	The trip ``takes place every year'' and was ``taken with the  
knowledge and approval of senior management,'' said Gail L. Klatt, 
associate vice-president in the university's department of audits. 
</P>
<P>
	The $9,100 trip to Las Vegas by coach Clem Haskins and three  
other coaches, as well as a trainer and all of the men's wives, was 
little more than a golf outing, auditors said in documents released 
Tuesday to the Saint Paul Pioneer Press and Star Tribune of 
Minneapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	A booster group paid for the 1997 trip, and coaches stood to  
avoid income taxes on the gift by declaring the travel 
business-related, Klatt said. 
</P>
<P>
	Neal Johnson, current president of the Golden Dunkers booster  
group, said his group paid for the annual trips to Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the group's federal income tax form that covered  
the 1997 trip in question, the Golden Dunkers spent $9,144 for 
``coaches' meetings.'' In each of the previous two years, the group 
reported spending similar amounts on the trips. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past, the trips have traditionally been approved by  
McKinley Boston, vice president for student development and 
athletics, and then-university President Nils Hasselmo, according 
to the audit review. 
</P>
<P>
	When internal auditors raised questions regarding the 1997 trip,  
the coaches instructed university bookkeepers to change payroll 
records to add the value of the trip to their incomes, Klatt said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1997 trip included $1,732 for airfare, $562 to play golf,  
$296 for golf clothing and an unspecified amount for meals, Klatt 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The coaches could be taxed for the benefit, or the university  
could seek reimbursement because such expenditures for travel by 
wives aren't allowed under university policy, the review says. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation was triggered by allegations from former  
office manager Jan Gangelhoff that she wrote or helped write more 
than 400 papers for men's basketball players. 
</P>
<P>
	Other findings from recent audits made public Tuesday reveal  
that auditors found that men's athletic department officials kept 
no record of checks written on a bank account and didn't balance 
the bank statement for three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Audits also showed that basketball and hockey coaches and  
players routinely received $10 more than the $34 maximum daily meal 
allowance for all university travel and that, despite rules 
forbidding the practice, coaches mentioned their university 
affiliation on at least four occasions in promotional brochures 
touting private camps. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1997 trip to Las Vegas was ostensibly for a coaches'  
seminar, but a university auditor found no evidence that any such 
event took place, according to memos written earlier this year to 
top university officials, including President Mark Yudof. 
</P>
<P>
	Klatt said the coaches later told an auditor the trip was a  
postseason ``debriefing'' but presented no documentation to support 
the claim. Auditors concluded it wasn't a legitimate business 
expense under university rules. 
</P>
<P>
	The four coaches are not identified in Klatt's memo, but she  
identified one as Haskins. 
</P>
<P>
	Haskins' lawyer, Ron Zamanksy, had no comment on the trip or the  
audit findings. Yudof's office referred all questions to his chief 
of staff, Tonya Moten Brown, who said the university president is 
aware of the problem and plans to address it in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	University policy forbids expenditures for trips that don't have  
a direct university business purpose. Even though the money was 
donated by boosters, those who received the gifts should have 
followed general university guidelines regarding nonbusiness 
travel, Brown said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 05:41:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sony Reports Drop in Net Income </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Buffeted by recession at home and abroad, Sony  
Corp. said today that its net income plunged nearly 20 percent in 
the last fiscal year and forecast an even steeper drop this year. 
</P>
<P>
	The Japanese electronics giant said consolidated net income for  
the year ending March 31 was $1.5 billion, down 19.4 percent from 
$1.9 billion the previous year. 
</P>
<P>
	The company painted an even grimmer picture for the current  
year, forecasting that consolidated net income will plunge 39 
percent to $922.8 million by March 31, 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	For the year just ended, sales and operating revenue gained 0.6  
percent, from $56.7 billion in the fiscal year ending in 1998 to 
$57 billion in the year just ended. 
</P>
<P>
	In its statement, Sony blamed its slumping income on the  
sluggish economies of Asia, Russia, Eastern Europe and Latin 
America. 
</P>
<P>
	The drop in income came mostly in the second half of the year,  
when the yen rapidly appreciated against the U.S. dollar, Sony 
said. A stronger yen makes Japanese exports more expensive 
overseas. 
</P>
<P>
	``Recent volatility of the yen exchange rate has made it more  
difficult to manage global procurement of materials, manufacturing 
and sales activities as planned,'' Sony said. 
</P>
<P>
	The fourth quarter was particularly bad for Sony, with cuts in  
sales in the company's electronics, music and video game 
businesses. Profit margins suffered from slashed production. 
</P>
<P>
	By segment, electronics sales slipped 0.5 percent; games sales  
were up 8.5 percent; music sales soared 9.4 percent; and sales in 
the motion pictures and television shows section plummeted 16 
percent. The strengthening yen, however, increased production 
costs. 
</P>
<P>
	For this year, Sony said economic problems will make recovery in  
sales in Latin America, Russia and Eastern Europe unlikely. The 
game business is also expected to decline. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also forecast a 4 percent drop in consolidated sales  
and operating revenue to $54.4 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The sour announcement follows a report from Sony Music  
Entertainment Inc. on Tuesday that it posted its first parent 
operating loss since 1969 in the fiscal year ended in March. 
</P>
<P>
	The company, a subsidiary of Sony Corp. set up in 1968, blamed  
the $2.9 million loss on a decline in revenues, higher costs of 
sales and a large increase in promotion expenses. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 12:51:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Yugoslav Deputy Leader Is Fired </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The Yugoslav prime minister today  
dismissed a deputy premier who urged his government to compromise 
with NATO, state media said. 
</P>
<P>
	The ouster came just three days after Deputy Premier Vuk  
Draskovic said the Serb leadership should recognize that ``we 
cannot defeat NATO'' and must respect the ``reality'' of facing a 
world united against it. 
</P>
<P>
	A terse report by the Tanjug news agency said Prime Minister  
Momir Bulatovic sacked Draskovic because of his ``public statements 
which were contrary to the government stands and jeopardizing the 
respect of the federal government.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The firing also was reported on Serbian television.  
</P>
<P>
	A 52-year-old maverick politician, Draskovic has had a long  
history of openly clashing with Yugoslavia's ruling powers. 
</P>
<P>
	Together with other leading pro-democracy activists, Draskovic  
founded a coalition called ``Zajedno,'' meaning ``Together,'' which 
won local elections in many cities in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	That led to more than three months of pro-democracy street  
protests that posed the most serious alternative to Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic's authoritarian rule since he came to 
power a decade ago. 
</P>
<P>
	After the breakup of Zajedno, Draskovic gradually moved closer  
to Milosevic, supporting the Yugoslav president during the Kosovo 
crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	He joined Milosevic's government as a deputy premier in January.  
His comments Sunday and Monday were his first public criticism of 
official policies. 
</P>
<P>
	Draskovic had threatened to launch street protests if Studio B,  
the radio and television controlled by his Serbian Renewal 
Movement, was taken over by the government. 
</P>
<P>
	His comments had prompted Western leaders to talk openly of  
serious cracks in the Milosevic regime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 15:35:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Singers Rock Around Tree Top </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STAFFORD, Calif. (AP) -- Joan Baez and Bonnie Raitt were hoisted  
up a 180-foot redwood to honor an environmental activist who has 
lived atop the tree for more than a year. 
</P>
<P>
	The two singers climbed a steep, two-mile mountain on April 22 --  
Earth Day -- and reached Julia ``Butterfly'' Hill's plywood perch 
with the help of a pulley system. 
</P>
<P>
	The singers serenaded Ms. Hill, and she responded by reading a  
poem she wrote about snow. They chatted for about 30 minutes as a 
filmmaker preserved the meeting on video. 
</P>
<P>
	``To experience Julia's commitment and love for these forests in  
person was a life-changing event,'' Ms. Raitt said. ``She was 
literally shining.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Baez added, ``Visiting Julia Butterfly was one of the most  
remarkable experiences of my life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Hill has lived atop the ancient tree for nearly 1 1/2 years  
without touching the ground to protest logging of ancient redwood 
trees 250 miles north of San Francisco. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 12:51:02 </DATE_TIME>
