<DOCNO> APW19990428.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 06:06:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> House Passes Satellite TV Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Satellite TV customers nationwide would be  
able, for the first time, to watch their favorite local broadcast 
TV shows via their satellite systems under a bill the House passed 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill, approved on 422-1 vote, is meant to resolve a dispute  
between satellite companies and broadcasters over conditions under 
which viewers who get their television from satellite can watch 
broadcast TV. 
</P>
<P>
	The measure would let DirecTV, EchoStar and other companies beam  
local broadcast signals to customers who use either pizza-sized 
dishes or big ``backyard'' dishes no matter where they live. Under 
existing law, companies can't do this. 
</P>
<P>
	With the change, satellite TV customers wouldn't be forced to  
use rooftop antennas or subscribe to cable TV to receive local 
broadcast signals. They would be able to get them directly from a 
satellite company, probably for a small monthly fee. Eventually, 
the companies would have to carry all local broadcast stations in a 
given market. 
</P>
<P>
	Only one satellite TV company, EchoStar, currently provides,  
under what it says are very limited conditions, some local 
broadcast stations in a few markets for a small fee. The company 
believes it can do this under existing law, but broadcasters 
disagree. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill aims to make satellite companies stronger competitors  
to cable TV providers, which carry local TV signals. That should 
serve as a check on cable rates, which were recently deregulated. 
</P>
<P>
	``The lack of local broadcasting programming is the No. 1 reason  
why consumers aren't willing to subscribe to satellite service and 
therefore are limited to a single competitor: the cable operator,'' 
said Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., who wrote the bill along with Rep. 
Howard Coble, R-N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill still must go through several steps to become law. The  
Senate has not yet voted on its version. Assuming the Senate bill 
passes, the two bills would have to be reconciled, and the 
resulting bill would need to be approved by both chambers and 
signed into law by President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	The House bill also would direct the Federal Communications  
Commission to come up with a better way of determining which 
satellite TV customers are eligible to receive broadcast network 
programs from ``distant'' network affiliates, Tauzin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Existing law lets satellite companies provide customers with  
``distant'' network signals, those from other broadcast areas, only 
if those customers cannot receive local stations using rooftop 
antennas. The current law doesn't take into account quality of 
local reception. 
</P>
<P>
	The satellite and broadcasting industries have been at odds for  
years over how to interpret the arcane legal test that determines 
when a satellite customer can't get a local signal and thus is 
eligible to receive network programs by satellite. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill tries not to disturb major parts of an agreement  
between DirecTV, the nation's largest satellite TV company, some 
small backyard dish providers and the four major broadcast 
networks, Tauzin said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under that agreement, satellite customers who aren't eligible to  
receive distant network signals and who live closest to their local 
TV stations would be cut off from ABC, CBS, Fox and NBC programs on 
June 30. But the bill does require DirecTV and others to provide 
ineligible customers who have been cut off with free antennas. 
</P>
<P>
	Also under the deal, ineligible customers who live on the  
fringes of their local stations' coverage areas would be cut off 
from network signals on Dec. 31. Under the bill, those customers 
would continue to receive network signals until the FCC develops a 
new way of determining eligibility, taking into account local 
reception quality. 
</P>
<P>
	Two major satellite players, EchoStar and PrimeTime 24, are not  
part of the agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	The only dissenter from the passing vote was Rep. Robert Brady,  
D-Pa. He voted against the bill at the request of a labor union, 
said Brady's chief of staff, Stanley White. 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 1554.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0103 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 12:46:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Derby a Big Time for Valhol Trainer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Outside Barn 42, Dallas Keen was handed a  
small box wrapped in silver paper. 
</P>
<P>
	Inside the box was a silver julep cup -- a memento for each of  
the Kentucky Derby trainers. 
</P>
<P>
	Keen officially became a Derby trainer Tuesday when a judge in  
Little Rock, Ark., ruled Valhol was entitled to the $300,000 
winner's share of the Arkansas Derby purse. 
</P>
<P>
	The julep cups were handed out at a trainer's dinner Tuesday  
night and Keen was on his way back to Louisville at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	The Arkansas Racing Commission ordered Oaklawn Park to hold up  
the purse after track officials said they had evidence jockey Billy 
Patin might have carried an electrical device when he won the April 
10 race aboard Valhol. 
</P>
<P>
	``The horse did nothing wrong,'' Keen said Wednesday.  
``Regardless of whether he used an electrical device or not, it's 
not going to make a horse run faster than what he is capable of 
doing. If anything, I think it's going to hurt one more than help 
one.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Leading to the Arkansas Derby, Valhol was second in a maiden  
race on Feb. 12 and fourth, beaten 2 1/2 lengths after traffic 
problems, in the Louisiana Derby on March 14. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute had kept Keen from enjoying his first Derby horse.  
</P>
<P>
	``It hasn't been fun,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	But now he can relax, somewhat.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a lot of relief for Valhol and my owner,'' he said.  
``It's been a tough go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	James Jackson, who paid $30,000 for Valhol as a 2-year-old, was  
exuberant moments after the Arkansas Derby, knowing the Kentucky 
Derby awaited. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's breathtaking,'' he said. ``It's the dream of every  
horsemen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Jackson was ecstatic about the verdict, but  
``vindication is yet to come.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the shadow cast by the investigation affected his family  
and Jackson's. Now they can concentrate on the race itself. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think the horse will embarrass us,'' Keen said. ``I  
think he's a champion. He's had a very short racing career but 
everything he's done has been so professional. He's the kind of 
horse you dream about being able to train. He doesn't make any 
mistakes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If more than 20 horses are entered in the Kentucky Derby, the  
field is limited to the top 20 in money earned in graded stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	Oaklawn general manager Eric Jackson emphasized the court ruling  
had nothing to do with the status of Patin. A hearing in the case 
is May 5. Keen said he has not talked with Patin since the 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	Willie Martinez, who was aboard Valhol for a half-mile workout  
Tuesday, will ride on Saturday. Churchill Downs probably would have 
tried to stop Patin from riding Valhol as long as the investigation 
was pending. 
</P>
<P>
	Keen said Martinez told him he had watched films of the  
gelding's races and was excited about getting the mount. 
</P>
<P>
	The Arkansas Derby check gives Valhol $338,400, good enough for  
11th on the list after the filly Excellent Meeting was entered in 
the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hopefully, after Saturday, it will have all been worth it,''  
Keen said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 12:46:03 </DATE_TIME>
