<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 'Vitamin O' Seller Must Stop Claims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) -- Companies selling a ``Vitamin O'' dietary  
supplement have been ordered to stop making unproven claims about 
purported health benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Edward Shea granted the Federal Trade  
Commission's request for a preliminary injunction that restricts 
ways two northeast Washington companies can advertise the product. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC filed a complaint March 11 after Rose Creek Health  
Products Inc. and The Staff of Life Inc. ran full- and half-page 
Vitamin O ads in USA Today and other newspapers. Both companies are 
based in Kettle Falls, about 75 miles north of here. 
</P>
<P>
	The order, entered Monday, will stay in effect until the matter  
is resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's very likely this case will never go to trial,'' said  
Eleanor Durham, an FTC staff attorney in Seattle. ``But I don't 
expect a final settlement before the end of the summer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A settlement likely won't occur until completion of studies the  
two companies hope will back up some of the health claims, Durham 
said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Calls were not immediately returned by Donald L. Smyth, who owns  
both businesses, or the operations' Spokane attorney, Lucinda 
Schilling Whaley. The companies, which market several dietary 
supplements, also do business as R-Garden Internationale. 
</P>
<P>
	The case involving Vitamin O -- the ``O'' stands for oxygen -- is  
one of several pending FTC complaints against producers of dietary 
supplements that claim to cure various ailments. Such products are 
frequently advertised in alternative-medicine publications and can 
be sold without approval from the Food and Drug Administration. 
</P>
<P>
	Rose Creek and The Staff of Life are among nearly a dozen  
companies nationwide that promote ``stabilized oxygen'' products 
purported to have health benefits. The FTC plans to scrutinize 
those companies as well, Durham said. 
</P>
<P>
	The FTC ultimately seeks a permanent order requiring Rose Creek  
and The Staff of Life to pay court costs and refund consumers' 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's temporary order requires the two companies to stop  
making unsubstantiated claims that ingesting the liquid or spraying 
it on the skin can cure or prevent ailments, Durham said. In 
addition, personal testimonials must include disclaimers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 23:12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teen Pregnancy Rate Keeps Falling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Talking about sex isn't easy for Laverne  
Coates, and she would rather assume that her daughter isn't having 
it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to hear about it,'' she said. ``I don't want to  
know about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She's made it clear, though, that pregnancy is not acceptable,  
and somehow, her daughter Tamara got the message. Tamara has been 
having sex for two years, she says, but she always uses 
contraception. 
</P>
<P>
	``To me, having a child in high school is not fun,'' Tamara  
Hayman, 18, of Baltimore said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Evidently, a lot of teens are getting the message: Teen  
pregnancy plummeted 17 percent in the 1990s to the lowest level 
since 1973, according to statistics being released today. Teen 
abortion rates were down, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have made real progress -- and must do more -- to encourage  
more young people to delay parenthood,'' said Vice President Al 
Gore, who plans a roundtable discussion with teen-agers at the 
White House today. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers point to a mix of reasons, including more reliable  
contraception, fear of AIDS, a new focus on abstinence and even the 
strong economy. 
</P>
<P>
	And there's fresh evidence that the peer pressure so many  
parents worry about actually does more good than harm. 
</P>
<P>
	Two new reports document the decline. New statistics from the  
Department of Health and Human Services show that births to 
teen-agers fell 4 percent in 1997, helping to push the national 
birth rate for all women to a record low. 
</P>
<P>
	And a report from the Alan Guttmacher Institute finds teen  
pregnancy dropped 4 percent in 1996 and fell 17 percent from its 
peak in 1990. The Guttmacher statistics combine the birth data with 
statistics on abortion and estimates for miscarriages. 
</P>
<P>
	The HHS report, which looks at a host of birth data, also found  
a new record low for births to unmarried black women and a 
continued decline in out-of-wedlock births in 1997. The year saw a 
record high for women getting early prenatal care and a record low 
rate of women smoking during pregnancy, down to 13.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Nationwide, there were about 880,000 teen pregnancies in 1996 --  
just under one for every 10 teen women. Sixty-two percent of them 
were 18- and 19-year-olds; the rest were 15 to 17 years old. The 
report did not look at teens under 15. 
</P>
<P>
	About one in three pregnancies were aborted, as the teen  
abortion rate dropped 3 percent in 1996. It fell 31 percent from 
1986. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the decline in pregnancy is due to increased use of  
birth control, said Jacqueline E. Darroch, a vice president at 
Guttmacher, a private research group. She noted that 11 percent of 
15- to 19-year-olds now use long-acting, highly effective birth 
control methods such as Depo-Provera shots. 
</P>
<P>
	Condom use also increased as fear of AIDS spread in the '90s.  
And national surveys point to decreased teen sexual activity as 
well. 
</P>
<P>
	Other explanations are harder to pin down, including an  
explosion of abstinence and pregnancy prevention programs and a 
strong economy that may be giving teens more hope for the future. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, for the first time, research suggests positive peer  
pressure may be stronger than the negative pressures parents 
usually fear. 
</P>
<P>
	Hanging out with friends who do well in school and don't drink  
or smoke will help a teen avoid pregnancy, researchers found. But, 
contrary to many parents' fears, hanging out with kids who engage 
in these and other risky behaviors doesn't make much difference, 
said Brad Brown of the University of Wisconsin, who analyzed a 
federal survey of teens for the National Campaign to Prevent Teen 
Pregnancy. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, some at the campaign are concerned that people believe  
the teen pregnancy problem has been solved. They note that U.S. 
rates are still higher than those of other industrialized nations. 
</P>
<P>
	Tamara Kreinin, who travels the country for the campaign,  
worries that condom use will decline as fear of AIDS recedes. 
``What I'm hearing from kids is you don't die from AIDS any more,'' 
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	But HHS Secretary Donna Shalala was more optimistic.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think people are that naive about American  
teen-agers,'' she said. ``We need to keep the same focus and 
philosophy and send consistent messages to every generation.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 05:35:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Border Patrol Falls Short of Agents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The head of the Border Patrol acknowledged  
Tuesday his agency will fall well short of its goal of adding 1,000 
agents this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Appearing before the Senate Judiciary immigration subcommittee,  
Border Patrol Chief Gus de la Vina said his agency will hire only 
200 to 400 of the 1,000 agents that Congress mandated this year. 
The bulk of them will be dispatched to current hot spots for 
illegal crossings: Arizona's Tucson sector and Texas' McAllen 
sector. 
</P>
<P>
	Blaming the Border Patrol's recruiting difficulties on a tight  
labor market, de la Vina voiced support for a plan to raise the 
entry-level pay scale for Border Patrol agents. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the pay increase ``would help us tremendously'' in  
recruiting and retaining agents. The Border Patrol has slightly 
more than 8,000 agents and loses 10 percent of its workforce 
annually, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., said he and Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison,  
R-Texas, will introduce a bill this week to increase agents' pay by 
about $8,000 annually. 
</P>
<P>
	Agents with a year's experience are paid roughly $33,000 in  
salary and earn on average 10 to 15 percent more in hazardous duty 
and overtime pay, according to Border Patrol statistics. The Kyl 
measure would increase that base pay to $41,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Kyl criticized the Immigration and Naturalization Service, the  
Border Patrol's parent agency, for not working with him on helping 
write the pay raise bill. ``We've been trying to help and we get 
stiffed by the INS,'' he complained. 
</P>
<P>
	An INS task force is studying pay issues, hoping to present a  
broader proposal later this year that would address compensation 
issues among its entire workforce of 29,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	An INS enforcement strategy aimed at push illegal border  
crossers away from population centers such as San Diego and El Paso 
and toward more rugged terrain has prompted a huge surge in 
crossings and apprehensions in Arizona. 
</P>
<P>
	The Border Patrol's Tucson sector, which covers most of the  
Arizona-Mexico border, recorded 60,000 apprehensions last month, 
Kyl said. He hypothesized that that two or three times that number 
were not apprehended. 
</P>
<P>
	Frustrated Arizonans living along the border have begun taking  
matters into their own hands. One rancher found 27 immigrants on 
his property on Easter Sunday, turning them over to the 
overburdened local Border Patrol office. Some are urging the 
governor to dispatch the Arizona National Guard to the border. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona state Rep. Gail Griffin, whose district reaches to the  
border, blamed the illegal aliens for a wave of break-ins, vehicle 
thefts, vandalism and destruction of livestock along the border. 
</P>
<P>
	De la Vina defended the enforcement strategy and noted the huge  
manpower increases within the Border Patrol in recent years. The 
Tucson sector has grown from fewer than 300 agents in 1994 to 1,050 
now. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know what we need to do in Douglas, Arizona. We're getting  
there as fast as we can,'' he said, referring to Arizona's current 
hot spot. ``Unfortunately, it does take some time.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 16:09:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Peruvians Strike Against Fujimori </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Peru's president ordered armored troop  
carriers and 20,000 police into the streets Wednesday to control 
protesters denouncing his failure to create jobs and reduce poverty 
in this Andean nation. 
</P>
<P>
	President Alberto Fujimori labeled the strike organizers as  
``communists.'' Labor Minister Pedro Flores declared the strike 
illegal and warned workers that their pay would be docked if they 
failed to show up for their jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Strike leaders said the threat had not succeeded in neutralizing  
the protest against Fujimori's free-market economic policies and 
his apparent plans to seek a third consecutive term next year 
despite a constitutional ban. 
</P>
<P>
	``The strike has been respected by 70 percent of the workers at  
the national level,'' said Jose Risco, leader of Peru's largest 
labor organization, the General Confederation of Peruvian Workers. 
</P>
<P>
	The protest was organized by leftist-led labor federations but  
was supported by a wide range of groups, including most opposition 
parties and even business organizations. 
</P>
<P>
	At least half of the businesses closed in downtown Lima, where  
protesters burned tires in the streets. Strikers stoned buses on 
major avenues on the outskirts of Lima. The strike was even 
stronger in major provincial cities. 
</P>
<P>
	``This strike is about poverty and unemployment,'' said Luis  
Carpio, a retired textile worker who has to make do with a 
$90-a-month pension. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hunger is the key issue. I've never seen people worse off in  
my 73 years,'' Carpio said as he watched protesters unfurl red 
banners in the Dos de Mayo Plaza that read ``No to the 
Dictatorship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of protesters from different parts of the city  
converged on the Plaza Mayor in front of the National Palace. 
</P>
<P>
	Soldiers with automatic weapons guarded public buildings and  
police fired tear gas at protesters burning tires in downtown Lima. 
</P>
<P>
	Street cleaner Zenobia Solorzano, a 45-year-old widow with three  
small children, showed up to work because she could not afford to 
lose a day's pay of $4.50 -- or her job. 
</P>
<P>
	``I work for a private company, and I came to work because if I  
didn't, they would have kicked me out,'' she said as she swept up 
trash in downtown Lima. 
</P>
<P>
	Peru's unions, weakened by anti-labor legislation under  
Fujimori, have gained renewed vigor as his free-market reforms have 
done little to generate jobs or reduce poverty. 
</P>
<P>
	The reforms halted hyperinflation that had soared above 7,000  
percent in 1990, the year Fujimori took office, and Peru's economy 
grew by a sizzling 32 percent between 1993 and 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	But in recent years, economic growth has stagnated and even the  
privileged classes now complain about Fujimori's policies. 
</P>
<P>
	Half of all Peruvians live in poverty. Ragged street beggars are  
visible everywhere. Privatizations of state enterprises have left 
tens of thousands without jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today there is agreement between bosses and workers that the  
economy is not functioning for either of them,'' said political 
analyst Nicolas Lynch. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 16:09:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
