<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> TRW Reorganizes Into Two Sectors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- TRW Corp., which agreed to acquire British auto  
parts maker LucasVarity PLC in a $7 billion deal, will reorganize 
into automotive and non-automotive sectors as it works to integrate 
the new business. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph Gorman, TRW chairman and chief executive, said TRW  
veteran Ronald Sugar has been appointed president and chief 
operating officer of TRW Aerospace and Information Systems. A 
search has begun for a president of TRW Automotive. 
</P>
<P>
	TRW Automotive will includes automotive operations of TRW and  
LucasVarity and will have 100,000 employees. TRW Aerospace and 
Information Systems includes TRW's space, defense and information 
systems business and Lucas Aerospace and will have nearly 35,000 
employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Gorman said he would lead a committee on integrating LucasVarity  
into TRW. 
</P>
<P>
	The company confirmed previous reports that Victor Rice, chief  
executive of LucasVarity, will not join TRW. 
</P>
<P>
	TRW makes automobile airbags, seat belts and other car parts,  
defense and aerospace equipment and is involved in information 
technology. The company made its bid for LucasVarity in January, 
beating out a rival automotive supplier, Federal-Mogul Corp. 

</P>
</TEXT>
