<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Drop / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices fell Wednesday as the market  
absorbed a supply of new Treasury debt securities and traders 
awaited a key measure of inflationary forces due on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 19/32  
point, or $5.94 cents per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which 
moves in the opposite direction, rose from late Tuesday's 5.54 
percent to 5.58 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices sagged as the U.S. Treasury auctioned another $15.0  
billion in debt securities, this time in two-year notes. On 
Tuesday, the Treasury sold $10.0 billion in 52-week notes. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders were also concerned that Thursday's report on  
first-quarter employment costs -- which typically account for 
two-thirds of a product's price -- might reveal inflationary 
pressures. Rising prices make fixed-income investments less 
enticing. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
finished unchanged to down 3/32 point, while intermediate 
maturities fell 7/32 to 13/32 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a 
financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.50 percent as the  
discount rose 0.02 percentage point from late Tuesday to 4.39 
percent. Six-month yields held steady at 4.58 percent, while the 
discount was unchanged at 4.41 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	One-year yields rose to 4.73 percent as the discount rose 0.4  
percentage point to 4.50 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 4.81 percent from late Tuesday's 4.88 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 1/8 point to 123 13/16. The average yield 
to maturity rose to 5.26 from 5.25 percent late Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
