<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4:30 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	House Votes To Restrict Clinton  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A divided House voted today to require  
President Clinton to get congressional approval before injecting 
``ground elements'' into the conflict in Yugoslavia. The 249 to 180 
vote to limit his ability to widen the war came despite Clinton's 
appeal to Congress that the United States must speak ``with a 
single voice'' on the crisis, as he said NATO had done. The 
restrictions are so vaguely worded that they could even make it 
hard to use the Apache attack helicopters that have been recently 
sent to Albania, Democratic opponents suggested. Democrats 
suggested a veto was likely if the measure is also enacted by the 
Senate. 

</P>
<P>
	Outspoken Yugoslav Official Fired  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Deputy Premier Vuk Draskovic, a  
former Yugoslav opposition leader who in recent days denounced 
Slobodan Milosevic's government, was dismissed today, state media 
reported. The Tanjug state news agency said Prime Minister Momir 
Bulatovic sacked the 52-year-old Draskovic because of ``public 
statements which were contrary to the government stands.'' 
Draskovic had said the Yugoslav leadership should stop lying to its 
people about the situation in the country after weeks of bombings 
and recognize ``we cannot defeat NATO.'' NATO also said it was 
seeing signs of growing discontent inside Yugoslavia. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Changing Sanctions Policy  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton has approved a major  
revision of U.S. sanctions policy that will permit sales of food 
and medical items to Iran, Libya and Sudan. Undersecretary of State 
Stuart Eizenstat said that denying countries food and medicines as 
well as medical equipment hurts innocent people in targeted 
countries, does not weaken the respective regimes, damages the U.S. 
image abroad and deprives U.S. companies of export opportunities. 
The policy will not affect congressionally mandated sanctions 
against Iraq, North Korea and Cuba. 

</P>
<P>
	Three Columbine Suspects Cleared  
</P>
<P>
	GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) -- Three teen-agers detained outside Columbine  
High School during last week's massacre have been cleared as 
suspects in the investigation, a sheriff's spokesman said today. 
Investigators also said that the 18-year-old girlfriend of one of 
the student gunmen bought three of the weapons used in the attack 
that left 15 dead. Sheriff's spokesman Steve Davis said the woman 
bought two shotguns and a semiautomatic rifle. 

</P>
<P>
	Casino, Lottery Moratorium Urged  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sharply divided, a panel studying gambling in  
America voted to recommend a moratorium on the spread of casinos, 
lotteries and slot machines around the nation. The National 
Gambling Impact Study Commission cannot impose a moratorium, but 
its report will call for ``a pause'' in the growth of legalized 
gambling and encourage state and local governments to form their 
own gambling study commissions. The commission, which has until 
June 18 to submit its report to Congress, the White House, 
governors and Indian reservations. 

</P>
<P>
	Justices Ponder Disabled  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court, trying to define the scope  
of a federal ban on discrimination, struggled today with a basic 
question: Who is disabled? As the court heard arguments about two 
nearsighted women who want to be United Air Lines pilots and a 
truck driver blind in one eye, some justices questioned whether 
poor eyesight is a disability protected under the Americans With 
Disabilities Act. By July, the justices are expected to use these 
cases to clarify who can sue under the ADA. 

</P>
<P>
	Study of Brain Comprehension Done  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A new study shows that humans' ability to  
understand speech is so deeply ingrained that people can even 
decipher sentences that have been recorded, chopped up into brief 
segments and played backwards. Researchers said the study shows 
that even if the message is distorted, ``other parameters are still 
able to convey the message.'' One professor said the research 
demonstrates that many areas of the brain are used to handle 
complicated auditory signals. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Mixed; Dow Ends Up 13.74  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices were mixed on Wall Street today as  
investors again collected profits from technology shares. But they 
kept buying big industrial stocks, pushing the Dow Jones industrial 
average to its second consecutive closing high: up 13.74 to 
10,845.45. On the NYSE, gainers led losers 1,735-1,279. The Nasdaq 
composite index, which is heavily weighted in technology stocks, 
was at 2,550.26, down 52.15. 

</P>
<P>
	Brewers' Vina Suspended  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Fernando Vina of the Milwaukee Brewers has been  
suspended for two games for putting a finger in the face of umpire 
Mike Winters during a dispute over balls and strikes. Vina was 
called out on strikes in a game in Pittsburgh on April 23. He 
angrily pointed his finger and apparently touched the umpire's 
face. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SAMANTHA CRITCHELL  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
