<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stocks Prices Slip / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks slipped today as investors sold  
issues to lock in profits before a series of national holidays. The 
dollar slipped against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 15.03 points,  
or 0.09 percent, ending the day at 16,942.24, erasing a 124.32 
point morning gain. On Tuesday, the average closed up 38.76 points, 
or 0.23 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 119.08 yen at late afternoon, down 0.38 yen  
from late Tuesday in Tokyo but below its late New York level of 
120.40 yen overnight. The currency ranged from 118.25 yen to 120.28 
yen. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices fell in the afternoon on profit  
taking, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier today, prices advanced following the overnight strength  
in New York stocks. Tuesday in New York, the Dow Jones industrial 
average rose 113.12 points to 10,831.71, topping its previous 
record finish of 10,727.18, set Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Demand was quite strong in the morning after shares in New  
York rose overnight, but sell orders began to pour in after the 
Nikkei average surpassed the 17,000 mark,'' said Yoshio Watanabe, a 
manager at the futures section of Toyo Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was up 8.72 points, or 0.65 percent, to 1,359.14. The 
TOPIX closed up 6.58 points, or 0.49 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the first section was estimated at 677.47 million  
shares, up from 633.38 million shares Tuesday. Retreating issues 
outnumbered advancers 695 to 483, with 137 issues unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar slipped on speculation that the  
government might put together a supplementary budget to prevent a 
deterioration of the economy later this year when funds for current 
stimulus measures run out. 
</P>
<P>
	But the dollar later rose back above 119 yen after Prime  
Minister Keizo Obuchi said he has no plans for an extra budget. The 
ruling Liberal Democratic Party's policy panel chief, Yukihiko 
Ikeda, also denied the speculation. 
</P>
<P>
	Automobile stocks were among shares that lost ground as the yen  
gained. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was trading at 127.22 yen, up from  
127.02 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Many players remained on the sidelines ahead of Japan's ``Golden  
Week'' holidays. Japanese financial markets will be closed 
Thursday, Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 212 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.460 percent from Tuesday's finish of 1.415 percent, 
driving its price down to 102.99 yen from 103.39 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
