<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 06:00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Envoys in Moscow To Discuss Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- Top diplomats and envoys converged on Moscow today  
in stepped-up efforts to settle the Kosovo conflict, with two 
European ministers and the U.N. chief arriving for talks with 
Russian officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The meetings came a day after a U.S. envoy discussed Yugoslavia  
with Russia's top policy-makers but left the Russian capital 
without any breakthroughs. Russia staunchly opposes NATO's 
airstrikes against Yugoslavia, and both sides remained divided over 
what type of international force should eventually move into 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia's special envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin, a former prime  
minister, met today with German Defense Minister Rudolf Scharping. 
Afterward, Scharping announced that Chernomyrdin would go to Bonn, 
Russian news agencies reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Scharping, whose country has played a key role in NATO 's air  
campaign, said afterwards there was ``hope for a political 
settlement to the crisis,'' the ITAR-Tass news agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he said his talks in Moscow ``should not be  
overestimated'' because any decisions regarding NATO must be 
approved by all alliance members. 
</P>
<P>
	Scharping also met with Russian Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev  
and Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov. 
</P>
<P>
	``The situation is extremely difficult, but there are still  
possibilities for a political way out of the present predicament,'' 
Ivanov said going into the meeting, according to Russian news 
agencies. 
</P>
<P>
	Greek Foreign Minister Georgios Papandreou, who has urged a  
political solution to the crisis, also arrived in Moscow today for 
talks with Chernomyrdin and Ivanov. 
</P>
<P>
	Greece is a NATO member but has no direct involvement in the  
bombing campaign. It faces growing public anger over the attacks 
against Serbia, a traditional ally. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan was to arrive in Moscow later  
today for talks on Kosovo, and Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd 
Axworthy was due in town Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Annan, Axworthy, Papandreou and Ivanov were to meet Thursday to  
discuss Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	While the West hopes Russia can play a key role in negotiating a  
peace deal, Moscow appears to have limited influence with Yugoslav 
President Slobodan Milosevic. Several Russian diplomatic missions 
to Belgrade have failed to make any progress. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, President Boris Yeltsin discussed Yugoslavia today  
with visiting Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko, who has 
also fiercely opposed NATO's actions. The two presidents called for 
close coordination of their actions regarding Kosovo, Yeltsin aide 
Sergei Prikhodko said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, U.S. Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott came  
to Moscow seeking to determine whether Russia had been able to 
persuade the Yugoslav government to compromise on any of the NATO 
demands over Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	Chernomyrdin said Washington and Moscow ``share certain points  
in their approaches to a peace settlement.'' But he reiterated 
Moscow's position that NATO must halt airstrikes on Yugoslavia to 
clear the way for talks, a condition repeatedly rejected by the 
alliance. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Russia's opposition to the NATO airstrikes, it has said  
it will not be dragged into the war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
