<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stephen Got Even Hopes To Win Derby </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- The baby tooth in the pendant is  
encircled by gold and diamonds. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the glare, it's not hard to notice the tooth in the  
bauble that hangs from an gold chain around Tomisue Hilbert's neck. 
The tooth belonged to a horse. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's my good luck charm,'' said the wife of Steve Hilbert, the  
owner Stephen Got Even, who will go into Saturday's Kentucky Derby 
off an impressive victory in the Gallery Furniture.com Stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	The tooth fell out while the colt was in the paddock before the  
Gallery Furniture on March 27 at Turfway Park, and Tomisue saw it 
on the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	It so happened the Hilberts had their sons, Christopher, 9, and  
Thomas, 4, and, she said, ``We made a wish to the tooth fairy to 
win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Got Even not only won the 1 1/8-mile race, his 2 1/2-length  
victory in only his fourth start kept him unbeaten in three races 
this year and made him a leading contender for the 1 1/4-mile Derby at 
Churchill Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe I'll go right to the Broadway show (the Derby) right  
from here,'' trainer Nick Zito said after the race. And that's what 
Zito has done with the colt who will give him a double-barreled 
shot at his third Derby victory. Zito, who also will saddle Wood 
Memorial winner Adonis for the 125th Derby, won the race with 
Strike the Gold in 1991 and with Go for Gin in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	The colt put in his final serious workout for the Derby last  
Saturday when he went five-eighths of a mile in 1:02 2-5 in company 
with another horse. Chris McCarron, who will ride Stephen Got Even 
for the first time in the Derby, flew in from California for the 
workout. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great feeling to be associated with Nick again,'' said  
McCarron, who won with Go for Gin. ``He knows how to get a horse up 
for the Derby.'' 
</P>
<P>
	According to Hilbert, president and CEO of Conseco, Inc., the  
largest publicly traded insurance company in the nation, Zito had 
the Derby in mind for colt after his only race as a 2-year-old -- a 
second-place finish Nov. 28 at Aqueduct. 
</P>
<P>
	The 52-year-old Hilbert, who paid $325,000 for Stephen Got Even  
at the 1997 Keeneland July Select Yearling Sale, recalled asking 
Zito what his plans were for the colt. Hilbert said he was 
referring to the next race, but Zito's response was his plan was 
for the colt to be at Churchill Downs on the first Saturday in May. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Got Even got his first victory in a 1 1-16-mile race  
maiden race Jan. 30 at Gulfstream Park and followed that up by 
winning a 1 1-16-mile allowance Race Feb. 27, also at Gulfstream. 
Then came the big win in the Gallery Furniture. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks later the other half of Zito's Derby Duo, Adonis,  
owned by Ernie Paragallo, turned in an impressive victory in the 
Wood Memorial at Aqueduct. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be the third Derby for Paragallo (Unbridled's Song,  
fifth, 1996, and Artax, 13th, 1998), but the first for the 
Hilberts. 
</P>
<P>
	Christopher and Thomas Hilbert will be at Churchill Downs on  
Derby Day. So, of course, will the good luck charm. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 14:25:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Etbauer Squeezed Out of Ky. Derby </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- A judge in Arkansas and a filly from  
California put Etbauer on the sideline for Saturday's Kentucky 
Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	In Little Rock, a judge said Valhol should be awarded the  
$300,000 for winning the Arkansas Derby on April 10. Then, trainer 
Bob Baffert decided Wednesday to enter the filly Excellent Meeting 
in Saturday's race. 
</P>
<P>
	That combination left Etbauer No. 21 on the graded stakes  
earning list of Derby hopefuls. Only the top 20 are entered. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a crummy feeling,'' Etbauer trainer Steve Wren said  
Wednesday. He and owner Hays Biggs hung around Churchill Downs 
during the morning, waiting for Baffert to make a decision about 
Excellent Meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	The filly and General Challenge are owned by the Golden Eagle  
Farm of John and Betty Mabee and Mabee said entering Excellent 
Meeting was an insurance policy of sorts. 
</P>
<P>
	Etbauer has $75,000 in graded earnings, but Valhol had only  
$38,400 prior to the judge's ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	The Arkansas Racing Commission ordered Oaklawn Park to put the  
first-place check on hold during an investigation that began after 
Oaklawn officials said they had evidence that Valhol jockey Billy 
Patin might have carried an illegal electrical device. Patin says 
he is innocent and a hearing in the case is May 5. 
</P>
<P>
	Biggs said Wednesday he considered challenging the judge's  
ruling, but decided against it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Kentucky Derby, to me, is the epitome of horse racing,''  
he said. ``I was just not going to tarnish it. Horse racing has 
been tarnished enough. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to sound like a guy bellyaching about spilled  
beans but that should have never happened,'' Biggs said. ``I feel 
bad that my horse and my trainer are penalized. 
</P>
<P>
	``Next week, when they have the hearing and all this is going to  
come out, it will not be easy to swallow,'' Biggs said. ``I've been 
in athletics all my life. The coach says always play by the rules. 
I've always raised my family that way. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people in this game don't play that way,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Etbauer ran second in his two races last year and started 1999  
with a 6 1/2-length victory in a maiden race. He won an allowance race 
at Oaklawn Park by a length and then captured the Grade III Rebel 
by almost a length on March 20. He finished sixth in the Arkansas 
Derby and jockey Calvin Borel said the son of Silver Deputy didn't 
like the surface. 
</P>
<P>
	Etbauer will probably make his next start in the May 8 Illinois  
Derby 
</P>
<P>
	Biggs said he was surprised that Baffert entered Excellent  
Meeting, but realized it was the trainer's prerogative. 
</P>
<P>
	Biggs drove to Louisville because he planned to bring in his six  
children for the race and knew he would need extra vehicles to 
transport everybody. He plans to head home Thursday and said he 
would not watch the Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got very close to getting in,'' he said. ``It would be very  
difficult for me.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 21:22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ford Cancels Plans for Brazil Plant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. has canceled plans to  
build a new auto plant in Rio Grande do Sul, a southern Brazilian 
state, citing a government decision to pull a $257 million 
financial incentive package from the project. 
</P>
<P>
	``The incentive package originally offered was a major factor in  
the company's decision to locate the plant in Guaiba,'' said a 
statement Wednesday from Marin Inglis, president of Ford South 
American Operations, and Ivan Fonseca e Silva, president of 
Ford-Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	``Without such support, Ford Motor Co. simply cannot be  
competitive,'' it read. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rio Grande do Sul state government said the $257 million  
incentive package extended to the Brazilian subsidiaries of Ford 
and General Motors Corp. was needed for infrastructure projects. 
</P>
<P>
	The plant was expected to begin making 120,000 cars a year as of  
2001. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said it will look at other sites for a Brazilian  
plant and continue its presence in Rio Grande do Sul through its 
dealerships. 
</P>
<P>
	General Motors is still in negotiation with the Rio Grande do  
Sul government, said John Mueller, GM's director of international 
communications. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not really commenting on anything pending the outcome of  
those negotiations,'' Mueller said. ``We're still hoping to begin 
operations there next year.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
