<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *Ronald Alley    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Ronald Alley, who built up the modern art  
collection at the Tate Gallery and served 21 years as its first 
Keeper of the Modern Collection, died Sunday. He was 73. 
</P>
<P>
	He joined the gallery staff in 1951 following studies at the  
Courtauld Institute of Art and found that the Tate had hardly any 
modern art. 
</P>
<P>
	Appointed Keeper of the Modern Collection in 1965, Alley built  
up the Tate's holdings. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Arbit Blatas    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Arbit Blatas, a Lithuanian-born sculptor,  
painter and stage designer noted for his portraits of Picasso, 
Matisse, Soutine, Cocteau and other artists, died Tuesday. He was 
90. 
</P>
<P>
	Blatas has a series of seven bronze tablets on a wall of the  
Campo del Nuovo Ghetto in Venice. The 1979 tablets commemorate the 
night of Dec. 5, 1943, when 200 of the city's Jews were rounded up 
for deportation and death. 
</P>
<P>
	Blatas also did the black-and-white drawings used in the  
introductory segments of the 1978 television series ``The 
Holocaust.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blatas' last book of paintings, ``An Artist's Venice'' (Vendrome  
Press), was published in 1997. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Frank Ford    	
</P>
<P>
	TUSCALOOSA, Ala. (AP) -- Frank Ford, a defensive end on Alabama's  
undefeated football team in 1966, died Sunday when his car ran off 
a road and crashed. He was 51. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford was an Associated Press All-Southeastern Conference  
selection in 1967 and 1968. He was a member of the Academic All-SEC 
team in 1968. 

</P>
<P>
                      *Heinz L. Fraenkel-Conrat    	
</P>
<P>
	BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) -- Biochemist Heinz L. Fraenkel-Conrat, a  
professor emeritus of molecular and cell biology at the University 
of California, Berkeley, died April 10 of pulmonary failure. He was 
88. 
</P>
<P>
	He discovered that genetic information controlling viral  
reproduction is carried in the nucleic acid core of each virus 
particle. 
</P>
<P>
	Fraenkel-Conrat, a native of Germany, fled the country after  
Adolf Hitler came to power. He earned his Ph.D. in biochemistry at 
the University of Edinburgh in Scotland in 1936 and came to the 
United States that same year. He joined the UC-Berkeley faculty in 
1952. 

</P>
<P>
                              *Al Hirt    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Al Hirt, whose power and technique made him  
``The King of the Trumpet'' in the 1960s when he won a Grammy for 
his hit ``Java,'' died Tuesday of liver failure. He was 76. 
</P>
<P>
	He had 21 Grammy nominations in a career spanning more than 50  
years. In 1964, he won a Grammy for best non-jazz instrumental for 
``Java.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At his peak in the 1960s, he played for John Kennedy's  
inauguration, starred at Carnegie Hall, and headlined numerous 
television variety shows, including his own ``Fanfare'' program on 
CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	In all, he recorded more than 50 albums -- four gold and one  
platinum. ``Honey in the Horn'' reached No. 3 on Billboard's 
Popular Music Album Chart in 1963; ``Sugar Lips'' won Billboard's 
favorite instrumentalist of 1965. In 1962 he was named `best 
trumpeter' in the Playboy jazz poll, a prize he won for 15 
subsequent years. 

</P>
<P>
                       *Dame Christian Howard    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Dame Christian Howard, a leader in the movement  
that led the Church of England to ordain women as priests, died 
Thursday. She was 82. 
</P>
<P>
	As a member of the General Synod, the church's governing body,  
she wrote a report, ``The Ordination of Women,'' in 1972. The 
report, which examined attitudes on women in church history as well 
as the Hebrew and Greek classical traditions, was updated in 1978 
and again in 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	It was a key document in a debate that ended in 1992 when the  
synod voted in favor of ordaining women. 
</P>
<P>
	She was a member of the faith and order committee of the World  
Council of Churches from 1961-75. 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Howard was made a Dame Commander of the Order of British  
Empire, the equivalent of a knighthood, in 1986. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Sir William McCrea    	
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Sir William McCrea, an astrophysicist who made a  
vital contribution to the understanding of the sun's composition 
and went on to develop important theories about the evolution of 
galaxies and planets, died Sunday. He was 94. 
</P>
<P>
	As a young research student in 1929, McCrea conclusively  
confirmed a hypothesis that hydrogen was by far the most common 
element in the outer layers of the sun's atmosphere. 
</P>
<P>
	His calculations -- and the subsequent realization that every  
star was mainly composed of hydrogen -- revolutionized the science 
of cosmology and led to the big-bang theory of the origin of the 
universe. 
</P>
<P>
	McCrea's publications included ``Relativity Physics'' (1935),  
``Physics of the Sun and Stars'' (1950), and ``History of the Royal 
Astronomical Society 1920 to 1980'' (1987). 
</P>
<P>
	He was knighted by Queen Elizabeth II in 1985.  

</P>
<P>
                           *Dr. Rose Payne    	
</P>
<P>
	SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- Dr. Rose Payne, whose more than three  
decades of research advanced the field of organ transplants, died 
April 18. She was 89. 
</P>
<P>
	Payne, an expert in tissue-typing, was credited with helping to  
identify proteins that play a key role in how the body accepts a 
tissue graft or blood transfusion. Before her work, doctors had to 
try and guess the likelihood of a transplant's success solely on 
matching the blood type of the donor and recipient. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1984, the American Society for Histocompatibility and  
Immunogenetics named an award in her honor. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Charles H. Pillard    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Charles H. Pillard, president of the  
International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers during the years of 
its greatest membership, died Monday of a heart attack. He was 80. 
</P>
<P>
	Pillard was the IBEW's president from 1968 to 1986. During that  
period the union successfully challenged President Nixon's federal 
wage controls as penalizing the working poor and won a case forcing 
Westinghouse to disclose information about its treatment of female 
and minority employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Pillard started his union career as an electrician in Buffalo,  
During his tenure as IBEW president, the union reached a peak 
membership of 1 million workers, now down to about 750,000. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Bert Remsen    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Bert Remsen, an actor whose long list of  
movie credits included ``Pork Chop Hill'' and the current ``Forces 
of Nature,'' died Thursday of heart failure. He was 74. 
</P>
<P>
	He thought he was finished in show business in 1964 when an  
84-foot crane toppled on the television set of ``No Time for 
Sergeants'' and broke his back. He then decided to become a casting 
director. 
</P>
<P>
	Remsen was casting the part of a psychotic cop in the film  
``Brewster McCloud'' in 1970 when director Robert Altman suddenly 
looked at him and said, ``You.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He later worked in other Altman films, including ``McCabe &AMP; Mrs.  
Miller,'' ``California Split,'' ``Nashville'' and ``Thieves Like 
Us,'' and he soon abandoned the casting business. 
</P>
<P>
	Other credits included ``A Wedding,'' ``Fast Break,'' ``The  
Sting II,'' ``Places in the Heart,'' ``Miss Firecracker,'' ``Dick 
Tracy,'' ``Only the Lonely,'' ``The Bodyguard,'' ``The Player'' and 
``Maverick.'' 

</P>
<P>
                           *Herbert Young    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Herbert Young, who received France's Legion of  
Honor cross for service during World War I, died Thursday. He was 
112. 
</P>
<P>
	Young received France's highest award for military service in  
February. He was named a knight in the National Order of the Legion 
of Honor. 
</P>
<P>
	As a member of the 807 Pioneer Infantry, Young served as a  
corporal in the bloody Meuse-Argonne offensive, which claimed the 
lives of thousands of American soldiers and was considered a 
turning point in the war. 
</P>
<P>
	His unit was one of many all-black outfits that fought on the  
front lines under the French flag because of U.S. Army segregation 
policies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
