<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 16:42:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coach in His Element As Wings Sweep </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- He hardly caused a ripple during the regular  
season. Those games are just warmups for the main event in the NHL. 
</P>
<P>
	It is in the playoffs when Detroit coach Scotty Bowman finds his  
element. 
</P>
<P>
	In the Red Wings' four-game sweep of the Anaheim Mighty Ducks in  
the first round, they got outstanding scoring from Steve Yzerman 
and clutch goaltending by Chris Osgood. 
</P>
<P>
	But the team also got the best of Bowman. That may prove most  
important of all as the Red Wings attempt to win the Stanley Cup 
for the third consecutive season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Scotty kind of comes to life this time of the year,'' Yzerman  
said. ``But he doesn't have to say very much to this group of 
guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bowman, 65, has a 1,100-516-284 regular season mark and a  
198-112 playoff record, winning five Stanley Cups with Montreal, 
two with Detroit and one with Pittsburgh. The only other coach to 
win eight Stanley Cups is his mentor, Toe Blake. 
</P>
<P>
	Only five times in NHL history have teams won three or more  
championships in succession, and no team has done it since Al 
Arbour guided the New York Islanders to four straight Cup titles 
between 1980-83. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowman began laying the groundwork for his latest run before the  
playoffs began. 
</P>
<P>
	Shortly after the trading deadline -- during which the Red Wings  
added some much-needed muscle in Chris Chelios, Wendel Clark, Ulf 
Samuelsson and goalie Bill Ranford -- Bowman began resting many of 
his veterans. The fresh legs were a factor against Anaheim as 
Yzerman scored five goals in the four games. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowman, a master at the mind games that add spice to the  
playoffs, went to work early against the Mighty Ducks. An example 
that stands out was the way he split up his defensemen. 
</P>
<P>
	For most of the season, Nicklas Lidstrom, the Red Wings' best  
defender, had been paired with Larry Murphy. Against the Mighty 
Ducks, Bowman had Lidstrom skating with Chelios. 
</P>
<P>
	It proved to be a master stroke.  
</P>
<P>
	Lidstrom and Chelios skated every shift against the high-powered  
Anaheim line of Paul Kariya and Teemu Selanne, holding them to 
three goals. Kariya broke his left foot stopping a shot and was 
unable to play in Game 4. But it probably wouldn't have mattered. 
</P>
<P>
	The pattern had been set by Bowman. The damage was already too  
great. Detroit won the fourth game 3-0 and awaits the outcome of 
Colorado's first-round series with the San Jose Sharks. If the 
Avalanche advance, as expected, Detroit and Denver would resume 
their grudge match in the second round. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowman, who missed the first two weeks of the season while  
recovering from heart surgery and a knee operation, also 
demonstrated his skill behind the bench during the sweep of 
Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
	During the third game, the Mighty Ducks were giving the Red  
Wings fits. The game was tied at 2 early in the second period when 
Stu Grimson cross-checked Kris Draper. 
</P>
<P>
	Grimson's five-minute major, coupled with another penalty, left  
Detroit with a two-man advantage for two minutes, and a power play 
for a full three minutes after that. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of just going with the flow, however, Bowman called  
timeout. 
</P>
<P>
	Most coaches like to save their timeouts for late in the game.  
Bowman felt this was the time to seize control. 
</P>
<P>
	Yzerman had been carrying the puck on the left side, with  
Brendan Shanahan and Clark crashing the crease. It wasn't working, 
but Bowman told the team to stay with it. 
</P>
<P>
	It worked. Yzerman's power-play goal gave Detroit a 3-2 lead.  
The Red Wings skated away with a 4-2 victory and a 3-0 edge in the 
series. 
</P>
<P>
	``You never know what Scotty's going to have up his sleeve,''  
forward Darren McCarty said. 
</P>
<P>
	Especially during the playoffs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
