<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Mixed; Dow Closes Up 13.74 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices ended mixed on Wednesday as  
investors again collected profits from technology shares and 
continued buying big manufacturing stocks, sending the Dow Jones 
industrial average to a second straight record high close. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow rose 13.74 to 10,845.45 after being up as much as 103  
points earlier in the session. It closed Tuesday at a record 
10,831.71. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 11.89 to 1,350.91, and the Nasdaq  
composite index, which is heavily weighted in technology stocks, 
fell 52.04 to 2,550.37. 
</P>
<P>
	Returning to a trading pattern that began last week, investors  
were buying previously ignored stocks of cyclical companies whose 
fortunes are closely tied to the economy. Analysts said growing 
signs that the global economy is recovering were making these 
stocks more attractive. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cyclical stocks have raced ahead and more of the growth names  
have backed off a bit,'' said Charles White, portfolio manager at 
Avatar Associates, referring to the drop in technology stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The active buying of cyclical names pushed up industrial  
stalwarts like Dow component Alcoa, which rose 6 5/8 to 62; Minnesota 
Mining and Manufacturing, up 3 11/16 at 84 1/2; and Allied Signal, up 
3 1/16 at 59 1/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil stocks were higher as crude prices rose on an unexpected  
decline in domestic supplies. Dow component Exxon was up 3 1/4 at 81 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	The enthusiasm for industrial stocks was bolstered by a report  
from the Commerce Department that orders to factories for 
big-ticket durable goods rose 2 percent in March after an 
end-of-winter slump. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors are increasingly optimistic about corporate profits  
for the second half of the year. The current crop of earnings 
reports has generally been very positive, including some pleasant 
surprises like IBM's first-quarter results, and analysts said that 
bodes well for the rest of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM, which has surged higher over the past week, was hit by  
profit-taking along Wednesday with other technology shares and slid 
7 points to 205. Other technology stocks fell as traders took 
profits, and analysts said lingering anxiety about Internet stocks 
that have soared in recent months was also weighing on high-tech 
issues. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft lost 1 7/8 to 82 1/8 and was the most actively traded Nasdaq  
stock. 
</P>
<P>
	There was some caution ahead of an earnings report from  
Amazon.com, scheduled to be released after the close of trading, 
and Amazon's shares were down 12 3/8 at 193 1/2. The online retailer 
reported a loss per share of 23 cents, outperforming analysts' 
expected loss of 29 cents. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, shares of America Online, which surpassed analysts'  
expectations in an earnings report late Tuesday, shed 10 to 143. 
Lycos, which runs an Internet search engine, was down 4 1/8 at 96 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Drug and consumer stocks fell as investors shunned them in favor  
of industrial names. The exit from drug stocks was also prompted by 
McKesson HBOC Inc., a pharmaceutical supply-management company, 
which restated fourth-quarter results after discovering improperly 
recorded sales. McKesson's shares plunged 31 1/4 to 34 1/2. Coca-Cola 
slid 1 1/2 to 67 15/16. 
</P>
<P>
	White said ``new money'' was coming into the marketplace, a sign  
that investors are more confident about stocks than they were a few 
months ago. Earlier in the year, investors parked tremendous sums 
of money in short-term money market funds, and White said this 
money now appears to be coming into stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a slim 9-to-8 margin  
on the New York Stock Exchange. Consolidated volume was heavy at 
1.17 billion shares, up from Tuesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 2.95 to 640.32, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 3.62 to 777.69. The Russell 
2000 index of smaller companies fell 1.63 to 433.53. 
</P>
<P>
	In foreign stock markets, the Nikkei index in Tokyo fell 0.09  
percent. In Europe, the FT-SE 100 in London set its second straight 
closing high, rising 0.1 percent to 6,598.8. The DAX index in 
Frankfurt inched up 0.02 percent, while the CAC index in Paris 
eased 0.4 after hitting a record on Tuesday. 

</P>
</TEXT>
