<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 15:35:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Past Is Prologue for Philly Mayor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- In a city trying hard to focus on the  
future, the two leading candidates for mayor can't seem to shake 
their pasts. 
</P>
<P>
	John Street, the buttoned-down former City Council president  
seeking to become Philadelphia's second black mayor, is trying to 
live down his reputation from the 1980s as a hothead and a 
rabble-rouser. His opponent is running a commercial with footage 
from 18 years ago of Street -- then a community activist with a big 
Afro -- angrily shoving a reporter to the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Street's chief rival for the Democratic nomination, lawyer Marty  
Weinberg, finds himself defending his political relationship with 
the late Mayor Frank Rizzo, one of the most polarizing figures in 
Philadelphia history. Rizzo left office 19 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not the nature of Philadelphia politics to let these  
things go,'' said G. Terry Madonna, a Millersville University 
political scientist. 
</P>
<P>
	Street and Weinberg lead a field of five Democrats trying to  
succeed Mayor Edward G. Rendell, who in two terms brought the city 
back from the brink of financial disaster. Philadelphia is now 
undergoing a downtown building boom, and its bright future includes 
the Republican National Convention in 2000. Rendell is prohibited 
from seeking a third term. 
</P>
<P>
	The winner of the May 18 primary will face wealthy GOP  
businessman Sam Katz in the fall. Rendell himself describes Katz as 
a formidable opponent with a chance to become Philadelphia's first 
Republican mayor since 1952. 
</P>
<P>
	The race has drawn national big-league political talent for a  
race that experts say could be one of the most expensive mayoral 
contests in U.S. history, running up to $20 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Weinberg, a political power broker making his first bid for  
office, has raised more than $3 million. Airing TV spots months 
before his rivals helped. In January, polls had him dead last. This 
month, a new poll showed him tied with Street. 
</P>
<P>
	Weinberg was a law professor at Drexel University when Rizzo  
named him city solicitor in 1972. The two forged a close political 
relationship that lasted until Rizzo's death in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Rizzo's administration was blamed for police brutality and  
financial mismanagement, and on the campaign trail, Weinberg always 
gets questioned about his ties to Rizzo. In a recent television 
debate, Street said he ``would hate to go back'' to the Rizzo 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Weinberg stands by his political mentor.  
</P>
<P>
	``Frank Rizzo did a lot of very good things for the city of  
Philadelphia. He was not perfect. He made mistakes. But nobody can 
ever deny the fact he loved this city and devoted his life to it,'' 
Weinberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Philadelphia politics, the question of race is never far  
below the surface. But political observers said so far, it has not 
become a dividing line. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the candidates are really striving hard to avoid these  
deep racial divisions,'' Madonna said. 
</P>
<P>
	Weinberg, who is white, expects to do well in the blue-collar  
rowhouse neighborhoods of this city of 1.5 million people, more 40 
percent of them black. 
</P>
<P>
	But he has a formidable foe in Street, who forged a close  
alliance with Rendell early this decade. Together, they took on the 
city's municipal unions and helped turn a $250 million budget 
deficit into a surplus before Street stepped down from the City 
Council to run for mayor. 
</P>
<P>
	Rendell, who leaves office with a glittering future and has  
discussed running for governor, has endorsed Street's candidacy and 
appeared in one of his campaign commercials. 
</P>
<P>
	Street was a vociferous community activist in his early days,  
protesting everything from vending regulations to housing programs. 
</P>
<P>
	He also had a temper. Besides shoving the TV reporter (who sued  
and settled for $1,000), Street is notorious for a 1981 fistfight 
on the floor of City Council spurred by the possibility of a school 
strike. 
</P>
<P>
	After that episode, Street began exerting more control over  
himself. His political views changed, too. Once a liberal, he had 
become by 1989 a fiscal conservative and a budget hawk. Street was 
elected City Council president in 1992, the year Rendell took 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's changed,'' said Randall Miller, a St. Joseph's University  
professor who follows Philadelphia politics. ``He's changed because 
he has exercised extraordinary self-discipline, as he insisted the 
city should do.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
