<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Mixed; Dow Up 17.18 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices were narrowly mixed on Wall Street on  
Wednesday as investors kept on buying big industrial stocks and 
took more profits from technology issues. 
</P>
<P>
	At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up  
17.18 at 10,848.89 after rising 113.12 Tuesday to a new closing 
high of 10,831.71. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
index was off 3.76 at 1,359.04, and the Nasdaq composite index, 
which is heavily weighted in technology stocks, was down 23.06 at 
2,579.35. 
</P>
<P>
	The market returned to the divergent trading pattern it began  
last week, with industrial stocks rising on growing signs that the 
global economy is recovering. That has increased trader appetites 
for economically-sensitive industrial companies like Dow component 
Alcoa, which was up 3 5/16 at 58 11/16 today. Another Dow stock, 
Goodyear Tire &AMP; Rubber, was up 1 11/16 at 55 15/16. 
</P>
<P>
	The market was optimistic about corporate profits for the second  
half of this year. The current crop of earnings reports has 
generally been very positive, including some pleasant surprises 
like IBM's first-quarter results, and analysts said that bodes well 
for the rest of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM, which has surged higher over the past week, was down 4 at  
208 today amid profit-taking. 
</P>
<P>
	Other technology stocks were falling as traders collected  
profits, and analysts reported lingering anxiety about Internet 
stocks that have soared in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	Bryan Piskorowski, a market analyst with Prudential Securities,  
said there was some caution in the market today as traders awaited 
an earnings report from Amazon.com, scheduled to be released after 
the close of trading. Amazon's results were being watched closely 
as a possible harbinger of what's to come for other online 
companies. The company's stock was down 8 1/4 at 197 5/8. 
</P>
<P>
	America Online, which surpassed analyst expectations in an  
earnings report issued late Tuesday, was down 3 1/2 to 149 1/2. Lycos, 
which runs an internet search engine, was down 4 7/8 at 96 1/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 5-to-4 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 426.1 million shares, 
down slightly from Tuesday's pace. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
