<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marfan Patients Urged On Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Surgery to correct a life-threatening heart defect  
in people with Marfan's syndrome is far safer if done before 
symptoms develop, researchers reported today in the New England 
Journal of Medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	About 200,000 people in the United States have Marfan's  
syndrome, an inherited disorder of the connective tissue. Those who 
inherit it are often unusually tall and are likely to have weakened 
aortas that can rupture disastrously, causing death. 
</P>
<P>
	In the early 1970s, the average life expectancy of people with  
the disorder was about 45. But it is now in the 70s, in part 
because of the use of open-heart surgery to repair weakened aortas. 
</P>
<P>
	New research concludes that this repair should be performed as  
soon as the defect is diagnosed. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Vincent L. Gott and others from Johns Hopkins University  
compared the results of routine aorta repair with waiting until the 
condition causes symptoms, when the surgery often must be done as 
an emergency operation. They reviewed the records of 675 patients 
who underwent aorta repair between 1968 and 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those who got elective surgery, about 2 percent died  
during the month following the operation. However, when the 
operation was considered an emergency, 12 percent died. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 06:25:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DEA Opens Its Own Training Facility </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Drug Enforcement Administration is opening  
a $29 million training academy for its agents beside the FBI 
Academy at Quantico, Va. 
</P>
<P>
	``The new academy is a dream come true for us at DEA,'' said  
Administrator Thomas Constantine, whose agency previously shared 
space in the FBI Academy. ``We will no longer have to work around 
the classroom space shortages we faced in recent years.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The center, which opens Wednesday, can house 250 trainees, two  
to a room, and will provide the basic 16-week training course that 
all new DEA agents receive. There are eight classrooms, each 
seating about 50. Two are equipped for computer training and one 
has simultaneous translation facilities for international classes. 
</P>
<P>
	The computers, audiovisual equipment, telephone and security  
arrangements cost $5 million in addition to the $29 million 
construction cost. 
</P>
<P>
	Support facilities include a health office, cafeteria, post  
office, bank and dry cleaner. 
</P>
<P>
	Adjacent to the new training center will be a special structure  
to train agents in the investigation of clandestine drug 
laboratories. This is often a life-threatening assignment because 
these labs typically contain explosive, flammable or toxic 
materials and may emit odorless, colorless poisonous gases. 
</P>
<P>
	As of this year, DEA has given the clandestine lab course to  
more than 4,600 federal, state and local agents. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, DEA trained 3,000 of its international counterparts.  
That program will continue in the new facility, as will the DEA's 
training of state and local police officers. 
</P>
<P>
	DEA trainees will continue to share a driver training course,  
firing range, gymnasium and auditorium with the FBI. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
