<DOCNO> APW19990428.0143 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 05:53:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Trumpet Extraordinaire Hirt Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- With a combination of power and virtuosity,  
Al Hirt could ruffle curtains at the back of an auditorium or ease 
out a honey-toned melody with his trumpet. 
</P>
<P>
	The 76-year-old musician, whose lilting version of ``Java'' won  
a Grammy in 1964, died Tuesday at home of liver failure. He had 
been in failing health since leaving a hospital a week ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Hirt's dazzling skill, amplified by awesome power, resulted in  
21 Grammy nominations during his 50-year career. ``Java'' won for 
best non-jazz instrumental. 
</P>
<P>
	``He represented a certain particular style of New Orleans music  
-- not just Dixieland or traditional jazz,'' said George Wein, 
producer of the New Orleans Jazz and Heritage Festival. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a side of New Orleans entertainment best personified by  
Louis Prima -- the waving handkerchief, the dancing, the whole 
showbiz aspect, all the time playing good music. It was unique to 
New Orleans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In all, Hirt recorded more than 50 albums -- four gold and one  
platinum. ``Honey in the Horn'' reached No. 3 on Billboard's 
Popular Music Album Chart in 1963; ``Sugar Lips'' won Billboard's 
favorite instrumentalist of 1965. In 1962, he was named `best 
trumpeter' in the Playboy jazz poll, a prize he won for 15 
subsequent years. 
</P>
<P>
	At his peak, he played for John Kennedy's inauguration, starred  
at Carnegie Hall, and headlined numerous television variety shows, 
including his own ``Fanfare'' program on CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was one of the best trumpet players all around the world,''  
said clarinetist Pete Fountain, a longtime friend. ``He had 
everything -- technique, stamina, education.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hirt and Fountain started out together, working as exterminators  
by day and playing music at night. They remained friends for more 
than 50 years and in recent years toured together with their two 
bands. 
</P>
<P>
	Born Alois Maxwell Hirt in New Orleans in 1922, Hirt got his  
first trumpet when he was 6 and was hailed as a prodigy when he was 
13. He was classically trained at the Cincinnati Conservatory of 
Music. 
</P>
<P>
	His first big break came in 1950, when he won second place in  
Horace Heidt's National Youth Opportunity Contest and was named 
solo trumpet in Heidt's band. 
</P>
<P>
	Real national fame came in 1960 when Hirt's Dixieland Six caught  
the attention of Dinah Shore and he became an overnight success on 
TV. 
</P>
<P>
	Hirt didn't call it jazz.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm a pop commercial musician, and I've got a successful  
format,'' he once said. ``If you have the ability to perform your 
musical idea, you become a good jazz player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hirt tried to arrange his career so he could stay with his wife  
and eight kids in New Orleans, where he was one of the original 
group to bring professional football to the city. His club on 
Bourbon Street became his musical headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1970, Hirt found himself in the spotlight for an unusual  
reason: a busted lip suffered while riding a Mardi Gras float. He 
told officers he was hit in the face with a brick. The injury 
required 12 stitches and hampered his playing for months. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1983, he provoked controversy when he said he had had enough  
of the crime and filth of the French Quarter and closed the club he 
had operated since 1960. He later apologized, but did not reopen 
the club. 
</P>
<P>
	After that he mostly toured and performed on television, with  
only occasional local appearances at ``Jellyroll's'' in the French 
Quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	He considered one of his most important performances the 1987  
solo of Handel's ``Ave Maria'' for Pope John Paul II during the 
pontiff's visit to New Orleans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 15:05:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McTeddy Craze Hits Malaysia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) -- Move over, Teenie Beanies. McTeddy  
Bears are the latest craze, causing a frenzy in McDonald's 
restaurants in Malaysia. 
</P>
<P>
	Collectors mobbed Malaysia's 122 McDonald's outlets Tuesday,  
pushing and shoving, even ripping a glass door from its hinges at 
one branch, to lay hands on a pair of promotional ``Wedding 
Bears,'' the last in a series of 14 miniatures. 
</P>
<P>
	Overwhelmed by the mania, McDonald's said Wednesday it would  
order more of the toys to meet customer demand. 
</P>
<P>
	The 3-inch bears, which were sold only in Asian McDonald's  
outlets, sold out within hours after people camped out overnight to 
avoid lines. Adults fought and yelled, and police were called to 
certain stores to control the crowds. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we started the McTeddy promotion, we didn't expect  
front-page news,'' Loi Liang Tok, marketing director for McDonald's 
Malaysia, said Wednesday. ``We just wish we'd ordered more.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To accommodate the heavy demand, McDonald's has set up a special  
mail-order option, with a relaxed May 15 deadline, so collectors 
can buy their bears from a Hong-Kong supplier, Loi said. 
</P>
<P>
	The McTeddy Bears went on sale in Malaysia on April 1. The  
frenzy this week may have been exacerbated by collectors' desire to 
own a complete set, including bathing bears, beach bears, boating 
bears and Scottish bears. 
</P>
<P>
	McDonald's is accustomed to wildly popular promotions. In 1997,  
the company offered the popular Teenie Beanies with its Happy Meals 
in the United States, prompting some parents to buy caseloads of 
the meals. The Teenie Beanies will again go on sale in June in U.S. 
restaurants, spokesman Brad Trask said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	He said customers were equally excited about a line of 28 Snoopy  
collectibles sold last year in Thailand, Singapore and Hong Kong. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is yet another example of promotions in Asia that have  
really illicited a phenomenal reaction,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 14:25:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Thunderstorms rippled across parts of the Southeast on Wednesday  
as rain was scattered in the East. Snow fell in the mountains of 
the West. 
</P>
<P>
	Thunderstorms piled up during the afternoon over southern  
Florida and the Florida Panhandle, and spread out across much of 
the rest of the state and into southern Georgia. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Weather Service posted severe thunderstorm warnings  
for several sections of Florida, including the Miami area, Tampa 
Bay, central Florida and the state's northeastern corner. 
</P>
<P>
	Warnings also were issued for parts of western Georgia.  
</P>
<P>
	Other showers and thunderstorms were scattered across the Ohio  
Valley, from Illinois into Indiana, Ohio and Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	A few thunderstorms also spread into eastern Tennessee, and  
showers extended through West Virginia into Virginia and the 
Carolinas. 
</P>
<P>
	Severe thunderstorm warnings were issued for southern Indiana  
and north-central Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	As much as 3 inches of rain was reported in parts of Ohio during  
the early morning. 
</P>
<P>
	In the West, mostly light showers were scattered from Idaho and  
Montana south through Utah, Wyoming, Colorado, northern Arizona and 
New Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	In the mountains, 4 inches of snow fell overnight at Alta, Utah,  
and in California's Sierra Nevada. Light snow also fell in Reno, 
Nev. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's temperatures around the Lower 48 states ranged from  
a morning low of 18 at Redmond, Ore., to an early afternoon reading 
of 85 at Fort Lauderdale, Fla. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
