<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MediaOne Posts First-Quarter Loss </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- MediaOne Group lost $111 million in the first  
quarter, but reported growing demand for its high-speed Internet 
access, a promising business that's made the cable television 
company the focus of a takeover battle. 
</P>
<P>
	The quarterly loss by MediaOne amounted to 21 cents per share,  
which was less than most Wall Street analysts had expected, 
according to a survey by the research firm First Call. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's report came about a week after AT&AMP;T made a surprise  
bid of $58 billion for the nation's fourth largest cable company, 
hoping to undo MediaOne's agreement to be acquired for $49 billion 
by No. 3 Comcast. 
</P>
<P>
	In the first quarter of 1998, MediaOne earned $212 million,  
although that profit reflected contributions from a wireless 
communications business that was sold off last April. 
</P>
<P>
	Excluding that business, MediaOne would have posted a net loss  
of $222 million in last year's first quarter, or twice as much as 
it lost in the first three months of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Likewise, MediaOne's first-quarter revenues of $665 million were  
down nearly 50 percent from year-ago levels, but actually represent 
an 11 percent improvement when compared with only those operations 
that remain part of the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps most noteworthy in the quarterly report was the net  
increase of 30,000 customers for high-speed Internet access, a 36 
percent jump to 114,000 since the end of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The sharp increase helps explain the urgency with which new  
alliances and takeovers are reshaping an industry whose wires, 
capable of carrying more traffic than phone lines, are being viewed 
as a perfect way to bring consumers a unified package of video, 
telephone and Internet services. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past year, AT&AMP;T has acquired Tele-Communications Inc.,  
the nation's second largest cable company, and formed an alliance 
with No. 1 Time Warner Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	``Operationally, we had an excellent quarter,'' said Chuck  
Lillis, MediaOne's chief executive. ``Obviously, the big news in 
the quarter was our agreement to merge with Comcast. Since then, of 
course, AT&AMP;T has presented us with a proposal, and we have signed a 
confidentiality agreement so we can negotiate with them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If successful in its bid for MediaOne, AT&AMP;T would become the  
largest cable company in the nation with the ability to reach more 
than 40 percent of the nation's cable households. The deal would 
also face regulatory scrutiny. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T's cash and stock bid values MediaOne at $87.375 per share.  
In Wednesday's trading on the New York Stock Exchange, MediaOne 
fell $1.75 per share to $80.06 1/4. The first-quarter report was 
released after the close of trading. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
