<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China: Surplus Pushing Prices Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Rising surpluses in agricultural goods and  
industrial products threaten to push prices lower this year as 
Chinese consumers limit their spending, Chinese economic officials 
said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The government found nearly all of 606 types of commodities it  
surveyed -- most of them industrial goods -- were in oversupply, Ding 
Junfa, deputy director of the State Administration of Internal 
Trade, told reporters at a news conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Although industrial production and retail sales grew at a brisk  
pace in the first quarter of this year, retail and consumer prices 
have continued to fall, reflecting the overhang in inventories, 
Ding said. 
</P>
<P>
	China's retail sales rose 7.4 percent and value-added industrial  
output increased 10.1 percent in the first quarter, compared with 
the same quarter last year. But China's retail price index dropped 
2.9 percent in the first quarter from the year-earlier period 
following monthly declines for more than a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Slowing growth in both urban and rural incomes has contributed  
to sluggish consumption rates, Ding said. In addition, consumers 
are saving more money to deal with rising educational and medical 
costs. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, consumers have been holding off on buying products,  
expecting prices to fall even more, he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Savings in China's banks surged 18.8 percent in the first  
quarter to $698.9 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Even the government's food storage system, aimed at stabilizing  
prices of key agricultural products such as grain and meat, has had 
limited success in halting the fall in prices because of 
mismanagement and graft at local levels, Ding said. 
</P>
<P>
	He predicted that prices will pick up a bit because of the  
government's fiscal spending measures and new consumer loans being 
offered by banks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
