<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 05:35:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Congress May Act on Minimum Wage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Calling it the ``wrong thing'' to do, House  
Majority Leader Dick Armey conceded Tuesday that Congress may act 
this year to raise the minimum wage. 
</P>
<P>
	As the House held its first hearing on the issue since the  
Republican takeover of Capitol Hill four years ago, Armey, R-Texas, 
acknowledged that a minimum wage increase has support among members 
of both parties. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will find a way to deal with it, if it becomes necessary to  
do the wrong thing in the least hurtful manner possible,'' said 
Armey, a former economics professor who vehemently opposes a 
federally mandated floor on hourly wages. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats, led by Sen. Edward Kennedy of Massachusetts and Rep.  
David Bonior of Michigan, are pushing to phase in a $1 increase to 
$6.15 an hour over two years. The last wage hike, 90 cents an hour 
was implemented in two stages, in 1996 and 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton called for a minimum wage increase in his  
State of the Union message and Democrats are aiming to make the 
issue a political one going into the 2000 election season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Really, my friends, this is not an academic debate,'' Labor  
Secretary Alexis Herman said during a Capitol news conference. 
``This is really about paying the rent. It's about buying clothes 
for the kids and putting food on the table.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But GOP-called witnesses Tuesday at House Education and  
Workforce Committee hearing suggested another another increase 
would either trigger unemployment or push families into higher tax 
brackets, plunging some into poverty. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our estimates suggest the net effect of minimum wages is to  
increase the proportion of families that are poor,'' said Michigan 
State University economics professor David Neumark. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of phased-out welfare benefits and marginal tax rates, a  
single mother of two children might be worse off earning $25,000 
annually than $10,000 each year, said New York University law 
professor Daniel Shaviro. 
</P>
<P>
	Even under his best-case scenario -- the mother lives in a state  
that has low welfare cash-assistance payments and is not receiving 
a government housing subsidy -- such a worker would gain only about 
$26 per week, Shaviro said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Missouri Rep. William L. Clay, the panel's senior Democrat,  
said that with a booming economy, unemployment at a 30-year low and 
the Dow soaring above 10,000, there is no excuse for opposing an 
increase in the minimum wage. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we do not raise the minimum wage during this Congress, its  
buying power will lag 19 percent below what it was in 1979,'' said 
Bonior. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0156 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 14:45:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> N.Y. Times To Refuse Cigarette Ads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A decision by The New York Times to rid its  
pages of all tobacco advertising was criticized Wednesday by a 
cigarette company spokesman as a ``pathetic'' policy. 
</P>
<P>
	``Isn't it ironic that a publication that trumpets freedom of  
the press would trample on the freedom of commercial expression?'' 
asked Mark Smith, a spokesman for Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Corp., 
the third-biggest U.S. tobacco company. 
</P>
<P>
	Times publisher Arthur O. Sulzberger Jr. said that the First  
Amendment ``gives the press the right to publish what it chooses 
to. It doesn't force the press to publish something, whether that's 
a news story or an advertisement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Times decided on the ban, the first by a national newspaper,  
because of concerns about the harmful effects of smoking, New York 
Times Co. spokeswoman Nancy Nielsen said. The decision to refuse 
advertising for cigars, cigarettes and other tobacco products was 
disclosed in Wednesday's edition and takes effect Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want to expose our readers to advertising that may be  
dangerous to their health,'' Ms. Nielsen said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than a dozen other U.S. newspapers refuse to publish  
tobacco ads. 
</P>
<P>
	The Seattle Times refuses ads for tobacco, handguns and  
pornographic movies, while The News &AMP; Observer of Raleigh, N.C., 
refuses ads for bingo, fortune tellers and 900 telephone numbers, 
according to the industry's Editor &AMP; Publisher International 
Yearbook. 
</P>
<P>
	Tobacco advertising accounted for less than 1 percent of the $1  
billion in ad revenues last year at the Times. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times likely has already run its last cigarette ad. A  
full-page color ad for Carlton cigarettes ran Monday, and no others 
were scheduled before the ban takes effect. The Times, which also 
shuns ads for handguns and tear gas, will continue to accept 
tobacco company ads that don't promote smoking, such as those for 
industry-sponsored festivals. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, the tobacco industry reached a $206 billion deal with  
46 states that had sued to recover health costs associated with 
smoking. The deal bans outdoor cigarette ads and forbids ads 
targeting children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
