<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Norfolk Southern's Earnings Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORFOLK, Va. (AP) -- Norfolk Southern Corp.'s first-quarter net  
income fell 15 percent, compared with operating profits a year ago, 
as preparations to take over part of Conrail pushed profits lower. 
</P>
<P>
	The railroad said Wednesday it earned $112 million, or 30 cents  
per share, down from $132 million, or 35 cents per share, in the 
first quarter of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Norfolk Southern said its 1998 first-quarter net earnings were  
boosted by $97 million from discontinued operations, mostly on a 
gain from the sale of Norfolk Southern's North American Van Lines 
subsidiary. When that gain is included, the company's net earnings 
in the just-ended quarter fell 51.1 percent from net income of $229 
million, or 61 cents per share, from a year earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	First-quarter earnings in 1999 continued to reflect the  
investments Norfolk Southern is making to integrate Conrail into 
its system, said David R. Goode, chairman, president and chief 
executive officer. Those investments affect the bottom line in the 
short term but will pay off in the long term, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Norfolk Southern expects to take over 58 percent of  
Philadelphia-based Conrail on June 1. Richmond-based CSX Corp. will 
control the rest in a $10.3 billion deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The earnings came on railway operating revenues of $1.03  
billion, down 3 percent from $1.07 billion the same quarter a year 
ago because of a depressed export coal market. 
</P>
<P>
	Railway operating expenses were $793 million for the quarter,  
down 3 percent from $815 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The restructuring of Conrail will introduce competition to  
several Northeastern markets for the first time since 1976, when 
Conrail began operating as a monopoly that Congress created out of 
six bankrupt railroads. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
