<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	House Wants Input on Ground Troops  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In a challenge to President Clinton over  
Kosovo, a divided House voted to limit his authority to use ground 
forces. The Republican-sponsored measure would require Clinton to 
obtain congressional approval before sending ``ground elements'' to 
Yugoslavia. However, Senate Foreign Relations Committee Chairman 
Jesse Helms, R-N.C., scheduled a hearing before his panel for 
tomorrow to vote on a measure by a bipartisan group of senators to 
authorize Clinton to use ``all means necessary,'' including ground 
troops, to prosecute the war. 

</P>
<P>
	Outspoken Yugoslav Premier Fired  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Slobodan Milosevic's regime fired a  
deputy premier today who suggested Belgrade was ready to accept key 
NATO demands for ending the crippling air campaign. Vuk Draskovic 
was dismissed because of ``public statements which were contrary to 
the government stands,'' the state-run Tanjug news agency said. The 
firing came the same day that NATO said it was seeing signs of 
serious discontent inside Yugoslavia. Draskovic had said the 
Yugoslav leadership should stop lying to its people about the 
situation in the country after weeks of bombings and recognize ``we 
cannot defeat NATO.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Klebold Girlfriend Bought Three Guns  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- Authorities further linked an  
18-year-old student to the Columbine High School gunmen, saying she 
bought three of the four guns used in the massacre. Investigators 
had said gunman Dylan Klebold's girlfriend, Robyn Anderson, bought 
two shotguns and a rifle last fall. A semiautomatic TEC DC-9 
handgun used in the attack has not yet been traced. Authorities 
have repeatedly said Anderson is considered a witness and not a 
suspect. A sheriff's spokesman also reaffirmed that three young men 
detained near the school shortly after the attack had been cleared 
of any involvement. 

</P>
<P>
	Two Students Shot in Canada School  
</P>
<P>
	TABER, Alberta (AP) -- One student was killed and another wounded  
today when a gunman opened fire at a high school in the Canadian 
province of Alberta. Other students said the shooter carried a 
.22-caliber rifle and they identified him as a former student at 
the school. A police spokeswoman confirmed two boys were shot at 
W.R. Myers High School, but gave no details. A secretary at the 
school said one person was in custody. 

</P>
<P>
	Govt.: Scientist Took Nuke Data  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A scientist suspected of spying for China  
began transferring top-secret nuclear weapons data from a highly 
restricted computer system as early as 1983, government officials 
said today. However, most of the transfers took place in 1994-95. 
Lee has been the target of an FBI investigation at Los Alamos since 
1996 after authorities became concerned that critical information 
about one of the W-88 warhead might have been obtained by the 
Chinese in the 1980s. 

</P>
<P>
	Starr Not Allowed To Interview Jury  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- In another setback for Kenneth Starr, a  
federal judge ruled today prosecutors cannot interview jurors who 
refused to convict Susan McDougal in her recent criminal trial. 
U.S. District Judge George Howard Jr. concluded Starr's office had 
not shown ``good cause'' for the court to make an exception to a 
policy of ``not invading the province of the jury.'' The jury 
acquitted McDougal on an obstruction of justice charge but 
deadlocked on two counts of criminal contempt for refusing to 
testify in the Whitewater probe. Prosecutors had said the jury 
interviews would influence their decision on a retrial. 

</P>
<P>
	IMF To Resume Lending to Russia  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The International Monetary Fund announced late  
today it had reached an agreement in principle with Russia on a new 
economic reform program. IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus 
said negotiations had resolved the major issues that had prevented 
the IMF from resuming a lending program cut off in August when 
Russia defaulted on billions of dollars in foreign debt. After a 
few ``technical elements'' are resolved, Camdessus said he would 
take the request for loan approval to the board and expected 
endorsement for $4.5 billion in new IMF loans. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Mixed; Dow Closes Up 13.74  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices were mixed today but the Dow  
industrials gained 13.74 to close at 10,845.45, another record 
high. On the NYSE, advancers led decliners 1,752-1,281. The Nasdaq 
fell 52.04 to 2,550.37. 

</P>
<P>
	Baffert Picks Derby Post Positions  
</P>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Bob Baffert's three-pronged assault on an  
unprecedented third straight Kentucky Derby victory will be 
launched from farther out than his first two. Baffert chose the 
sixth post for the filly Excellent Meeting, No. 14 for Prime Timber 
and No. 15 for General Challenge. Baffert's first Derby winner, 
Silver Charm, started from the No. 5 post in 1997, while Real Quiet 
started from the No. 3 post in 1998. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SAMANTHA CRITCHELL  
</P>
</TEXT>
