<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marine Navigator Gets Immunity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A judge granted immunity today to a  
Marine navigator for his testimony at the obstruction of justice 
trial of his crewmate, the pilot of a jet that clipped an Italian 
ski lift cable and killed 20 people. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilot, Capt. Richard Ashby, admitted during his manslaughter  
trial in March that he helped hide a videotape shot during the 
flight before his EA-6B Prowler struck the cable on Feb. 3, 1998. 
Ashby was acquitted of the manslaughter charges. 
</P>
<P>
	The navigator, Capt. Joseph Schweitzer, pleaded guilty to the  
charges Ashby now faces, said in his request for immunity that he 
didn't want his testimony to result in further charges against him. 
Schweitzer was ordered dismissed from the Marine Corps. 
</P>
<P>
	Col. Alvin Keller, the military judge, granted Schweitzer's  
request before opening statements were to begin for Ashby's trial 
today. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer said he threw the tape into a bonfire because he  
feared a frame on it of his smiling face might be used to vilify 
him and the rest of the crew in the Italian media. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer's lawyer, Maj. Eric Veit, said his client needed  
immunity because there is a chance his guilty plea could be 
overturned on appeal. The defense is concerned that a reversal 
might lead prosecutors to charge Schweitzer with impeding an 
administrative proceeding. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want this thing to end and I don't want to revisit it,''  
Schweitzer said. ``The issue here is what will happen two to three 
years from now. All I want is closure.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer said he will testify to the same facts as he did at  
his own sentencing hearing. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer, 31, of Westbury, N.Y., testified he used the camera  
three times during the flight through the Alps but wasn't sure that 
he ever recorded images because he didn't know how to use it. The 
camera belonged to Ashby. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors had argued that Schweitzer's plea agreement didn't  
include a grant of immunity and required him to testify truthfully, 
both at his sentencing last month and at Ashby's trial. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 05:35:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Six Leading Dancers Shine at Ballet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- For an evening to be gala, American Ballet  
Theater presented the right mix for springtime cum opening night: a 
lavish, three-act ballet ``Don Quixote'' with a pair of principals 
for each act. 
</P>
<P>
	All six leading dancers -- Paloma Herrera with Angel Corella,  
Susan Jaffe with Jose Manuel Carreno and Nina Ananiashvili with 
Julio Bocca -- were more than splendid on Monday night at the 
Metropolitan Opera. There was plenty of bravura for all and, 
dancing in only one act, no one held back. All the men, dazzling, 
high-jumping virtuosos, also were considerate partners. 
</P>
<P>
	Though titled ``Don Quixote,'' the ballet features the don  
(danced by Victor Barbee) as only a minor character, along with 
Sancho Panza (Gil Boggs), Kitri's rich old suitor (Guillaume 
Graffin) and her father (Ethan Brown). 
</P>
<P>
	The leading characters are Kitri and Basil, the poor barber in  
love with her. In Act 1, in the village square, Herrera and Corella 
were fleet, fast and flirty. The audience warmed to their youth and 
-- when they stopped trying to make each other jealous by flirting 
with others -- their ardor. 
</P>
<P>
	Act 2 has three scenes. The central one follows some lively  
dances at a gypsy camp and features Don Quixote's dream of 
beautiful ballerinas, with Kitri dancing solo. Jaffe, who has 
incredible balance for solo steps requiring a stop and staying 
motionless on one toe, was chosen for Act 2, along with the 
exciting Carreno. 
</P>
<P>
	Ananiashvili and Bocco, who have already achieved the stardom  
that the other principals are approaching, danced the final act, 
``The Wedding.'' Choreography by Marius Petipa and Alexander Gorsky 
builds the ballet's most dramatic pas de deux with variations of 
increasing excitement. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don Quixote'' includes a matador, traditionally part of the  
colorful background along with the gypsies, villagers, flower 
girls. But Maxim Belotserkovsky, partnering Irina Dvorovenko, made 
it much more. That couple, in the opening night gala, must be 
elevated for praise alongside the three principal couples. Though 
some of the matador's gestures might look effete, Belotserkovsky 
made them look macho. 
</P>
<P>
	The Imperial Russian Ballet performed the premiere of ``Don  
Quixote'' in 1869. ABT placed it in its repertoire in 1978. This, 
its third production, was staged in 1995 by artistic director Kevin 
McKenzie and ballet master Susan Jones. Ermanno Florio conducted 
the melodic Ludwig Minkus music. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the dancing began, Caroline Kennedy, cochairman of the  
gala with Blaine Trump, recalled a dress rehearsal by Ballet 
Theater in 1962 at the White House. Now, like her mother taking her 
to performances in New York, she takes her daughter. ``Love of the 
arts,'' she said, speaking from the stage, ``is one of the most 
special gifts we can give our children.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
