<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Pastor Officiating Colo. Funerals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- With his third funeral just behind him  
and his fourth just ahead, the Rev. Billy Epperhart was feeling 
overwhelmed like never before. 
</P>
<P>
	For days, in a soft southern accent and a crisp black suit, he  
has been a pillar of public strength, ministering to hundreds of 
mourners in the aftermath of last week's Columbine High School 
shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	In private, he wipes away tears and cannot finish sentences.  
</P>
<P>
	``When you go through this many funerals and meetings with  
families, it makes it all real,'' the 43-year-old pastor said 
Tuesday. ``You know, death is all so real.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Normally, Epperhart's warehouse-like evangelical church, Trinity  
Christian Center, is a place where members occasionally speak in 
tongues and perform a ``laying on of hands'' to cure physical and 
emotional ailments. 
</P>
<P>
	But during the past week it has become a place where families of  
all denominations, or no denomination at all, celebrate the life of 
loved ones they lost. And at the podium is Epperhart, trying to 
make sense of it. 
</P>
<P>
	By night, he writes funeral speeches with other pastors' help.  
By day, he consoles parents and listens to stories of lost 
children, sweet smiles and funny moments, stories of innocence and 
potential. He puts the memories into speeches that he delivers as 
caskets are lowered into the earth. 
</P>
<P>
	Death means something to everyone, he says -- everyone except  
Dylan Klebold and Eric Harris, the two teen-agers who killed 12 
students, a teacher and themselves in a hail of gunfire and 
explosives April 20. 
</P>
<P>
	``Death to these kids was not a real thing. It couldn't have  
been,'' the pastor said. 
</P>
<P>
	A funeral typically has one director and one, maybe two  
assistants. Since the shootings, Trinity Christian has been using 
five full-time pastors and 40 ushers, many wearing walkie-talkie 
headsets to coordinate parking, media access and crowd control. 
</P>
<P>
	Epperhart, a pastor for 21 years who heard ``the call of the  
ministry'' in Texas at age 10, is taking pains to avoid turning the 
Columbine funerals into pulpits condemning school violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, he tries to shape them into intensely personal  
experiences that bring grieving families together both physically 
and spiritually. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can be in a crowd of people and still be lonely,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Epperhart has seen tragedy in his church before. More than a  
decade ago, a mentally unstable man burned down his church in 
Alexander, La., forcing him to deliver sermons under a tent. 
</P>
<P>
	Nothing, however, compares to last week.  
</P>
<P>
	``I've never seen grief and shock like this in my life,''  
Epperhart said. ``It's cliche, really, but it's kind of true: You 
have to really come together. And in times like this, barriers 
really drop.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
