<HEADLINE> K.C. Wizards Hire Former U.S. Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Bob Gansler, coach of the 1990 U.S.  
World Cup team, was hired today as coach of the winless Kansas City 
Wizards of Major League Soccer. 
</P>
<P>
	Gansler succeeds interim coach Ken Fogarty, who took over when  
Ron Newman resigned April 14. Kansas City was 0-4 under Newman and 
0-2 under Fogarty, who will coach today's game while Gansler 
observes. 
</P>
<P>
	Gansler takes over a team that won the MLS Western Conference in  
1997 but fell to last in 1998. The Wizards had scored only two 
goals this season heading into today's home game against the 
Columbus Crew. 
</P>
<P>
	Gansler, a 57-year-old native Hungarian, grew up in Milwaukee.  
He made 25 appearances for the Olympic and U.S. national team in 
1968-69 and was captain of the U.S. Olympic teams in 1964 and 1968. 
He led the U.S. team to a 14-16-6 record from 1989 to 1991 and also 
coached the national team for one game, a win, in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. team went 0-3 in Rome at the World Cup.  
</P>
<P>
	Most recently, he coached the Milwaukee Rampage of the A-League,  
a second-division professional league. The Rampage won the 1997 
title, but Gansler was dismissed after the 1998 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Gansler also has coached the U.S. under-20 national team, the  
World University team, the U.S. under-19 national team and the 
University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee. 
</P>
<P>
	Tony Meola, the Wizards' injured goalkeeper, started all three  
World Cup games for Gansler in 1990. Kansas City midfielder Chris 
Henderson was on the roster but did not play. 
</P>
</TEXT>
