<HEADLINE> Pa. Sheriff To Disband Posse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEDFORD, Pa. (AP) -- A Pennsylvania sheriff who says he can't  
keep his posse of mounted volunteers corralled is disbanding the 
group. 
</P>
<P>
	``They try to operate on their own without letting me know what  
they're doing,'' Sheriff James Wright said of the Bedford County 
Sheriff's Posse, a brigade of 23 volunteers who help with searches, 
rescues and security. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright has told posse members to turn in their badges, but they  
don't understand the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have never done anything to harm anyone,'' said posse  
member Bill King. ``We've just done a lot for the county and the 
people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The posse was formed 12 years ago in this south-central  
Pennsylvania region to provide free help on horseback. 
</P>
<P>
	Lyn Yokum, vice president of the group, said Wright's pique at  
the posse's endeavors has turned into a ``grudge match,'' a charge 
Wright denied. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no personality conflict whatsoever,'' Wright said.  
``The conflict is doing this work on their own without me knowing 
anything about it. The liability falls back on the sheriff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bedford County commissioners plan to meet with Wright and posse  
members in May to resolve the dispute. Commissioner Gary Ebersole 
said that he knows of no complaints that the posse has been out of 
control, rude or rowdy. 
</P>
<P>
	And since the posse is a nonprofit group that doesn't work for  
Wright, the sheriff may not have the authority to disband it, 
Ebersole said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
