<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Icahn Withdraws RJR Board Nominees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financier Carl Icahn will not pursue a proxy  
fight over RJR Nabisco Holdings Corp.'s decision to spin off its 
U.S. tobacco operations as a separate company owned by RJR 
shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	Icahn said in a statement late Tuesday that he made his decision  
to withdraw his slate of board nominees after discussions with 
several other large shareholders, who said they did not want to 
delay the decision to spin off the companies in light of a recent 
Supreme Court decision to hear arguments on whether the federal 
Food and Drug Administration should be allowed to regulate tobacco. 
</P>
<P>
	RJR shareholders are scheduled to vote on the spinoff at the  
company's May 12 annual meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	RJR Nabisco, which was the target in the biggest and most  
dramatic takeover battle of the 1980s, owns the nation's 
second-biggest tobacco company that is led by the Winston, Salem 
and Camel cigarette brands. 
</P>
<P>
	It also owns an 80.6 percent stake in Nabisco Holdings Corp.,  
which is traded separately and is the nation's biggest cookie and 
cracker maker with brands such as Oreos, Chips Ahoy, Snackwells and 
Ritz. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Icahn and RJR management feel the food company would fare  
better in the stock market if its ties were severed to the tobacco 
business which faces hundreds of lawsuits. But they had disagree 
over how to make the split leading Icahn to file a competing slate 
of candidates for the RJR board. 
</P>
<P>
	Icahn had said earlier his slate consisted of people whose main  
ambition would be to spin off the food business and, if that were 
blocked, try the tobacco spinoff that RJR had proposed. 
</P>
<P>
	In the statement, Icahn reiterated his belief that his plan to  
spinoff Nabisco from RJR Holdings was the best way to go, but 
backed down after talking to other shareholders who said they would 
support the tobacco spinoff. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
