<DOCNO> APW19990428.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 12:25:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Plan Raises Hopes for Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Over the past month, Japan has loaned $400 million  
to Indonesian power companies, hundreds of millions more to build 
railways and roads in Malaysia, and $1 billion for South Korea to 
use pretty much however it sees fit. 
</P>
<P>
	It's all part of the ``Miyazawa Initiative,'' a $30 billion loan  
package Japan hopes will help Asia climb out of its financial 
crisis and boost this country's stature as the region's economic 
leader. 
</P>
<P>
	The initiative indicates a mix of Japan's increased desire to  
exert influence on the world stage and frustration throughout Asia 
with the way the West has tried to deal with the nearly two-year 
old crisis in Asian economies. 
</P>
<P>
	And though the initiative was initially met with caution, it is  
now winning kudos. 
</P>
<P>
	``The plan has helped stabilize the situation in Asia,'' said  
Robert Alan Feldman, an economist for Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. 
``Japan has been very serious in trying to help the Asian countries 
overcome some of their difficulties.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Japan's motives aren't purely altruistic, of course.  
</P>
<P>
	Asia's only economic giant hopes that by helping its neighbors  
it can also help itself. A recovery in the region would undoubtedly 
spur business for Japanese firms. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, Japan has long been eager to assume a larger economic  
leadership role in the region, and the Miyazawa plan is seen as an 
attempt to put more control of Asian economies in Asian hands. 
</P>
<P>
	In particular, leaders in Japan, Indonesia and elsewhere in the  
region have harshly criticized International Monetary Fund bailouts 
for Thailand, South Korea and Indonesia, which they say only made 
matters worse. 
</P>
<P>
	They argue conditions imposed by the IMF, such as interest rate  
hikes and spending cuts, were too strict for wobbling economies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Asian countries, to be frank, are disappointed with the  
behavior of the IMF,'' said Kiyoshi Miura, chief economist at the 
Institute for International Monetary Affairs in Tokyo. ``Now is a 
very good time for Japan to take a bigger role.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The aid package, named for Japanese Finance Minister Kiichi  
Miyazawa, was first drafted in October, but the lending hasn't 
gathered momentum until recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, more than half the money, or $16.6 billion, has been  
appropriated to five crisis-struck nations -- South Korea, Thailand, 
Malaysia, the Philippines, and Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	In Manila, Japanese funds will be included in a $300 million  
loan by the Asian Development Bank to help combat air pollution. 
Thailand's Health Ministry, meanwhile, will use small chunk of the 
$1.85 billion allotted the country to hire local villagers as 
temporary rat catchers. 
</P>
<P>
	South Korea will get the biggest share -- $8.35 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	In contrast to the IMF, Japan has imposed few conditions on the  
loans. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the money will flow to the cash-strapped countries  
through local institutions such as the Korean Development Bank. And 
although there have been a few exceptions, Japan has mostly left it 
up to those institutions to decide how to disburse the money. 
</P>
<P>
	This is a departure for Tokyo.  
</P>
<P>
	Past Japanese development programs have often been criticized  
for their stringent conditions, especially for requirements that 
Japanese firms be hired for big parts of any project. 
</P>
<P>
	Stock markets throughout the region have rebounded strongly this  
year as investors bet the worst of the crisis is over. 
</P>
<P>
	Economists generally agree that the Japanese loans are one  
reason for the growing confidence, but many believe the 
IMF-encouraged reforms are actually a bigger factor. 
</P>
<P>
	And a good deal of the Miyazawa money will be needed just to  
repair the damage Japan has caused in the region as its own slow 
growth has dragged on neighboring economies. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Tokyo's help is being felt -- and appreciated.  
</P>
<P>
	``We have done quite well,'' Malaysian Second Finance Minister  
Datuk Mustapa Mohamad told the Malaysian newspaper Business Times 
after securing a $700 million yen loan from Japan early this month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
