<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft Sues 15 Florida Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Microsoft Corp., the world's leading software  
maker, is suing 15 Florida companies, alleging that they sold or 
installed illegal copies of its programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other companies are under investigation, police said  
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuits are the latest move in Microsoft's nationwide  
crackdown on software pirates. The suits seek unspecified damages 
and a judge's order to stop distribution of the software, said 
corporate attorney Nick Psyhogeos. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft has taken similar actions in New York, New Jersey,  
Pennsylvania, Ohio, Virginia, Maryland, California, Illinois, 
Minnesota and Alabama. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft claims that software piracy cost Florida 7,186 jobs in  
1997 and $490 million in lost wages, tax revenue and retail sales. 
Microsoft isn't able to estimate how much software piracy costs the 
company, but it's a $2 billion-a-year problem for the industry, a 
company spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Software pirates often sell programs for 50 percent of the  
average retail value, and some for as low as 10 percent, Psyhogeos 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The actions come as the company fights federal charges that it  
illegally wields its Windows monopoly to stifle competition in the 
technology industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0181 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 22:52:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Prostate Cancer Screening Faulted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- After reviewing the results of prostate biopsies  
performed in the mid-1990s, a suburban hospital found that 20 men 
were misdiagnosed and suffer from cancer they were told they did 
not have. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel shock, anger, disbelief -- there's nothing we can do,''  
said the wife of one misdiagnosed patient, requesting that the 
family's identity and hometown be kept anonymous. ``We don't know 
what's going to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said her 62-year-old husband was told two weeks ago by  
Sturdy Memorial Hospital that his test had been inaccurately 
reported by a former pathologist. Since then, her husband has been 
told to seek aggressive radiation therapy. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the errors, the cancer was left undiagnosed and  
untreated in the 20 men for some time, perhaps lowering their 
chances of survival. 
</P>
<P>
	The hospital 30 miles south of Boston planned a news conference  
for today to discuss the biopsies. 
</P>
<P>
	The flawed exams were performed between January 1995 and  
December 1997, The Sun Chronicle of Attleboro reported this week. 
Sturdy Memorial has said it reviewed 279 tests and discovered that 
20 were botched. Two of the 20 men have apparently died of 
unrelated causes, the hospital told the newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at Sturdy Memorial would not release the conditions of  
the other misdiagnosed men, nor elaborate on what triggered the 
review of the tests. 
</P>
<P>
	The mistakes are under investigation by the state's Department  
of Public Health and Board of Registration in Medicine. Both groups 
refused comment Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The tests were supposed to detect malignant cells in the  
prostate, a walnut-sized organ in men located just below the 
bladder. 
</P>
<P>
	Approximately 179,000 men are diagnosed with prostate cancer  
nationwide every year. About 37,000 men die of the disease each 
year, according to the American Cancer Society. 
</P>
<P>
	The five-year survival rate in men whose cancer is detected  
early and has not spread is nearly 99 percent, said Kara Smigel, a 
spokeswoman for the National Cancer Institute. If the cancer has 
spread to bones or organs, that figure drops to 32 percent, she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	At least one recent cancer misdiagnosis case resulted in  
criminal action. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, a Wisconsin laboratory pleaded no contest to reckless  
homicide after failing to find obvious signs of cancer in Pap 
smears of two women who later died. Lawsuits against the lab, 
health maintenance organization and individuals were settled for 
$9.8 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
