<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 15:05:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sabres Flying High After Sweep </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Fore! The Buffalo Sabres can go golfing  
this week. 
</P>
<P>
	But that doesn't mean they're finished playing hockey.  
</P>
<P>
	It just means they'll be teeing off on the front nine instead of  
on opposing goaltenders for a few days. 
</P>
<P>
	Thanks to a swift and stunning playoff sweep of second-seeded  
Ottawa, the Sabres can keep their drivers in the same bag with 
their hockey sticks while awaiting the next Stanley Cup round. 
</P>
<P>
	``I might play a round or two,'' Sabres forward Brian Holzinger,  
who scored twice in Game 3, said during a day off Wednesday. ``But 
the main thing is we have time to nurse some injuries and heal up 
while watching the other teams beat up on one another.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vaclav Varada's two goals and Dominik Hasek's 40 saves sank the  
Senators 4-3 in the Eastern Conference quarterfinals Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The win triggered a shower of brooms onto the ice and sent the  
Sabres out of the gate as the playoffs' lead dark horse. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years the Sabres got used to playing golf while other  
teams were still playing hockey. Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff, a former 
Sabres captain, recalls seven first-round exits between 1984 and 
1993. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was something that I waited to see a long time, both as a  
former player and now as a coach, to see the fans get to celebrate 
after a series victory,'' Ruff said. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year the Sabres upset Philadelphia and swept Montreal, both  
on the road. Buffalo then fell to Washington in the conference 
final, losing the last game at home. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres spoke confidently going into the series with Ottawa,  
but some of them shuddered. The Northeast Division rivals were 
mired in five overtimes during the season. Four games ended in 
ties; the Senators won the other. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was extremely scared before this series started,'' said  
Sabres wing Dixon Ward, who assisted on both of Varada's goals in 
Game 4. ``I didn't want to play Ottawa, I'll be honest with you. 
But as the series went along we just gained more confidence. We 
seemed to get better and found ways to win games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres stole the first game in Ottawa and outlasted the  
Senators in double overtime in Game 2. Anchored by Hasek and 
propelled by an aggressive offense, they outplayed the Senators in 
Buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres also held Senators star Alexei Yashin to no points in  
the series despite Yashin's team-leading nine shots Tuesday. 
Buffalo captain Michael Peca and Varada did most of the work on the 
frustrated Yashin. 
</P>
<P>
	The acrobatic Hasek did all but stand on his head to make the  
difference in the first game and allowed six goals on 162 shots in 
the series. 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek allowed nine goals in three straight losses to the  
Capitals in last year's conference finals. This season he had a 
strong start and faltered before a groin injury sidelined him for 
12 games between February and March. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a little hungrier this time,'' Ward said. ``He had a  
little more rest down the stretch this year. And he's extremely 
focused on trying to prove a few naysayers wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not trying to prove anything to anyone,'' Hasek said.  
``I'm just trying to win games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the series against Ottawa, the Sabres got more of what helped  
them throughout the regular season, such as Hasek's good 
goaltending, plus something they lacked -- scoring. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine Sabres scored goals against the Senators and 14 finished  
with points. Alexei Zhitnik, Varada and Rasmussen, a rookie who 
shuttled between Buffalo and Rochester during the season, all 
scored their first goals in the series Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We talked about scoring by committee and that's just what we  
needed, especially with Miro out of the lineup,'' Rasmussen said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're playing real well right now,'' Holzinger said, adding  
that the Sabres will have to find some way to stay sharp as they 
await their next playoff foe. 
</P>
<P>
	``The coaches will make sure we're ready to go,'' Holzinger  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The injured include the Sabres' top scorer, Miroslav Satan, who  
bruised his foot when a teammate's shot struck him during in 
Sunday's Game 3. X-rays were negative, but Satan, a 40-goal scorer, 
was reduced to hobbling around on crutches for a couple days. 
``He's off the crutches now,'' Holzinger said. 
</P>
<P>
	Geoff Sanderson, who injured some ligaments in his hand when he  
was slashed in a game recently, is likely to return for the next 
round. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
