<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Infinity Beats Wall Street Forecasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Infinity Broadcasting Corp. earned $48 million  
in the first three months of 1999, edging Wall Street's forecasts 
in the radio company's first full quarter since its partial spinoff 
by CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	The profit by the operator of 160 radio stations and a major  
billboard business represented a 55 percent improvement over 
Infinity's earnings as a unit of CBS in the same period last year, 
before last June's acquisition of American Radio Systems. 
</P>
<P>
	On a per-share basis, Infinity earned 6 cents, up from 4 cents  
in the first quarter of 1998 and a penny better than what most 
analysts expected, according to a survey by First Call. 
</P>
<P>
	First-quarter revenues, including those from the American Radio  
System, totaled $474 million. That's an increase of about 16 
percent from the combined revenues of Infinity and ARS in the first 
quarter last year, when they were still separate entities. 
</P>
<P>
	Infinity, still about 82 percent owned by CBS, attributed the  
improvement to strong revenues from both radio and billboard 
advertising, as well as the addition of ARS. 
</P>
<P>
	``Infinity continues to benefit from new Internet-related  
advertising on its radio stations and outdoor advertising venues, 
and also will benefit from its participation in the developing 
position CBS enjoys on the Internet,'' said Mel Karmazin, chief 
executive of both Infinity and CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	In December, CBS sold 140 million shares of Infinity, its most  
profitable division, for $20.50 apiece, in an initial public 
offering of stock that raised $2.87 billion. CBS had acquired 
Infinity for $3.9 billion two years earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Since the IPO, Infinity's stock has risen as high as $33.50 per  
share. On Wednesday, the shares fell $1.12 1/2 to $27 on the New York 
Stock Exchange. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
