<HEADLINE> Arrested Nanny Pleads Innocent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORWALK, Conn. (AP) -- A nanny caught on videotape kicking,  
hitting and tossing children in her care has pleaded innocent to 
criminal charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Joan Kahn, 59, a nanny for two families, was charged April 16  
with two counts of risk of injury to a minor. She entered her plea 
Monday and was freed on $50,000 bail. 
</P>
<P>
	The father of an 11-month-old boy arranged to have a camera  
hidden in a clock in his home after he found his son and a 
10-month-old girl in Kahn's care with dirty diapers and unexplained 
bruises. 
</P>
<P>
	The video showed the nanny repeatedly hitting, kicking and  
tossing the children. At one point, Kahn lifted the boy and slammed 
him face-down onto her thigh, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kahn initially denied hitting the children, but when she watched  
the video, she told police she didn't remember hitting the 
toddlers, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	The families received the hidden camera from Know Your Nanny, a  
New Jersey company that checks out nannies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
