<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Releases Microsoft Testimony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- While Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates parried  
with government antitrust lawyers, two of his biggest rivals opened 
secret negotiations that led to America Online's nearly $10 billion 
purchase of Netscape, an executive involved in those talks 
disclosed Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The court where Microsoft is fighting its antitrust case also  
released 684 pages of transcripts showing Gates, the world's 
wealthiest person with an estimated $41 billion in stock, 
struggling with government questions during his three days of 
depositions last August. 
</P>
<P>
	Roughly one-third of that testimony was previously shown on  
video as part of the trial, but a federal appeals court ordered the 
rest released Wednesday -- along with almost 10,000 pages of other 
depositions, including those from some of the high-tech industry's 
most famous executives. 
</P>
<P>
	As in portions of his interview already played in the courtroom,  
Gates can be seen carefully parsing questions put to him by 
government lawyers, who quickly grow frustrated. Tempers rose. 
</P>
<P>
	``I must say I think your answers are nonresponsive and  
rambling,'' said Stephen Houck, the lead lawyer for the 20 states 
suing Microsoft along with the Justice Department. ``And if that 
continues to be the case, I'm just letting you know this is going 
to take much longer than I would have hoped.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The questioning continued for 19 1/2 more hours.  
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, a Microsoft lawyer questioned Peter Currie,  
Netscape's former chief financial officer, who helped put together 
the company's sale to AOL, which was finalized last month for $9.9 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson previously agreed to  
allow Microsoft to gather evidence about the sale's implications on 
the trial, saying the deal ``might be a very significant change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Government lawyers contend that Microsoft illegally forces  
consumers who buy its dominant Windows computer operating system 
also to use its bundled Internet browser, discouraging people from 
using rival Web software, such as Netscape's. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft argues that the lucrative sale of Netscape undermines  
charges that Netscape was any kind of victim and that competition 
within the industry is thriving. 
</P>
<P>
	AOL, with nearly 17 million subscribers, is the world's largest  
Internet provider. Netscape produces popular Web browsing software 
and owns Netcenter, one of the most successful sites on the 
Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	Currie testified that discussions between AOL and Netscape  
started in late August, but the sale wasn't publicly acknowledged 
until November. Government lawyers also questioned Gates in late 
August. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft attorney Michael Lacovara asked whether Netscape,  
which supports the government's case, considered how the deal might 
affect the outcome of the trial, which started in October. 
</P>
<P>
	``My recollection was that there was a brief discussion whether  
it May but that we need to make decisions about the business and 
treat the trial as a separate issue,'' Currie said. ``And I have to 
say, there were very few people who were focused on the trial.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He could not remember specific discussions about the deal's  
impact on Microsoft, but he said Netscape realized the software 
giant wouldn't be pleased. 
</P>
<P>
	``AOL was willing to secure the animus of Microsoft,'' Currie  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the companies apparently cast an eye toward the courtroom.  
Currie said the sale seemed ``on quite a fast time frame'' until 
the trial started -- and executives from AOL and Netscape were the 
first witnesses for the government -- when the deal ``went on 
hiatus, when nothing happened for weeks and weeks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The secret negotiations resumed closer to November. Lacovara  
said the apparent code name chosen for Microsoft in the deal was 
Mars, the Roman god of war. 
</P>
<P>
	The Microsoft trial currently is in recess and is not expected  
to resume before the middle of next month. 

</P>
</TEXT>
