<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mich. To Begin Welfare Drug Testing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LANSING, Mich. (AP) -- Welfare applicants in three areas of  
Michigan will be required to take drug tests before receiving 
benefits under a new state law that takes effect this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilot program to begin Oct. 1 is believed to be the first in  
the nation to require drug tests of all applicants at specified 
welfare offices, said Bill Kordenbrock, an official with the state 
Family Independence Agency, which administers welfare benefits. 
</P>
<P>
	The testing is needed to make sure drug use doesn't provide a  
stumbling block to moving off welfare, said Gov. John Engler, who 
signed the bill into law Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``For some ... substance abuse remains a barrier to  
independence,'' he said. ``This program will help us identify these 
individuals and provide them with the incentive to change their 
lives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the plan, Michigan will use Medicaid funds to provide  
treatment for those who screen positive for drugs. Anyone refusing 
treatment will face at least a partial loss of welfare benefits, 
and applicants who refuse to take the test will have their benefits 
denied. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials have not determined which areas of the state will take  
part. 
</P>
<P>
	Civil liberties groups and welfare advocates have said  
across-the-board drug testing of anyone who applies for welfare 
unfairly discriminates against the poor. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Governor Engler was truly concerned about making sure  
welfare applicants could get jobs, he would also be looking at 
factors such as alcohol abuse, and literacy and homelessness,'' 
said Wendy Wagenheim of the American Civil Liberties Union in 
Michigan. ``This is just one, and it's strictly punitive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new law requires drug tests to be given to welfare  
applicants statewide beginning April 1, 2003. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 05:26:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clemens Leaves With Stiff Hamstring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Roger Clemens' bid to become the first  
AL pitcher to win 18 straight decision ended after two innings 
Tuesday night because of stiffness in his left hamstring. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Yankees trailed the Texas Rangers 5-0 when Clemens  
did not come out to pitch the bottom of the third. He was replaced 
by Hideki Irabu, who was given all the time he needed to warm up 
because an injury forced the pitching change. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens looked out of synch throughout his brief stint. He threw  
53 pitches, only 29 of them strikes. 
</P>
<P>
	The first out he recorded came on an RBI fielder's choice that  
put Texas ahead 3-0. The Rangers scored twice more before making 
another out, although it began a streak of five straight outs for 
Clemens. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens allowed five runs on four hits and two walks. He didn't  
have any strikeouts. Two starts before, he allowed seven runs in 
three innings and left trailing Baltimore 7-6 but the Yankees came 
back to win 9-7. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens, who last lost May 29 against Seattle, tied the AL win  
streak record of 17 in his previous start, which also was against 
Texas. The mark was first set by Cleveland's Johnny Allen in 
1936-37 and matched by Baltimore's Dave McNally in 1968-69. Carl 
Hubbell holds the major league record with 24, set for the New York 
Giants from 1936-37. 
</P>
<P>
	In his first attempt to add this record to his milestone-filled  
career, Clemens bought 50 tickets for friends and relatives. The 
drama was heightened by the fact the game was in his home state and 
against the team that nearly acquired him in a trade in February. 
</P>
<P>
	But the native Texan wasn't welcomed home.  
</P>
<P>
	A near sellout crowd booed Clemens in pre-game introductions and  
again while he warmed up before the first inning. They booed for a 
third time when pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre visited the mound 
during the first inning, then fans gave the Rangers a standing 
ovation after the five-run first. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens had won his last six decision against Texas since April  
1, 1996, when he was with Boston. The Rangers were the losers in 
streak wins Nos. 8 and 17. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 05:26:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Clemens Leaves With Stiff Hamstring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Roger Clemens' bid to become the first  
AL pitcher to win 18 straight decision ended after two innings 
Tuesday night because of stiffness in his left hamstring. 
</P>
<P>
	The New York Yankees trailed the Texas Rangers 5-0 when Clemens  
did not come out to pitch the bottom of the third. He was replaced 
by Hideki Irabu, who was given all the time he needed to warm up 
because an injury forced the pitching change. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens looked out of synch throughout his brief stint. He threw  
53 pitches, only 29 of them strikes. 
</P>
<P>
	The first out he recorded came on an RBI fielder's choice that  
put Texas ahead 3-0. The Rangers scored twice more before making 
another out, although it began a streak of five straight outs for 
Clemens. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens allowed five runs on four hits and two walks. He didn't  
have any strikeouts. Two starts before, he allowed seven runs in 
three innings and left trailing Baltimore 7-6 but the Yankees came 
back to win 9-7. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens, who last lost May 29 against Seattle, tied the AL win  
streak record of 17 in his previous start, which also was against 
Texas. The mark was first set by Cleveland's Johnny Allen in 
1936-37 and matched by Baltimore's Dave McNally in 1968-69. Carl 
Hubbell holds the major league record with 24, set for the New York 
Giants from 1936-37. 
</P>
<P>
	In his first attempt to add this record to his milestone-filled  
career, Clemens bought 50 tickets for friends and relatives. The 
drama was heightened by the fact the game was in his home state and 
against the team that nearly acquired him in a trade in February. 
</P>
<P>
	But the native Texan wasn't welcomed home.  
</P>
<P>
	A near sellout crowd booed Clemens in pre-game introductions and  
again while he warmed up before the first inning. They booed for a 
third time when pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre visited the mound 
during the first inning, then fans gave the Rangers a standing 
ovation after the five-run first. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens had won his last six decision against Texas since April  
1, 1996, when he was with Boston. The Rangers were the losers in 
streak wins Nos. 8 and 17. 
</P>
</TEXT>
