<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brazilian Bank Cuts Interest Rate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- The Central Bank on Wednesday cut  
the benchmark interest rate in Brazil from 34 percent to 32 
percent, citing healthy economic signs. 
</P>
<P>
	Central Bank president Arminio Fraga announced the cut at a  
press conference in Brasilia, the capital. It is the fourth time in 
five weeks the bank has lowered interest rates, which were at 45 
percent in early March. 
</P>
<P>
	During this period foreign investment has started to return, the  
currency has strengthened and inflation has declined. Recent 
figures estimate it will be in single figures in 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, there were also indications that a scandal  
involving former Central Bank president Francisco Lopes has not 
damaged foreign investors' confidence in Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sao Paulo Stock Exchange's Bovespa Index closed up 2.2  
percent. The currency, the real, also ended stronger, at 1.68 to 
the dollar compared to 1.70 a day earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Police arrested Lopes Monday after he refused to sign an  
oath to tell the truth at a Senate inquiry into alleged banking 
irregularities. He was later released on bail. 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate said Wednesday it would summon Lopes again but did  
not say when. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
