<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Make Room in Sky for 650-Seat Jet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the 1970s, young children would stand in  
fields near O'Hare airport in Chicago, watching a new aerial 
behemoth -- the Boeing 747 -- head in for a landing. 
</P>
<P>
	A jet now under design by Airbus Industrie, the world's second  
biggest aircraft maker, would dwarf the 747's capacity, while 
offering features normally found on cruise ships. 
</P>
<P>
	Airbus hasn't signed off on building the plane, but on Tuesday a  
top company executive announced that 600 people are working on 
plans for the $10 billion project, and he sounded committed to 
seeing the plane built. 
</P>
<P>
	The A-3XX, which does not yet have a complete name, would have  
an upper deck running from its cockpit to its tail, allowing it to 
seat from 550 to 650 passengers. That's up to 200 more than the 
Boeing 747, now the largest commercial plane in the sky. 
</P>
<P>
	The two stories also would open up a range of possibilities not  
fully enjoyed in commercial aircraft, including the installation of 
a gym, shops and sleeping berths. Those amenities would be 
important distractions on the plane's target routes, longhaul trips 
across the Pacific Ocean and throughout Asia. 
</P>
<P>
	``Airline productivity jumped in 1970 with the arrival of the  
Boeing 747 -- more than twice the size of its predecessor,'' Jack 
Schofield, chairman and CEO of Airbus Industrie of North America, 
told the Aero Club of Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``The time has now come for a new, larger plane to pick up the  
pace of progress,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Airbus' chief rival, the Seattle-based Boeing Co., considers the  
A-3XX a potential white elephant, costly enough to sink a company. 
On Monday, Boeing Chairman Phil Condit told shareholders at the 
company's annual meeting that Boeing has no plans for a 600-seat 
aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't think there is a market that is big enough to support  
the development of a very large airplane,'' Condit said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, Boeing continues work on two new versions of  
its 747-400: One that would extend the plane's range to about 8,000 
nautical miles, an increase of 600 miles, and another that would 
increase the passenger capacity from about 420 to over 500 people. 
</P>
<P>
	A trade publication, Aviation Week &AMP; Space Technology, also  
published drawings this week of a potential Boeing ultra-widebody, 
a three-aisle jumbo jet that would seat up to 550 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Schofield, the Airbus executive, said he is not surprised Boeing  
says there is no demand to replace 747. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have a family and you want to protect it, because the only  
other option is to spend money to develop a new plane,'' he said. 
``We, on the other hand, don't have a `queen of the sky' -- yet.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's not clear when Airbus will have its rival aircraft.  
Development of the A-3XX has been slowed by the Asian financial 
crisis, which has pushed the possible rollout date from 2003 to 
2005. Nonetheless, Schofield said Airbus has over 600 people 
working on the project full time, and chances are good the company 
will announce early next year that it is forging ahead with its 
design. 
</P>
<P>
	The A-3XX tries to address a capacity problem in global  
aviation. The number of airline passengers is growing by about 5 
percent annually, and analysts project that world air traffic will 
double in 15 years and triple in 22. Government officials predict 
that the number of annual air travelers in the United States alone 
will increase from about 600 million to over 1 billion by 2012. 
</P>
<P>
	A ``superjet'' has its drawbacks, however. One is that it could  
overwhelm an airport, dumping 650 people -- and their luggage -- at 
once on a system that can have trouble handling the baggage from 
tiny commuter planes. 
</P>
<P>
	Another concern is safety: The Federal Aviation Administration  
requires that a plane be evacuated within 90 seconds even if half 
of its exits are blocked. That could be a daunting challenge for a 
plane seating the equivalent of a crowded movie theater. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
