<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Amazon.com Losses Triple in Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Losses for Amazon.com Inc. more than tripled in  
the first quarter, but sales surged as the Internet merchant worked 
to grow a base of loyal customers and give them more things to buy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Seattle-based company reported Wednesday a net loss of $36.4  
million, or 23 cents a share, in the quarter ended March 31, 
compared with a net loss of $10.4 million, or 7 cents a share, in 
the year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales for the quarter were $293.6 million, an increase of 236  
percent over sales of $87.4 million a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon.com's results topped Wall Street analysts' expectations  
for a loss of 29 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought it was an outstanding quarter. By just about every  
measure I track, they exceeded my expectations by a fairly 
significant margin,'' said analyst Derek Brown at Volpe Brown 
Whelan. 
</P>
<P>
	Founded in 1995, Amazon.com has yet to make a profit as it  
spends freely to advertise its site, expand its offerings and build 
itself into a diversified online shopping hub. 
</P>
<P>
	It is already the Internet's top seller of books, music and  
video. In recent months it has expanded into auctions, greeting 
cards and has invested in the online pharmacy drugstore.com and 
Internet pet store Pets.com. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Weinstein, an analyst at Pacific Crest Capital, said he  
was not especially worried about Amazon.com's continuing losses. 
The company has to spend heavily now to cement its presence on the 
Web and to establish itself as a leading brand, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are expanding into a lot of new businesses, and all of  
the businesses they are looking at have tremendous opportunities,'' 
Weinstein said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Bezos, founder and chief executive officer, said more  
spending is ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have begun and will continue to build out, a significant  
distribution infrastructure,'' Bezos said. ``This will give 
customers greater availability, faster shipping times and even 
better service. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will also continue to invest in systems, people, and  
product expansion, each of which helps us better serve customers. 
For the rest of 1999, we expect to invest more heavily than we have 
in the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, Brown said Amazon.com is only spending about $10-$15 to  
bring in each new customer. And Bezos said that more than 66 
percent of the orders in the most-recent quarter were from repeat 
customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's basically happening is Amazon is acquiring customers  
extremely cost-effectively, then they are bringing those customers 
back through their doors at ever-increasing rates,'' Brown said. 
``And not only are they bringing them back through the doors again, 
they are providing them with a broader range of products to 
purchase.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Accounting for merger- and acquisition-related costs of $25.3  
million in the first-quarter, Amazon's net loss for the quarter was 
$61.7 million, or 39 cents a share. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
