<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NY Cops Arrested in Brothel Scandal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Two police officers were indicted Tuesday and  
two have pleaded guilty to charges they accepted sexual favors and 
a place to nap as bribes to let a brothel operate in their 
precinct. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Buscarino, 34, and James Gombach, 37, face charges of  
promoting prostitution, receiving bribes, misconduct and falsifying 
records. 
</P>
<P>
	They were released without posting bail, suspended and face a  
hearing May 25. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other officers, Lawrence Levine and James Trout, pleaded  
guilty earlier this month to taking bribes and resigned. 
Prosecutors wouldn't say whether they were promised specific 
sentences for their pleas. 
</P>
<P>
	All four officers had a relationship with the madam who ran the  
brothel in central Manhattan -- home to some of the city's most 
famous areas, including Times Square and the theater district, 
District Attorney Robert Morgenthau said. 
</P>
<P>
	The officers alerted the madam to planned raids and failed to  
file reports about the brothel's activities. 
</P>
<P>
	Buscarino and Gombach were assigned to desk jobs since  
disclosures last July that two dozen cops protected the brothel in 
exchange for sex and a spot to goof off or sleep. 
</P>
<P>
	As a reward, Morgenthau said, the madam gave the defendants  
thousands of dollars in cash, gifts including airline tickets and 
jewelry, and the sexual services of the brothel's prostitutes. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the other 20 officers have been charged.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 15:15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Salvaged Architecture Goes On Sale </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- When urban renewal came to Boston in the 1950s and  
'60s, no one cared much about the decorative bas-reliefs, fountains 
and Greek Revival columns that were left for the wrecking ball. 
</P>
<P>
	No one except Jorge Epstein, a Boston jeweler and scavenger who  
rescued enough of the city's architectural heritage to fill a bus 
barn and factory. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, five months after Epstein's death at 85, the mammoth  
collection of salvaged architecture is being sold. 
</P>
<P>
	A tag sale of a million items -- including fireplace mantels,  
leaded glass windows, plaster ornaments -- begins Thursday at the 
factory, which came to be known as Old Mansions Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, workers feverishly stacked wrought iron fences,  
Victorian doors, Greek Revival columns and dusty old paintings in 
anticipation of the hordes expected. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole place makes your eyes pop,'' said Mary Westcott, an  
associate at Kaminski Auctioneers, which is liquidating the 
collection. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale is expected to take about five months.  
</P>
<P>
	Only a small percentage of the collection had been priced. A  
pine lintel from a Colonial home was marked $300. Four 
black-and-silver art deco cornices were priced at $75 apiece. A 
framed watercolor by an unknown artist had a sticker with $175 
scrawled on it. 
</P>
<P>
	``He couldn't see how people couldn't save the stuff,'' said his  
son, Norman Epstein, standing next to a dusty stack of books 
containing municipal records that hadn't been moved from its perch 
at Old Mansions in 30 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``So we started taking stuff,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	And selling it.  
</P>
<P>
	Jorge Epstein sold the Brooklyn Museum of Art its Sculpture  
Garden. He sold a Colonial tavern to the Smithsonian Institute. He 
sold a sermon preached before John Hancock on the first day of 
American independence at auction through Christie's auction house, 
his son said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some things he couldn't stand to sell -- like rare books.  
</P>
<P>
	Other things he gave away, like bottles of 1947 Chateau  
Lafitte-Rothschild, part of the wine cellar he bought at auction 
for $50 from the Weston estate of William Blake, Thomas Edison's 
business partner. 
</P>
<P>
	Bill Mavodones, who is handling rare books and ephemera, said he  
almost threw out a dirty, dusty box filled with junk the other day. 
At the bottom of the box he found an original signature of Booker 
T. Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've had people who jumped up and down when they saw this  
stuff,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 05:41:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Newsmagazines Dominate Ratings / TV Ratings  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Television networks responded quickly last week  
to the public hunger for news about the Colorado school massacre. 
</P>
<P>
	Six prime-time newsmagazines, each one with reports on the  
Littleton shooting, were among the 12 most-watched programs 
measured by Nielsen Media Research during the past week. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC's ``20/20'' on April 21 had more viewers than any other  
newsmagazine, and had its highest ratings of the year except for 
the Monica Lewinsky interview. 
</P>
<P>
	For the first time, CBS's ``48 Hours'' beat NBC's ``ER'' in the  
ratings, although last Thursday's medical drama was a rerun. CBS 
faced criticism, however, for not responding to the Littleton story 
in prime-time as fast as its rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, viewership was down for the networks as they geared up  
for the May ratings ``sweeps'' period. CBS won the week with an 8.4 
rating and 14 share, NBC was second with an 8.1 rating and 14 
share, ABC had a 6.8 and 12 and Fox was at 6.1 and 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the emerging networks, the WB had a 2.8 rating and 5  
share, UPN had a 1.7 rating and 3 share and Pax TV was at 0.8 and 
1. 
</P>
<P>
	The most popular show of the week was a new episode of NBC's  
comedy, ``Friends.'' ABC's drama, ``The Practice,'' had its second 
highest rating in the history of the show. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC's ``Nightly News'' did well during a busy news week, scoring  
its largest margin of victory over the ``CBS Evening News'' in more 
than two years. NBC had an 8.2 rating and 18 share, while CBS was 
at 6.5 and 14. ABC's ``World News Tonight'' was second with a 7.9 
rating and 17 share. 
</P>
<P>
	A rating point represents 994,000 households, or 1 percent of  
the nation's estimated 99.4 million TV homes. The share is the 
percentage of in-use televisions tuned to a given show. 
</P>
<P>
	For the week of April 19-25, the top 10 shows, their networks  
and ratings were ``Friends,'' NBC, 14.4; ``20/20-Wednesday,'' ABC, 
12.4; ``Frasier,'' NBC, 12.2; ``Touched By an Angel,'' CBS, 12.2; 
``60 Minutes,'' CBS, 12.1; ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' NBC, 12.0; ``Law and 
Order,'' NBC, 11.8; ``Dateline NBC-Friday,'' NBC, 11.7; ``Dateline 
NBC-Wednesday,'' NBC, 11.6; ``48 Hours,'' CBS, 11.0. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 12:46:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Foreman Testifies Before Grand Jury </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWARK, N.J. (AP) -- George Foreman testified Wednesday before a  
federal grand jury said to be investigating whether the IBF sold 
rankings and arranged fights in return for kickbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	The former heavyweight champion was in the grand jury room for  
less than an hour. 
</P>
<P>
	On the advice of his lawyer, Foreman would not discuss his  
testimony. But asked if he had ever paid a kickback, he said, 
``No,'' and also said this was his first appearance before any 
grand jury. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawyer, Lawrence H. Wechsler, would not comment either, but  
he has said federal prosecutors are examining whether Foreman was 
extorted by sanctioning groups, and that he did not know if Foreman 
ever paid to better his ranking. 
</P>
<P>
	In past weeks, the grand jury has heard from officials of the  
New Jersey-based IBF, one of the world's three major sanctioning 
organizations. It does not appear that its president, Robert W. Lee 
Sr., has testified. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreman did discuss with the media the need to reform boxing and  
the sanctioning groups. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that boxing should be given some time to clean up its  
act. If not someone should do it for them,'' Foreman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Although inactive in the ring for several years, Foreman -- who  
recently turned 50 -- also said he wants to fight the man he 
considers the heavyweight champion, Lennox Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd like to keep coming back until I'm a grandfather and  
boxing is a sport as clean as pingpong,'' said Foreman, who later 
playfully sparred with news photographers outside the courthouse. 
</P>
<P>
	At 45, Foreman captured the IBF and WBA championships to become  
the oldest champion in any weight class, and now boasts a record of 
76-5. 
</P>
<P>
	The grand jury earlier this month heard from the boxing judge  
criticized for her scoring in last month's Evander Holyfield-Lennox 
Lewis title fight. 
</P>
<P>
	Eugenia Williams told the grand jury that no one attempted to  
sway her decision, her lawyer has said. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreman had his opinion. He said, ``I think Lewis won the fight  
hands down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But he said it was not the first robbery the sport has seen, and  
claimed his defeat in 1974 by Muhammad Ali in Zaire should be a 
prime example. 
</P>
<P>
	The controversy over the Holyfield-Lewis fight created an  
opportunity for improvements, including having the sanctioning 
groups adopt guidelines on how they set rankings, Foreman said. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal grand jurors have subpoenaed all IBF records since 1982  
on rankings and contracts for fights, as well as checks, invoices, 
expense forms and telephone records, its attorney has said. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal prosecutors, citing grand jury secrecy, decline to  
comment on the investigation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 12:46:03 </DATE_TIME>
