<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 09:25:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nashville Sound: the ACM Awards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Country singer Jo Dee Messina fanned  
herself with her hand and fluttered her eyelids, doing a send-up of 
the classic Southern belle. 
</P>
<P>
	Messina, a Yankee from Massachusetts, was expressing her joy at  
receiving three nominations at this year's Academy of Country Music 
Awards, including best new female vocalist, best female vocalist 
and best album for ``I'm Alright.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The cool part is I get to sit on the ballot next to Faith  
Hill, Martina McBride, and all those people I love,'' the 
28-year-old singer said. 
</P>
<P>
	The ACM Awards show airs May 5 on CBS from 8-11 p.m. EDT from  
the Universal Amphitheater in Universal City, Calif. Nominees for 
best entertainer are Garth Brooks, the duo Brooks &AMP; Dunn, Tim 
McGraw, George Strait and Shania Twain. 
</P>
<P>
	Faith Hill leads all nominees with six. In addition to best  
female vocalist, she's up for best album for ``Faith''; song, 
single and video for ``This Kiss''; and best vocal event for her 
duet with husband Tim McGraw, ``Just to Hear You Say That You Love 
Me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The country music artist of the decade will be announced during  
the show. Previous winners were Marty Robbins for the 1960s, 
Loretta Lynn for the 1970s and Alabama for the 1980s. The smart 
money is on Garth Brooks for the 1990s, but Gene Weed, the show's 
producer, says George Strait and Reba McEntire also are strong 
contenders. 
</P>
<P>
	Messina's nominations cap a remarkable comeback for the country  
singer, who broke through in 1996 with two top 10 hits -- ``Heads 
Carolina, Tails California'' and ``You're Not in Kansas Anymore'' -- 
from her debut album, ``Jo Dee Messina.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She leased a bus, hired a band and hit the road after her debut.  
But expenses often ran higher than her paychecks. Then the release 
of a new album was delayed when Messina and her producers had 
trouble finding songs they thought could be hits. Bookings dried up 
and things became desperate. ``I owed everybody money. It was 
gross. I was so overwhelmed,'' Messina said. 
</P>
<P>
	Help from her record label, a local bank and a small endorsement  
deal with a trucking company got her through the end of last year. 
And ``Bye Bye,'' the first single from ``I'm Alright,'' went 
straight to No. 1. The album has already sold a million copies. 
</P>
<P>
	The ACM Awards is the first of three country music awards shows  
telecast each year. The fan-voted TNN Music City News Awards follow 
in June on The Nashville Network, and the Country Music Association 
hands out trophies in the fall. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in country music...  
</P>
<P>
	COUNTRY MILLENNIUM: Dolly Parton, Ray Charles, Jeff Foxworthy  
and Steve Wariner are among performers who will help bring in 2000 
at the Opryland Hotel in Nashville with four-days of performances 
from Dec. 30 to Jan. 3. Packages start at about $1,600. The Judds 
have already announced a New Year's Eve show in Phoenix, Ariz. 
</P>
<P>
	LIVE AT BILLY BOB'S: Famous Fort Worth, Texas, country music  
club Billy Bob's Texas is releasing a series of live albums 
recorded there. First up is Eddy Raven, Pat Green and Jon Conlee. 
Upcoming releases include Merle Haggard, Roy Clark, Waylon Jennings 
and Ray Price. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Nominees for Academy of Country Music Awards:  
</P>
<P>
	ENTERTAINER: Garth Brooks, Brooks &AMP; Dunn, Tim McGraw, George  
Strait and Shania Twain. 
</P>
<P>
	MALE VOCALIST: Garth Brooks, Vince Gill, Tim McGraw, Collin Raye  
and George Strait. 
</P>
<P>
	FEMALE VOCALIST: Faith Hill, Martina McBride, Jo Dee Messina,  
Shania Twain and Trisha Yearwood. 
</P>
<P>
	DUET OR GROUP: Alabama, Brooks &AMP; Dunn, Dixie Chicks, Sawyer  
Brown, and The Wilkinsons. 
</P>
<P>
	NEW MALE VOCALIST: Deryl Dodd, David Kersh and Mark Wills.  
</P>
<P>
	NEW FEMALE VOCALIST: Sherrie Austin, Jo Dee Messina and Allison  
Moorer. 
</P>
<P>
	NEW GROUP OR DUET: Dixie Chicks, The Warren Brothers and The  
Wilkinsons. 
</P>
<P>
	ALBUM: ``Double Live,'' Garth Brooks; ``Faith,'' Faith Hill;  
``I'm Alright,'' Jo Dee Messina; ``One Step at a Time,'' George 
Strait; ``Wide Open Spaces,'' Dixie Chicks. 
</P>
<P>
	SONG: ``A Broken Wing,'' Martina McBride; ``Don't Laugh at Me,''  
Mark Wills; ``Holes in the Floor of Heaven,'' Steve Wariner; 
``Husbands and Wives,'' Brooks &AMP; Dunn; ``This Kiss,'' Faith Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGLE RECORD: ``A Broken Wing,'' Martina McBride; ``Holes in  
the Floor of Heaven,'' Steve Wariner; ``This Kiss,'' Faith Hill; 
``26 Cents,'' The Wilkinsons; ``You're Still the One,'' Shania 
Twain. 
</P>
<P>
	VOCAL EVENT OF THE YEAR: ``Burnin' the Roadhouse Down,'' Steve  
Wariner and Garth Brooks; ``If You See Him, If You See Her,'' 
Brooks &AMP; Dunn and Reba McEntire; ``Just to Hear You Say That You 
Love Me,'' Faith Hill and Tim McGraw; ``No Place That Far,'' Sara 
Evans and Vince Gill; ``Same Old Train,'' Clint Black, Joe Diffie, 
Merle Haggard, Emmylou Harris, Alison Krauss, Patty Loveless, Earl 
Scruggs, Ricky Skaggs, Marty Stuart, Pam Tillis, Randy Travis, 
Travis Tritt and Dwight Yoakam. 
</P>
<P>
	VIDEO: ``Drive Me Wild,'' Sawyer Brown; ``Getcha Some,'' Toby  
Keith; ``Holes in the Floor of Heaven,'' Steve Wariner; ``I'll Go 
on Loving You,'' Alan Jackson; ``This Kiss,'' Faith Hill. 
</P>
