<DOCNO> APW19990428.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 03:35:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lakers Have Little Time To Improve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INGLEWOOD, Calif. (AP) -- It's gotten ugly for the Los Angeles  
Lakers recently. And they find themselves with very little time to 
get things right before the playoffs begin. 
</P>
<P>
	``We haven't played very good basketball lately,'' forward Rick  
Fox understated Tuesday on the heels of two horrendous performances 
in Texas. ``Are we capable of changing that? Yeah, I'd like to 
think we're a team capable of changing that. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've done the talking before. That's enough talk.''  
</P>
<P>
	The Lakers reached the Western Conference finals last spring,  
and were considered prime contenders to succeed the Michael 
Jordan-led Chicago Bulls as NBA champions before the start of the 
abbreviated 1999 season. 
</P>
<P>
	If nothing else, they were anointed the league's glamour team,  
as evidenced by their many games on national television -- far more 
than anyone else. 
</P>
<P>
	However, just about everything that could go wrong has, and now  
the Lakers have just the fifth-best record in the West with only 
four games left before the playoffs begin May 8. 
</P>
<P>
	--Coach Del Harris was fired after three straight losses dropped  
the team to 6-6 in late February. 
</P>
<P>
	--Eccentric seven-time NBA rebounding champion Dennis Rodman was  
brought in to help on defense and on the backboards, and while he 
did help at times, he also created several disruptions. He was 
waived April 15. 
</P>
<P>
	--Sharpshooter Glen Rice and J.R. Reid were acquired from  
Charlotte for Eddie Jones and Elden Campbell just before the trade 
deadline seven weeks ago, and it's been an ill-fated deal to this 
point. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lakers certainly saved their worst for the last 2 1/2 weeks,  
losing six of eight games, including the last three. The six losses 
came by an average of 17 points, including a 108-81 embarrassment 
at San Antonio on Saturday night and a 102-80 humiliation at 
Houston on Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The team spent nearly 2 1/2 hours behind closed doors Tuesday  
before practicing for about 70 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Meetings and film, that's what went on,'' Lakers coach Kurt  
Rambis said. ``We hashed out some things as a team. The whole idea 
was to get everybody on the same page. There were some frustrations 
that were aired.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rambis wouldn't know about all of those frustrations, because a  
players-only meeting was held, as well as an overall team meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't heated,'' Kobe Bryant said of the players-only  
get-together, which he said lasted about 45 minutes. ``We were 
trying to figure out what happened, why we started spiraling 
downward, how we got to this point, how we're going to get out of 
this. It wasn't pointing fingers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rambis admitted after the game in Houston that his team didn't  
play hard. On Tuesday, he added that a lot of the problems ``come 
from within.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I think you have a tendency to play harder when you feel a  
responsibility to the team,'' he said. ``When individuals accept 
that, they play beyond their expectations, because they don't want 
to let their teammates down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There have been reports of friction between center Shaquille  
O'Neal, the NBA's No. 2 scorer, and Bryant, who ranks 15th in the 
league. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just have to regroup,'' was one of the few things O'Neal  
told reporters Tuesday. ``I'm glad we're the underdog. You 
(reporters) counted us out about four weeks ago, you guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 20-year-old Bryant, who shot just 3-for-14 at Houston, said  
he didn't believe the Lakers were a team in turmoil, and claimed 
the reported problems with O'Neal were overblown. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know him that well off the court,'' Bryant said. ``Our  
relationship on the court, it's very, very fine. We're constantly 
communicating on the court. It's really not that big a deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bryant said the two haven't had a talk about things.  
</P>
<P>
	``No, for what? Our relationship is great on the basketball  
court, and it's only going to get better,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	O'Neal recently told reporters: ``You know the real problem,  
you're just scared to write about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He later told CBS Sportsline: ``What is this, an experiment?  
Nobody waited for me when I came into the league. ... I'm not going 
to be here that long that I want to wait years for (Bryant) to 
figure it out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When asked why the Lakers have been losing, Bryant said,  
``There's a lot of different reasons, not just one particular 
reason. I really don't want to get into it. A true team keeps 
things like that to themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bryant said he's optimistic, regardless of what's happened  
recently. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't care if we lose by 40,'' he said. ``I always feel we  
can bounce back.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
