<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jones Lawyers Ask For More Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Lawyers for Paula Jones asked today for  
additional time to calculate expenses that President Clinton must 
pay for his false testimony in her sexual harassment lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Donald Campbell, the lead attorney for much of Mrs. Jones' legal  
case, asked U.S. District Judge Susan Webber Wright to extend to 
May 7 a May 3 deadline for submitting the costs. The judge ordered 
the payments when she held Clinton in civil contempt for his 
deposition testimony in January 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Campbell said the delay was necessary because of other court  
cases and vacation schedules in his Dallas law firm. 
</P>
<P>
	Wright on April 12 found that Clinton gave ``intentionally  
false'' testimony about his relationship with Monica Lewinsky, 
imposing a judicial rebuke on a president for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge ordered the president to pay ``any reasonable expenses  
including attorneys' fees caused by his willful failure to obey 
this court's discovery orders.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The judge also ordered the president to pay $1,202 as  
reimbursement for the judge's travel to Washington in the case, and 
set in motion a process that could strip Clinton of his Arkansas 
law license. 
</P>
</TEXT>
