<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 14:55:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Can Bradley Give Gore a Race? </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUBUQUE, Iowa (AP) -- In his uphill campaign against Al Gore for  
the Democratic presidential nomination, Bill Bradley is picking up 
a bit of what politicians call ``traction.'' He's getting more 
attention than seemed likely a short time ago and even Gore 
advisers say he has made the race competitive. 
</P>
<P>
	``I see the guy everywhere,'' says Iowa Democratic Chairman Rob  
Tully. ``He's able to fly under the radar screen better than the 
vice president can. I think he's going to make it a spirited 
race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore loyalists dismiss the phenomenon as nothing more than ``the  
Bradley boomlet,'' a label applied by one of them, Chicago 
political consultant David Axelrod. They see it as a brief and 
media-driven frenzy. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Axelrod conceded that Bradley ``is going to be  
competitive. I've always felt that Bradley had the potential to 
make some noise in Iowa.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The former New Jersey senator is getting a new look from  
liberals and those who worry that Gore is too cautious; last week, 
liberal Paul Wellstone of Minnesota became the first senator to 
endorse Bradley. 
</P>
<P>
	Tully said he's been traveling the state and keeps crossing  
paths with Bradley, who is quietly building a network, making 
low-key, grassroots appearances in the important early states. 
While he can't match Gore's blue-chip roster of backers, he can 
spend hours rubbing shoulders in places like Iowa and New 
Hampshire. 
</P>
<P>
	Clearly aware of that, Gore has picked up the pace of his  
campaign, beefing up his schedule and refocusing his style. He's 
paying attention to rubbing shoulders with voters. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview Wednesday, Gore waved off the prospect of a  
Bradley threat. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm fully aware of how campaigns evolve over time,'' said  
Gore. ``Some who haven't been through these things before sometimes 
misinterpret the snapshots of the moment and don't see the moving 
picture of the entire campaign.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel very comfortable with where things are,'' he added.  
``I'll let others analyze the opposition. I don't have any unkind 
words for the opposition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some say it was inevitable that the race would turn competitive,  
even though Gore has the backing of virtually all of the Democratic 
establishment and access to the White House political network. 
</P>
<P>
	History is on his side, too. A sitting vice president hasn't  
been denied the nomination since 1952. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just think there's an inevitability of the Democratic  
nominating process, which is people like competition and they like 
having a real race,'' said Bill Carrick, a Democratic consultant in 
California who advises Gore. ``And they're more inclined to be for 
outsiders and insurgents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans have picked up on that. They are keeping a closer  
eye on Bradley and have begun including questions about him in 
their polling. Gore aides dismiss that as a GOP effort to hurt Gore 
by building up his rival. 
</P>
<P>
	But some recent polls show Bradley as close as 20 points to  
Gore, half the gap of earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	In Iowa, where precinct caucuses launch the presidential  
nominating season, Bradley aides say his crowds have been big. 
</P>
<P>
	``He has a natural advantage in this process,'' said Iowa's  
Democratic Gov. Tom Vilsack. ``He can spend more time and the time 
he spends is more personal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vilsack describes himself as ``friendly'' to Bradley's effort,  
hastening to add: ``I like both of them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gore's campaign has faced challenges. A bombing campaign in  
Yugoslavia and President Clinton's affair with a White House intern 
and brush with impeachment have made it tough for Gore to break out 
on his own. There have been complaints that Gore relies too heavily 
on a tight inner circle, few of whom have presidential campaign 
experience. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite all that, Gore has huge assets.  
</P>
<P>
	Axelrod said Gore has two national campaigns under his belt and  
the weight of the party's establishment behind him. 
</P>
<P>
	``At these early stages, Bradley is going to wear well, but  
later on it's going to be tough,'' Axelrod said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dana Strother, a nonaligned Democratic strategist, dismissed  
Bradley's early fund-raising success, arguing that raising about $5 
million amounts to tapping a few friends. That's pocket change 
compared with the other $25 million Bradley must raise to be 
competitive, Strother said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Bill Bradley says he has big ideas,'' said Strother. ``But let  
me tell you, big money will beat big ideas.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
