<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Accused of Betraying Athletes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Olympic leaders betrayed athletes,  
sponsors and the public in the Salt Lake bribery scandal, a senior 
IOC official said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In a meeting with corporate backers of the 2000 Games in Sydney,  
International Olympic Committee vice president Jacques Rogge said 
the committee must accept ``collective guilt'' for the damage 
caused by the worst corruption case in its 105 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a member of the IOC, I have to express my apologies for the  
wrongdoings that have been made by the IOC,'' Rogge said at the 
start of the first visit to Sydney by a top-level IOC official 
since the scandal broke late last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel very sorry, because we have betrayed the athletes whom  
we represent and for whom we are working, we have betrayed the 
sponsors, we have betrayed public opinion, we have betrayed the 
organizers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rogge told the sponsors that there would be ``leaner, meaner''  
IOC by the time the Sydney Olympics start. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will deliver,'' Rogge said. ``We can reassure them that we  
will have in Sydney the best-ever Olympic Games and they will have 
legitimate returns on their investments.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rogge, chairman of the IOC's coordination commission for the  
2000 Games that is visiting Sydney this week, said the sponsors 
were critical of the IOC and concerned about damage the scandal has 
caused to the Sydney budget and Olympic marketing. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sydney Organizing Committee for the Olympic Games announced  
last week it would cut its expected revenue from sponsors by $32 
million. With other cuts, SOCOG said, the overall budget had been 
reduced by $48 million. 
</P>
<P>
	SOCOG president Michael Knight blamed the sponsorship shortfall  
on the IOC scandal and said some services would have to be cut, but 
that the overall quality of the games would not be affected. 
</P>
<P>
	Rogge said the IOC recognized the scandal created a ``difficult  
climate'' for attracting new sponsors, but said it was just one of 
the reasons for the budget gap and rejected suggestions the IOC 
should pay for the damage. 
</P>
<P>
	The Belgian official said Sydney's sponsorship target was  
``ambitious'' to start with, and a shortfall -- blamed on the Asian 
financial crisis -- had been identified before the scandal broke. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are taking our part of the responsibility, but it is not  
the only cause,'' Rogge said. 
</P>
<P>
	He also noted that the SOCOG budget still projected a surplus.  
</P>
<P>
	Ten IOC members have resigned or been expelled in the scandal,  
which involved a million-dollar scheme to buy votes in Salt Lake 
City's successful bid for the 2002 Winter Olympics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
