<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls Against Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar fell against the yen Wednesday, but  
rose against the euro as the conflict continued in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 119.22  
Japanese yen, down from 120.40 yen late Tuesday. The euro fell 
against the dollar, trading at $1.0627, down from $1.0660. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar dropped two yen during Asian trading as the chairman  
of the Japanese government's tax commission recommended a 15 
trillion yen supplemental budget, including 5 trillion yen in tax 
cuts and credits. 
</P>
<P>
	Japan is fighting its worst recession in decades partly through  
public works spending and such a recommendation was seen as a major 
initiative to stimulate the economy. Further rumors helped spur the 
yen's rise. 
</P>
<P>
	``The big mover in the past 24 hours has been the yen,'' said  
Ben Strauss, a vice president of foreign exchange at Bank Julius 
Baer &AMP; Co. ``Everytime we see the concept raised, the yen 
rallies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rally ended when Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi said the plan  
was not under consideration. But traders failed to retake the 
dollar's ground against the yen despite trying through the European 
and North American trading sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, many investors stayed away from the markets ahead  
of Japan's ``Golden Week'' holidays. Japanese financial markets 
will be closed Thursday and the first three days of next week. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was quoted at 1.5122 Swiss francs, up from 1.5074,  
and 1.4783 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4793 late Tuesday. The 
British pound was quoted at $1.6137, down from $1.6179. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro no  
longer are traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed 
rate. Based on the euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8406 German 
marks, up from 1.8349; 6.1728 French francs, up from 6.1538, and 
1,821.49 Italian lire, up from 1,814.88. 
</P>
</TEXT>
