<DOCNO> APW19990428.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 09:15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> DaimlerChrysler Earnings Up 16 Pct. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STUTTGART, Germany (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler AG today said strong  
U.S. sales at its Chrysler division offset weak results in Asia and 
Latin America during the first quarter, boosting operating earnings 
16 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	After adjustment for one-time items, earnings totaled $2.73  
billion, or $1.77 a share, compared with $2.35 billion, or $1.55 a 
share, for the company formed by the merger of Chrysler Corp. and 
Daimler-Benz AG a year ago. It was the first full quarter earnings 
report for the company since the merger in November. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first-quarter figures support our confidence for 1999,''  
chairman Juergen Schrempp said. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues were up 10 percent to $37.82 billion from $34.44  
billion a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Co-chairman Robert J. Eaton said DaimlerChrysler had a  
particularly strong quarter in the United States, but that problems 
persisted in Asia and Latin America. He also said the recent 
slowdown in Western Europe was expected to continue into the second 
half of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	The company is ahead of schedule in integrating the operations  
of the two automakers, Eaton said. Savings from combining such 
operations as purchasing and engineering should provide ``a 
tremendous opportunity for overall growth in the full year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the United States, DaimlerChrysler plans to increase  
production this year to meet higher demand, he said. The former 
Chrysler operations were responsible for more than half of the 
first quarter earnings, but Eaton said he expected that percentage 
to decline as the rest of the company grows at a faster rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Eaton said sales of the French-built Smart car has been a  
disappointment in Europe and was a drag on Mercedes-Benz profits, 
but that the company was taking steps to boost demand, including 
lowering prices, increasing standard equipment and spending more on 
marketing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're clearly going to try to turn that around,'' he said.  
``But it's possible we'll conclude it's a good idea but simply one 
who's time hasn't come.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Brazil, where DaimlerChrysler is starting up production of  
the small Mercedes-Benz A-class car, the market remains down 
sharply. But Eaton said he was optimistic. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think it has hit the bottom. We're looking for a turn-up  
early next year,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He was less optimistic about Asia, particularly Japan. ``It's  
our judgment (Japan's) not going to turn around and be positive for 
two or three years, potentially.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eaton said management will recommend at the new company's first  
annual meeting next month an annual dividend of about $2.50 a 
share, which is in line with what Chrysler paid but substantially 
above the former Daimler-Benz dividend. 
</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler said it adjusted its first-quarter results for  
one-time items from the public offering of its telecommunications 
unit Debitel and Germany's tax reform. 1998 results were adjusted 
for the sale of the group's semiconductor business and gains from 
the sale of two buildings in Berlin. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of DaimlerChrysler workers worldwide increased 8  
percent during the quarter to 456,440, taking into account the 
acquisition of Adtranz, the company's rail systems unit. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 15:43:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  China Says Complain, Don't Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- Chinese citizens should make their complaints  
known through proper channels rather than through protests, a 
communist official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Demonstrating outside Zhongnanhai, the headquarters of the  
government and the ruling Communist Party, is ``completely wrong,'' 
the state-run Xinhua News Agency said late Tuesday night, quoting 
an unidentified official in charge of handling complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	The remarks were part of the government's first explanation of  
how it used persuasion to defuse a massive demonstration by members 
of a martial arts sect. 
</P>
<P>
	``Different views and opinions are allowable and can also be  
reported through normal channels according to law,'' the agency 
said, quoting the official. 
</P>
<P>
	The demonstration unnerved Chinese leaders because it came close  
to the 10th anniversary of the 1989 crackdown on pro-democracy 
activists in Tiananmen Square. 
</P>
<P>
	The government's criticism of protests follows dozens of  
unrelated labor demonstrations in recent months by workers who feel 
victimized by China's economic reforms. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 4,000 retired miners blocked a train line Monday in  
the northeastern city of Fushun, protesting a cutoff of their 
pension payments, a labor rights group reported. 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday, more than 10,000 followers of the group Falun Gong  
surrounded the leadership compound in a silent protest to call for 
assurances that they could legally practice the teachings of their 
leader, Li Hongzhi, a Chinese native who lives in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Falun Gong is a form of qigong, a traditional practice that uses  
exercise and meditation and attempts to channel unseen forces to 
improve health. Qigong has been hugely popular in China for 
decades, and Falun has rapidly grown to more than 70 million people 
in China, according to a government estimate. 
</P>
<P>
	The government has not yet made an official ruling on whether  
Falun Gong is an acceptable form of qigong or a cult-like offshoot 
that must be stopped. 
</P>
<P>
	But the party official said anyone using the pretext of  
practicing any form of qigong to disrupt stability will be 
prosecuted. 
</P>
<P>
	Mindful of qigong's wide appeal, the government handled the  
protest carefully. Officials met with participants, listened 
patiently and persuaded them to leave, Xinhua reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The daylong protest ended Sunday night with protesters simply  
walking away. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 15:43:46 </DATE_TIME>
