<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> American Starting Flights to Alaska </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- American will start flights to Alaska  
in June as part of the airline's expansion plans in the West. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's decision to grow westward earlier this year by  
purchasing Reno Air touched off a yet-to-be-resolved feud with its 
pilots' union. 
</P>
<P>
	This time the company is expanding from within. American, a  
subsidiary of AMR Corp., will be adding 20 new flights over the 
summer. As well as the Dallas to Anchorage flights, other new 
nonstop routes will include Los Angeles to Paris and Hartford, 
Conn.; Seattle to Tokyo, New York and Boston; and San Jose, Calif., 
to Tokyo, San Diego and Orange County, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are making a major commitment to growth and expansion on  
the West Coast,'' said Michael Gunn, American's senior vice 
president of marketing. 
</P>
<P>
	This isn't American's first foray into Alaska. In the 1980s, the  
company had a pilot interchange program with Alaska Airlines. An 
American Airlines pilot would fly from Dallas to Seattle, for 
example, then an Alaska Airlines crew would continue to Alaska. 
</P>
<P>
	In the late 1980s, AMR bought a small West Coast airline named  
AirCal in an effort to pick up routes along the California coast. 
American ultimately absorbed AirCal and withdrew many of its 
airplanes from the area in the early 1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, still hoping to keep a hand in California, AMR started a  
frequent-flier plan with Reno Air. All of those moves were a 
prelude to a dispute earlier this year between the company and its 
pilots, many of whom are still angry that Reno Air pilots took over 
their routes when American left the area. 
</P>
<P>
	When American announced the purchase of Reno last December, the  
dispute reached a boiling point that ultimately resulted in a 
sickout by pilots over 10 days in February. The job action cost the 
company millions of dollars, delayed jets around the world and 
stranded hundreds of thousand of passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge held the Allied Pilots Association and its two  
top officers in contempt and fined them $45 million for ignoring 
his order to tell pilots to return to their cockpits. He has not 
yet decided how the three parties will divide the fine among them. 
</P>
<P>
	APA plans to appeal the judge's decision to the 5th Circuit  
Court in New Orleans. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0230 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 14:35:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Changing Sanctions Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration opened the way  
Wednesday for the sale of food and medical items to three countries 
listed as terrorist states -- Iran, Libya and Sudan -- arguing that 
economic sanctions often do more harm than good. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sales of food, medicine and other humanitarian necessities do  
not generally enhance a nation's military capacity or support 
terrorism,'' Under Secretary of State Stuart Eizenstat told 
reporters. ``On the contrary, funds spent on agricultural 
commodities and products are not available for other, less 
desirable uses. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our purpose in applying sanctions is to influence the behavior  
of regimes, not to deny people their basic humanitarian needs,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Barring such sales usually fails to hurt targeted regimes while  
depriving American companies of export opportunities, officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new policy is part of a broader attempt at comprehensive  
sanctions reform. The goal is to resort to unilateral sanctions 
only after all other options, including diplomacy and multilateral 
sanctions, have been exhausted. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the changed approach, humanitarian items will be exempted  
from future sanctions. Wednesday's announcement will not affect 
Iraq, North Korea and Cuba, all sanctioned countries to which sales 
of certain items are already permitted. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials said it was unclear whether the changed policy  
meant a pending Iranian request for more than $500 million worth of 
American grain and sugar will be approved. A number of farm state 
senators and House members have been seeking approval of the 
request. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., welcomed the policy shift, saying in  
a telephone interview that the administration has, in effect, been 
telling farmers, ``'You pay the cost of our foreign policy.''' He 
added: ``Fidel Castro and Saddam Hussein have never missed a meal 
because of our sanctions policy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He noted that large grain stocks have led to depressed prices.  
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Dick Lugar, R-Ind., a strong advocate of sanctions reform,  
also was supportive. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do not believe that food and medicine should be used as a  
tool of foreign policy,'' said Lugar, the Senate Agriculture 
Committee chairman. ``Doing so typically injures innocent civilians 
in the sanctioned country, imposes little hardship on recalcitrant 
leaders whose behavior we wish to change and opens the door for 
other exporting countries to replace the U.S. as a food supplier.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Government experts predict the policy change could increase  
wheat and corn exports by 1 million tons, said Agriculture 
Secretary Dan Glickman. 
</P>
<P>
	Eizenstat said the new policy is not directed at any particular  
country. Among the countries subject to curbs on food and medicine, 
only Iran has been a target of a U.S. effort for improved 
relations. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration has called for resumption of an official  
dialogue with Iran but thus far has been rebuffed. Iran was one of 
America's most important allies in the Middle East until the 
pro-American monarchy was toppled two decades ago and replaced by a 
regime led largely by Islamic fundamentalists. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Cuba, Eizenstat noted that sales of medicine and medical  
supplies are allowed with certain limitations under legislation 
approved in 1992, and the regulated sales of food, pesticides and 
related items were permitted under a policy shift announced in 
January. 
</P>
<P>
	And while Iraq is subject to unilateral U.S. sanctions as well  
as U.N.-mandated sanctions, it has been authorized to sell oil on 
the international market so long as the proceeds are earmarked for 
purchases of humanitarian goods. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, despite unilateral sanctions against North Korea,  
the administration approved the donation of tens of thousands of 
tons of food assistance to that country in recent years through the 
U.N. World Food Program. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Foreign Relations Committee Chairman Jesse Helms, R-N.C.,  
offered conditional support for the policy. Marc Thiessen, a Helms 
spokesman, said: ``Every dollar Iran or Sudan or Libya wants to 
spend on American grain instead of on terrorism or weapons of mass 
destruction is fine with us.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0231 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 09:35:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Brit Aerospace Mulls Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- British Aerospace PLC is reportedly talking with  
France's Lagardere and Italy's Finmeccanica SpA about merging their 
guided weapons operations to create the world's second-largest 
missile manufacturer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Financial Times reported Wednesday that British Aerospace  
chief executive John Weston said the three companies were 
discussing how to merge the operations. 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper said such a merger would create the world's  
biggest missile maker after Raytheon Co., based in Lexington, Mass. 
</P>
<P>
	British Aerospace spokesman Mike Peters confirmed Wednesday that  
the three companies have held discussions, but noted that they 
already have projects in common and refused to say whether their 
talks were aimed specifically at forming a joint project to build 
missiles. 
</P>
<P>
	``We continue to advocate the consolidation of the European  
aerospace and defense industry on the basis that the globalization 
of the industry is moving ahead,'' Peters said. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares in British Aerospace were up 2.3 percent in late  
afternoon trading in London, while Lagardere shares were trading 
1.0 percent higher on the Paris stock exchange. Finmeccanica shares 
slipped 1.0 percent in Milan. 
</P>
<P>
	British Aerospace is the largest arms company in Europe and,  
with its acquisition of the Marconi defense operations of General 
Electric Co. PLC, it will rank No. 3 in the world. British 
Aerospace agreed in January to acquire Marconi in a deal worth 
$11.9 billion. It reached a definitive sales agreement with GEC on 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	British Aerospace expects that another decade of consolidation  
in the aerospace sectors will leave just two or three companies 
capable of competing on a global scale. 
</P>
<P>
	It wants to see ``a European company with the widest possible  
distributed shareholder base'' as one of the surviving competitors, 
Peters said. 
</P>
<P>
	British Aerospace and Lagardere's Matra subsidiary already have  
a guided weapons joint venture called Matra BAe Dynamics. 
</P>
<P>
	Both companies are increasing their weapons production through  
new partnerships -- Matra through its merger with France's 
Aerospatiale, and British Aerospace through Marconi's 50 percent 
stake in a project with Alenia SpA, part of the Finmeccanica group. 
</P>
<P>
	Matra BAe Dynamics also has a 30 percent stake in LFK, the  
missiles subsidiary of DaimlerChrysler Aerospace. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, scores of peace activists were ejected from  
British Aerospace's annual shareholder meeting after they protested 
the company's sale of ground attack aircraft to the Indonesian 
government and assault rifles to the Turkish army. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0232 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 15:15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Anheuser-Busch Earnings Up 20 Pct. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Anheuser-Busch Cos. reported a 20 percent  
increase in first-quarter profits due largely to increased beer 
sales in America. 
</P>
<P>
	The maker of Budweiser and Bud Light said Wednesday it had net  
income of $319 million, or 66 cents per share, up from $265 
million, or 54 cents per share, in the same period a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues rose to $3.15 billion from $2.95 billion.  
</P>
<P>
	Anheuser-Busch's domestic beer market share rose 1.5 percent to  
48.1 percent in the first quarter. Domestic revenue per barrel was 
up 2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Domestic beer shipments increased 7.9 million barrels to 23.2  
million barrels. The company said the increased shipments reflected 
the continued strength of Budweiser products and the February 
rollout of Tequiza, which combines the flavors of tequila and lime. 
</P>
<P>
	Worldwide beer sales volume rose 7.6 percent to 24.5 million  
barrels. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Anheuser-Busch rose 37 1/2 cents to $75.37 1/2 in trading on  
the New York Stock Exchange. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
