<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jagr Expects To Play in Game 5 / Hockey Game Story  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CANONSBURG, Pa. (AP) -- After a 30-minute workout Wednesday,  
Pittsburgh Penguins captain Jaromir Jagr said he expects to play 
against the New Jersey Devils Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Jagr, who missed three games after reinjuring his groin in Game  
1 of the opening-round Stanley Cup playoff series last Thursday, 
doesn't expect to be at full strength for Game 5 at East 
Rutherford, N.J. But through acupuncture and rest, Jagr's condition 
has improved, and he is anxious to play. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins and Devils are tied 2-2. Game 6 is Sunday at Civic  
Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to play because I think I can help the team even if I'm  
not going to be 100 percent,'' Jagr said. ``I feel I should be 
there. I feel I should play Friday, but everybody should understand 
that I cannot do much out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jagr, who won his third NHL scoring title in five seasons and  
second straight, had an assist in Game 1, which the Penguins lost 
3-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Jagr has made his linemates better players. Journeyman Kip  
Miller's 19 goals and 42 points, rookie Jan Hrdina's 13 goals and 
42 points and Martin Straka's career-best 35 goals and 83 points 
are prime examples of Jagr's influence. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you picked a guy that you wouldn't want injured during the  
series, one of the guys would be Jaromir,'' coach Kevin Constantine 
said. ``So, when you lose him, you've lost a lot. And when you get 
him back, you get back a lot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Jagr badly wants to play, he probably won't go if he can't  
skate at full speed. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course, I expect the pain, but this is different,'' Jagr  
said. ``Every time I make a step, every time I push, I feel pain. 
And it's very tough to skate. ... I don't think it matters whether 
I play five minutes or 15 minutes. If I'm going to play, it's going 
to hurt.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
