<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 15:44:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Militia Opposed to East Timor Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DILI, Indonesia (AP) -- Anti-independence militiamen on Wednesday  
rejected plans for a U.N.-supervised ballot on East Timor's future, 
pledging to maintain their fight to stay part of Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	The fighters, blamed for a dramatic upsurge of violence in the  
former Portuguese colony, also refused to say if they would obey a 
demand by the Indonesian military to surrender their weapons before 
the vote. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Indonesian President B.J. Habibie announced plans  
for a ballot Aug. 8 that will deliver autonomy or independence to 
East Timor 24 years after Indonesia invaded. 
</P>
<P>
	The United Nations was to supervise the poll with the aid of an  
unspecified number of international police advisers and poll 
monitors from six countries, including the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	The first U.N. officials were expected to arrive in East Timor's  
capital, Dili, within two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The militiamen said they opposed the vote because it would  
foment more unrest between opposing sides of the independence 
issue. 
</P>
<P>
	Violence has escalated this year since Indonesia said it would  
consider letting go of the territory, which accounts for roughly 
half the island of Timor. Dozens of people have been killed in 
recent weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will fight everybody who wants to trouble us and wants to  
force us to accept their opinion,'' said John Estevan Soares, a 
pro-Indonesian leader. 
</P>
<P>
	``We reject it. We refuse it,'' he said of the August ballot.  
``The United Nations must bear the consequences if things go 
wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Indonesian military, accused of doing little to curb militia  
attacks on civilians, said it will disarm rival groups. But it was 
far from certain that militiamen and separatist rebels would lay 
down their weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Col. Tono Suratman, East Timor's military commander, said he  
held personal misgivings about the ballot. However, he said he 
would carry out the orders of Habibie's government. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those who have guns which can kill will have to surrender them  
to the police,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The ballot plan was to be signed by Indonesia and Portugal at  
U.N. headquarters in New York next Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Pro-independence activists say the vast majority of East Timor's  
800,000 people want to break away from Indonesia. However, they say 
a full U.N. military peacekeeping force is required to maintain 
security vital for a free and open ballot. 
</P>
<P>
	Soares said the militiamen would never accept independence and  
would even launch a guerrilla war in East Timor's mountainous 
interior if that were the outcome of the ballot. Rival 
pro-independence rebels have fought Indonesian troops this way for 
more than two decades. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, seven Dili journalists accused militiamen and  
soldiers of harassing them. Earlier this month militia groups 
trashed the office of their newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	Yayasan Hak, a Timorese human rights group, said two civilians  
had been kidnapped in Dili by anti-independence groups on Tuesday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0238 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 21:13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Wants Hedge Fund Disclosure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A presidential working group is recommending  
that risky investment funds be required by law to disclose 
financial information now deemed private, a House source said 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The long-awaited recommendations on hedge funds are in response  
to the near collapse of a Connecticut-based fund last fall that 
threatened to send financial markets around the world into a 
tailspin. They were to be made public Thursday by the President's 
Working Group on Financial Markets, the House official said, 
speaking on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	The group is composed of officials from the Federal Reserve, the  
Treasury Department, the Securities and Exchange Commission and the 
Commodity Futures Trading Commission. It has been studying for 
months the events leading to the meltdown of Long-Term Capital 
Management, a big speculative fund for wealthy investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel also is recommending that Congress give the SEC and  
the CFTC more authority to collect data on unregulated affiliates 
of securities firms that participate in hedge funds, the House 
official said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another recommendation is that the SEC begin requiring publicly  
traded companies, such as big banks and brokerage firms, to 
disclose any significant investments they have in hedge funds. 
</P>
<P>
	And the panel recommends that regulators require banks and  
brokerage firms to set aside more reserves to cover potential 
losses from hedge fund investments, the source said. 
</P>
<P>
	The hedge funds would be required to disclose their financial  
data to federal regulators every three months under the White House 
panel's proposal. Currently some but not all hedge funds are 
required to file financial reports with the CFTC, but the reports 
are often out of date and kept confidential. 
</P>
<P>
	The working group, however, is not calling for direct government  
regulation of hedge funds, according to the source. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan and SEC Chairman Arthur  
Levitt both have said publicly in recent months they believe that 
new government controls on hedge funds aren't needed. 
</P>
<P>
	Greenspan acknowledged recently that the Long-Term Capital  
debacle was a failure of the current system, which relies on banks 
-- rather than federal regulators -- to supervise the hedge funds to 
which they lend money. But he called it ``a single mistake ... a 
very rare event.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Long-Term Capital's near collapse last September after its  
managers bet wrong on interest-rate swings threatened financial 
markets until the Federal Reserve helped arrange a $3.6 billion 
bailout by a group of big banks and brokerage firms. 
</P>
<P>
	Patrick Parkinson, associate director of the Fed's research and  
statistics division, told lawmakers last December that banks making 
generous loans to Long-Term Capital ``didn't ask enough questions'' 
about the fund's risks and operations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0240 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 19:22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coyotes' Roenick Returns to Ice </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. (AP) -- All-Star center Jeremy Roenick, whose  
jaw was shattered near the end of the season, skated at the Phoenix 
Coyotes' practice facility on Wednesday and hinted that he might 
return to action in the second round of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just have a lot of confidence in my teammates that they're  
going to finish off St. Louis,'' he said. ``It could be a couple of 
weeks yet. We'll have to wait and see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Coyotes have a 3-1 lead on the Blues and could close out  
their first-round series by winning Game 5 on Friday. If Phoenix 
did advance, it would face Dallas, the No. 1 team in the Western 
Conference. 
</P>
<P>
	Stars defenseman Derian Hatcher drew a seven-game suspension --  
including five in the playoffs -- for injuring Roenick in an April 
14 game. He caught Roenick, the Coyotes' leading scorer, by 
surprise with an elbow to the face and was forced to sit out seven 
games, including the first five of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Because the Stars swept Edmonton in four games, Hatcher will  
have to miss the first game of their second-round series. 
</P>
<P>
	Roenick's right thumb also was broken in the last meeting with  
Dallas when Craig Ludwig slashed him. That injury alone was 
expected to sideline him for three to four weeks, but Roenick cut 
the cast off his hand last week. 
</P>
<P>
	While most of his teammates took the day off, Roenick went  
through shooting and conditioning drills. Roenick had 24 goals and 
48 assists in 78 games before the latest injury. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0241 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 13:05:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Champion Has Breast Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- Olympic hurdles gold medalist Ludmila  
Engquist has been operated on for breast cancer and will undergo 
chemotherapy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russian-born Engquist, 35, won the 100-meter hurdles for  
Sweden at the 1996 Atlanta Games. She also won world championships 
in 1991 and 1997. Last year, her season was cut short by a 
hamstring injury. 
</P>
<P>
	She told a news conference Wednesday she underwent surgery last  
week and although the operation went well, there were indications 
the cancer was spreading and she would need chemotherapy. 
</P>
<P>
	``My first reaction was that I did not want to live any  
longer,'' she said. But now she hopes to recover quickly enough to 
compete at the 2000 Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I cannot have survival as my only goal,'' she said. ``That  
would be too boring. My goal is to come back in my best running 
form. It is good for me to have that goal; it will help me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Engquist also won the 1991 world indoor 60-meter hurdles title  
and set the world record in the 60 hurdles in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
