<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NuSouth Label Tries To Sell Unity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) -- Lining the racks of a small shop in this  
city of the Old South are jackets, sweaters and caps with a 
startling Confederate Flag -- the traditional red, white and blue of 
the old Confederacy replaced with the black, red and green of black 
liberation. 
</P>
<P>
	The two black entrepreneurs who founded NuSouth Apparel hope  
that blending those powerful symbols as a show of unity also will 
prove profitable at a time when showing one's colors has been good 
business for the Ralph Laurens of the world. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a clothing line with a conscience,'' said Angel Quintero  
as he sat in the company's boutique just off the beaten path in 
this city where the Civil War started. 
</P>
<P>
	What began as a design for the cover of an album by a local rap  
group is now a trademarked clothing line that Quintero and partner 
Sherman Evans promise will challenge the Calvin Klines and Tommy 
Hilfigers. 
</P>
<P>
	Five years after the album cover and almost two years after the  
company opened its tiny boutique, NuSouth is shipping its spring 
and summer line to more than 200 retailers nationwide. A second 
store opens in Atlanta this spring and NuSouth hopes to add stores 
in Houston and Charlotte, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	They sell everything from baseball caps to socks and men's  
underwear. The line includes shorts selling for $26 a pair, polo 
shirts for $29 and jackets for $62.50. 
</P>
<P>
	Audrey Guskey, a marketing professor at Duquesne University in  
Pittsburgh who has consulted for companies such as General Motors 
Corp. and Eastman Kodak Co., said the timing seems right for 
NuSouth. 
</P>
<P>
	``This type of logo that stands for a philosophy or a way of  
thinking is rare. It's coming at a time when this would be 
acceptable. Ten or 15 years ago it might have been too avant-garde, 
too risky or too controversial,'' Ms. Guskey said. 
</P>
<P>
	Quintero and Evans say whites make up about 70 percent of their  
business and they don't want NuSouth pigeonholed as an urban brand 
just for young blacks. 
</P>
<P>
	``For the sons and daughters of former slaves,'' reads their ad  
pitch. ``For the sons and daughters of former slave owners. Threads 
that connect us. Words that free us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The idea is to put the divisions of the past behind, Evans said.  
</P>
<P>
	``People say, 'I'm not a former slave,' or, 'I'm not a former  
slave owner.' Well, you know, somewhere in your family you have 
been one or the other,'' he said. ``Quit polarizing us and making 
it a black or white thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Evans and Quintero say it's not just a one-season fad.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to Atlanta,'' said Evans, who owns another  
clothing boutique across town. ``The bottom line is Atlanta is the 
capital of the South. There's Coca-Cola, there's Ted Turner and 
there's NuSouth, that's how we see it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's not cockiness, said Quintero who also owns an auto  
detailing shop. ``It's just that we believe in what we are doing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pair say they use only American mills to make the clothes  
and have avoided bank financing in favor of small investors. Evans 
would not discuss how much NuSouth has raised. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're hungry, we're aggressive and we have a vision. We're not  
selling out,'' he said. ``We tell the venture capitalists that, 
'You're not getting 65 percent of the company.' '' 
</P>
<P>
	The emphasis has been on creating the brand, said Evans. Sales  
this season are ``slightly south of a million,'' he said, ``we're 
projecting this coming year $10 million total.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stores carrying NuSouth clothing must display it in an in-store  
boutique, not just on a rack with other brands. ``We're a little 
more sophisticated than people give us credit for. We understand 
the value of having a brand,'' Evans said. 
</P>
<P>
	After the pair designed the album cover for the local rap group  
da Phlayva, media attention followed when a girl was suspended from 
an area high school in 1994 for wearing a T-shirt with the logo and 
the group's name. 
</P>
<P>
	Evans and Quintero later sold some items during the Million Man  
March. Then came the boutique, a Web site and a catalogue. Articles 
in GQ and other fashion magazines spread the buzz. 
</P>
<P>
	Charleston Police Chief Reuben Greenberg, who is black, bought a  
flag license plate after seeing one on Quintero's truck. Quintero 
said Greenberg pulled him over and asked where to get one. 
</P>
<P>
	Combining the flag, a symbol of oppression to some people, with  
a symbol of liberation may take some explaining outside the South, 
Ms. Guskey said. ``You have to make a connection for them or have 
somebody make the connection,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	She also warned that NuSouth must move quickly to prevent  
knockoffs, but so far, the company has not had a bootlegging 
problem, Evans said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Anyone who would go buy a bootleg NuSouth really doesn't get  
it. NuSouth is far deeper,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
