<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Columbine Students Pass the Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- Pete Forsberg is renting movies and  
having sleepovers -- and visiting hospitals. Katie Ulibarri has gone 
back to work at the mall -- in between funerals. Katie Crona is 
helping her mom with chores -- when she's not watching memorial 
services. 
</P>
<P>
	The three Columbine High students haven't sat in classrooms or  
done homework for a week. But this is a break like no other, and 
the minutes tick by ever so slowly. 
</P>
<P>
	Their minds are filled with images from last week, when two of  
their classmates killed 12 students, a teacher and themselves. 
Classes won't resume until Monday, when students head to nearby 
Chatfield High School to finish out the year. 
</P>
<P>
	In the meantime, many are spending time saying goodbye to  
friends. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've tried to do everything to keep my mind off of it,'' said  
Miss Crona, 14. ``It happened a week ago, but it could've happened 
four to five months ago. It just seems so slow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Crona, a freshman, was among two dozen students who cheered  
the Columbine Rebels girls' soccer team Tuesday afternoon. The 
game, which marked the resumption of the school's extracurricular 
activities, was played in neighboring Lakewood. 
</P>
<P>
	During a moment of silence just before kickoff, students held  
hands, wept and watched a stadium flag fly at half-staff against 
dark clouds. 
</P>
<P>
	After Columbine took a 2-0 lead against rival Golden High, one  
mother in the bleachers called out: ``We are!'' With sure voices, 
the students responded with a strong ``Columbine!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Forsberg, a 17-year-old junior, wore a blue-and-silver Columbine  
memorial ribbon. Hanging out with four buddies, he said he's been 
going to the hospital, sometimes twice a day, to visit wounded 
friends. He and his friends are having sleepovers and watching 
movies like ``Airplane'' on video. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been spending a lot of time with each other because we  
draw strength from each other,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Parents have become friends. One girl said she camped out with  
her mother and father for three nights at Clement Park, where a 
makeshift shrine now covers an area the size of a football field. 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Ulibarri also has been engaging in a decidedly un-teen-age  
activity by hanging out with her parents, who ``won't let me out of 
their sight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I've gotten more hugs and kisses than I've gotten in my whole  
life,'' she said on her second day back to work at Afterthoughts, a 
shop in the Southwest Plaza mall near the high school. 
</P>
<P>
	But Miss Ulibarri is staying away from Clement Park, which she  
thinks has become a tourist attraction. ``You can't go there 
without getting a camera shoved in your face,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Natalie Baker, 15, who strolled through the mall with a friend  
Tuesday, has been spending some of her time with investigators. She 
was in the cafeteria when shooting broke out, so they've come to 
her house to find out what she saw. 
</P>
<P>
	Otherwise, Miss Baker has passed the hours with friends, talking  
through what happened. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last night, we just drove around 'til four in the morning,''  
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jessica Hughes, meanwhile, needed to get away from Littleton --  
far away. 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Hughes, who had known gunman Dylan Klebold since they were  
in an accelerated program together in third grade, went to Oregon 
to be with her college-student brother. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been too hard for her,'' said Abigail Hughes, her  
22-year-old sister. ``She's been totally depressed.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
