<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Attack Prompts Manson To End Tour </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Shock rocker Marilyn Manson has canceled the  
band's last five dates of its American tour ``out of respect for 
those lost in the school tragedy at Littleton, Colo.,'' according 
to Manson's web site. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are trying to sort out what happened and to deal with  
their losses,'' Marilyn Manson said. ``It's not a great atmosphere 
to be out playing rock'n'roll shows, for us or the fans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The band's music is popular among Gothic youth, who wear black  
and think a lot about death. The two students at Columbine High 
School in Littleton, Colo. who fatally shot 12 students, a teacher 
and then committed suicide, were members of a group that called 
itself the ``Trenchcoat Mafia'' and appeared to have adopted some 
of the Gothic lifestyle. 
</P>
<P>
	``The media has unfairly scapegoated the music industry and  
so-called Goth kids and has speculated -- with no basis in truth -- 
that artists like myself are in some way to blame,'' Manson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This tragedy was a product of ignorance, hatred, and an access  
to guns. I hope the media's irresponsible finger-pointing doesn't 
create more discrimination against kids who look different,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The band will postpone concerts scheduled for May 3 in Reno, May  
4 in Fresno, May 5 in Las Vegas, May 7 in Phoenix and May 8 in Los 
Angeles. It was not clear when the band would hold the concert or 
what ticketholders should do with their tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	Manson had been scheduled to headline a concert in Denver on  
April 30. The show was canceled by the radio station sponsoring it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
