<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Seeks Compromise on Y2K Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Senate is searching for a formula for  
legislation that would prevent an avalanche of lawsuits arising 
from Year 2000 computer breakdowns without eroding basic legal 
rights to redress wrongs. 
</P>
<P>
	A meeting of Senate leaders and key players Tuesday failed to  
resolve several remaining issues, including how to cap punitive 
damage awards so as to discourage frivolous lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	The outstanding issues ``are tough. They are very difficult,''  
said Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., the chief sponsor of the ``Y2K'' 
litigation bill with Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore. ``I'm not sure we will 
be able to resolve them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bill would allow companies 90 days to fix faulty computers  
before lawsuits can go forward, and encourage mediation. It would 
also put a $250,000 cap on most punitive damage awards and make it 
harder to file class action lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	Strongly backed by the high tech industry and business groups,  
the measure is aimed at blunting what some experts warn could be 
the largest crush of lawsuits in U.S. history, a $1 trillion mass 
of litigation that could cripple the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	One potentially dangerous result of computer breakdowns -- and a  
possible source of big lawsuits -- was the subject of a House 
hearing Tuesday, where health experts acknowledged that they can't 
guarantee that hospitals and doctors will have their biomedical 
equipment -- MRI machines, pacemakers and dialysis machines -- ready 
for Jan. 1, 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	The fear is that some computers will mistake the year 2000 for  
1900, causing errors and breakdowns. Almost all hospitals say they 
will have their computers fixed by yearend, but Joel Willemssen of 
Congress' General Accounting Office said hospitals surveyed in 
February found that only 6 percent of medical devices and 13 
percent of information systems were Y2K-compliant. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents of McCain's bill, led by Sen. Fritz Hollings, D-S.C.,  
argue that hospitals and other businesses will, out of 
self-interest, address the problem so as to avoid losing customers 
and attracting lawsuits. Hollings said the real purpose is to 
change tort law to favor defendants trying to avoid huge penalties. 
</P>
<P>
	But Wyden argued that there is a ``real centrist coalition''  
growing behind a bill that both protects consumers and ensures ``we 
don't have bedlam in our economy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said major pro-consumer changes had been made in McCain's  
original bill, such as limiting the bill to three years to make 
clear it is not changing basic tort law and eliminating punitive 
damage caps when fraud or willful negligence is involved. Language 
in the original bill that exempted company directors and officers 
from personal liability also was modified. 
</P>
<P>
	But some Democrats are still pushing for removal of all caps on  
punitive damages and want stronger language on officer liability. 
Also at issue is language that a person is liable for damages only 
if it is determined he acted with specific intent to injure the 
plaintiff. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said he would order  
a vote Thursday to cut off debate and move to a final vote if 
differences aren't settled before then. 
</P>
<P>
	One of those differences has nothing to do with the computer  
problem, but concerns Democratic demands they be given a chance 
soon to take up some of their priorities, including gun control 
legislation. Democrats have threatened to attach gun control 
amendments to the Y2K bill if Lott doesn't agree to their demands. 
</P>
<P>
	----	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is S.96.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
