<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> IMF Prepares To Help Balkans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The international community is preparing  
significant contributions to deal with the human and economic costs 
of the air war in the Balkans, top officials of the International 
Monetary Fund and World Bank reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	A donor conference Tuesday night, representing both wealthy  
industrial countries and six Balkan nations affected by the Kosovo 
crisis, produced good results in terms of assessing initial needs 
and making sure financial support begins quickly, said Michael 
Deppler of the IMF. 
</P>
<P>
	``The meeting was successful in galvanizing the process of  
international economic cooperation,'' Deppler said. 
</P>
<P>
	But as the spring meetings of the 182-nation IMF and its sister  
lending organization, the World Bank, wrapped up today, officials 
reported much less success on other major agenda items dealing with 
helping the global economy recover from nearly two years of 
currency turmoil. 
</P>
<P>
	The IMF also failed to resolve a number of differences in  
approaches to overhauling the financial architecture to prevent or 
at least better cope with future crises. 
</P>
<P>
	As it has throughout the four days of talks, the United States  
continued to warn against complacency in addressing the reform 
issues, now that there are hopeful signs the crisis is drawing to a 
close. 
</P>
<P>
	``The crisis has abated. But it is still a dangerous world out  
there and profound challenges remain,'' Deputy Treasury Secretary 
Lawrence Summers said today. 
</P>
<P>
	In a joint statement released after the Kosovo discussions, the  
IMF and World Bank said the meeting, called at the request of 
France, had been attended by seven international agencies and 33 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	While preliminary European estimates for reconstruction in the  
Balkans have put the costs as high as $30 billion, officials urged 
caution in using such high figures, saying much more needs to be 
known about the damage done by the NATO bombing, how long the war 
will last and how quickly economic activity may recover to 
pre-crisis levels. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the countries taking part were the six Balkan nations  
outside Yugoslavia most directly affected -- Albania, Bosnia, 
Bulgaria, Croatia, Macedonia and Romania. 
</P>
<P>
	``Speakers (at the meeting) broadly endorsed the methodology  
adopted by the joint IMF/World Bank paper to assess the economic, 
financial and social costs of the crisis,'' the agencies said. 
</P>
<P>
	The World Bank and the 15-nation European Union will coordinate  
assessing needs and how they are provided, the statement said. 
Donor countries will hold pledge meetings in the next few weeks for 
the Balkan countries. 
</P>
<P>
	In a separate communique Tuesday night, the IMF conceded that it  
had failed to reach agreement on a number of outstanding issues on 
dealing with future currency crises. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, the IMF's policy-setting interim committee issued a  
10-page final statement pledging to continue efforts to resolve 
competing proposals put forward by the United States and other 
industrial countries. 
</P>
<P>
	It hailed as its one major achievement the creation of new  
U.S.-proposed contingent credit lines that could provide billions 
of dollars for warding off financial panic to countries pursuing 
sound economic policies. 
</P>
<P>
	But agreements could not be reached on involving the private  
sector in sharing the cost of future bailouts or monitoring the 
borrowing practices of countries with emerging economies. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States, led by Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin,  
favored a more market-oriented, case-by-case approach for 
private-sector involvement. Britain and other nations preferred 
specific rules defining the obligations of investors whose bets on 
emerging markets go bad. 
</P>
<P>
	Other issues left on the table included ways to better manage  
wild currency fluctuations both in developing countries and 
industrial nations. 
</P>
<P>
	The United States opposed efforts pushed by Japan and Germany  
for more coordinated efforts among countries to manage currency 
levels. 
</P>
<P>
	Even in areas where there was agreement, such as the need to  
provide greater debt relief for the poorest countries, the IMF 
could not resolve how much of its gold reserves should be sold to 
help finance the initiative, or how much money wealthy nations 
would be willing to contribute to the effort. 
</P>
<P>
	Debt relief was also expected to be taken up when President  
Clinton and the other leaders of the world's seven largest 
economies hold their annual economic summit in mid-June in Cologne, 
Germany. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
