<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Economic Recovery Called Fragile  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration, disappointed with  
the failure to reach agreement with its major allies on a strategy 
to reform the global economy, warned today that despite recent 
glimmers of an upturn in many crisis countries, ``it's still a 
dangerous world out there.'' The International Monetary Fund and 
its sister lending agency, the World Bank, concluded four days of 
talks with pledges to intensify efforts to deal with weaknesses 
exposed by the Asian-currency crisis. But they left most of the 
hard decisions until later. Some officials expressed concerns that 
recent rebounds in the markets of several of the countries leveled 
by the currency crisis over the last two years may have reduced a 
needed sense of urgency. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Plan Raises Hopes for Asia  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Over the past month, Japan has loaned $400 million  
to Indonesian power companies, hundreds of millions more to build 
railways and roads in Malaysia, and $1 billion for South Korea to 
use however it sees fit. It's all part of the ``Miyazawa 
Initiative,'' a $30 billion loan package Japan hopes will help Asia 
out of its financial crisis and boost this country's stature as the 
region's economic leader. The initiative indicates both Japan's 
desire to exert influence on the world stage and frustration 
throughout Asia with the way the West has tried to deal with the 
nearly two-year-old crisis. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Mixed; Dow Closes Up 13.74  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices were mixed on Wall Street today as  
investors again collected profits from technology shares. But they 
continued to buy big industrial stocks, pushing the Dow industrials 
up 13.74 to 10,845.45, its second consecutive closing high. The 
enthusiasm for manufacturing stocks was bolstered by this morning's 
Commerce Department report that orders to factories for big-ticket 
durable goods rose 2 percent in March after an end-of-winter slump. 
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 11.89 to 1,350.91, and the Nasdaq 
fell 52.14 to 2,550.27. Bryan Piskorowski, a market analyst with 
Prudential Securities, said there was some caution in the market 
today as investors awaited an earnings report from Amazon.com, 
scheduled to be released after the close of trading. Amazon.com 
shares fell 13 today to 192 7/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures just before Wednesday's  
