</P>
<P>
	Execs Convicted of Trade Espionage  
</P>
<P>
	YOUNGSTOWN, Ohio (AP) -- A federal jury convicted two Taiwanese  
executives of paying a researcher at Avery Dennison Corp. to hand 
over adhesives industry trade secrets. The case was the first to 
reach trial under the 1996 Economic Espionage Act, which banned the 
theft of trade secrets. Pin Yen Yang, president of Four Pillars 
Enterprise Co. Ltd., and his daughter, Hwei Chen ``Sally'' Yang, 
were each found guilty of two counts of economic espionage. The 
jury also found Four Pillars guilty of the same charges. Defense 
attorneys immediately filed for a mistrial. 

</P>
<P>
	Greenspan 'Conflicted' on Privacy  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan said financial  
privacy poses an increasingly difficult dilemma for regulators, who 
must balance individual rights against the importance of 
information in business. Greenspan, testifying today before a House 
panel, was asked about a proposal adopted by the House Banking 
Committee last month that would restrict the sharing of certain 
information among affiliated banks, brokerage firms and insurance 
companies. Under the provision, customers' transaction data still 
would be allowed to be shared among affiliated financial companies. 
Greenspan said the issue ``is going to become increasingly 
difficult for our whole regulatory structure.'' 

</P>
<P>
	US, Canada in Beef Hormone Dispute  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- The United States, Canada and the European Union  
set out their positions on hormone-treated beef today. Trade 
representatives fear the dispute will escalate like the battle over 
banana imports, which resulted in the United States imposing 100 
percent tariffs on selected EU imports. The WTO has ruled that the 
European Union is acting illegally in banning imports of beef 
treated with certain hormones from countries including the United 
States and Canada. But in an apparent widening of the divide, the 
European Commission received the go-ahead to ban all imports of 
American beef as of June 15. 

</P>
<P>
	Coca-Cola Must Inform EU of Deal  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The European Union asserted  
jurisdiction today over Coca-Cola Co.'s proposed $1.75 billion 
acquisition of Cadbury Schweppes PLC's beverage brands outside the 
United States. EU Competition Commissioner Karel van Miert said 
failure to notify the 15-nation EU of its plans could result in 
``heavy penalties'' for the Atlanta-based soft drink maker. 
Coca-Cola has claimed it doesn't need to notify the EU executive 
commission about the deal because the acquisition falls below a 
minimum threshold set by the EU for review of such deals. Coca-Cola 
shares were down 1 1/2 at 67 15/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Anheuser-Busch Earnings Up 20 Pct.  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Anheuser-Busch Cos. reported a 20 percent  
increase in first-quarter profits due largely to increased beer 
sales in America. The maker of Budweiser and Bud Light said it had 
net income of $319 million, or 66 cents per share. Revenues rose to 
$3.15 billion from $2.95 billion. Anheuser-Busch's domestic beer 
market share rose 1.5 percent to 48.1 percent in the first quarter, 
and domestic beer shipments increased 7.9 million barrels to 23.2 
million barrels. Worldwide beer sales volume rose 7.6 percent to 
24.5 million barrels. Anheuser-Busch stock rose 1 1/2 to 75 3/8. 

</P>
<P>
	DaimlerChrysler Earnings Up 16 Pct.  
</P>
<P>
	STUTTGART, Germany (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler AG today said strong  
U.S. sales at its Chrysler division offset weak results in Asia and 
Latin America during the first quarter, boosting operating earnings 
16 percent. After adjustment for one-time items, earnings totaled 
$2.73 billion, or $1.77 a share, compared with $2.35 billion, or 
$1.55 a share, for the company formed by the merger of Chrysler 
Corp. and Daimler-Benz AG a year ago. It was the first full quarter 
earnings report for the company since the merger in November. 
Co-chairman Robert J. Eaton said DaimlerChrysler is ahead of 
schedule in integrating the operations of the two automakers. 
DaimlerChrysler shares fell 2 3/16 at 99 1/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Bausch &AMP; Lomb Sells Sunglass Brands  
</P>
<P>
	ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Bausch &AMP; Lomb Inc., maker of premium  
Ray-Ban sunglasses since the 1920s, is selling its sunglass 
business for $640 million to Italy's Luxottica Group SpA, owner of 
the LensCrafters retail chain. While Bausch &AMP; Lomb controls around 
40 percent of the world's premium fashion eyewear business, the 
sunglass unit has struggled of late to turn a profit. Bausch &AMP; Lomb 
has been refocusing in recent years on eye care -- contact lenses, 
ophthalmic drugs, eye surgery instruments -- and appears ready to 
shed a hearing-aid unit and other noncore businesses by the end of 
1999. Bausch &AMP; Lomb stock fell 1 to 78. 

</P>
<P>
	American Starting Flights to Alaska  
</P>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- American will start flights to Alaska  
in June as part of the airline's expansion plans in the West. 
American, a subsidiary of AMR Corp., will be adding 20 new flights 
over the summer. As well as the Dallas to Anchorage flights, other 
new nonstop routes will include Los Angeles to Paris and Hartford, 
Conn.; Seattle to Tokyo, New York and Boston; and San Jose, Calif., 
to Tokyo, San Diego and Orange County, Calif. AMR shares were up 
5/16 to 72 15/16. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	Durable goods: up 2 percent  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Unemployment claims  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: New home sales  
</P>
<P>
	Friday: Gross domestic product  

</P>
