<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> United Developing Turbulence Sensor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Passengers had settled in for the night on a long  
flight from Tokyo to Honolulu when it felt like a giant fist 
slammed into the United Airlines jumbo jet. A pocket of air 
turbulence hit with such violence in the late 1997 incident that 
one woman suffered a broken neck and died while 100 other 
passengers were injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Turbulence often strikes without warning, but now United and two  
technology companies -- AlliedSignal Aerospace and Coherent 
Technologies -- hope to develop a system that could give passengers 
a one-minute warning to fasten their seat belts to avoid being 
tossed around the cabin. 
</P>
<P>
	The turbulence-detection system being sought by the No. 1 U.S.  
airline is at least three years from being implemented and would 
provide no guarantee of an end to stomach-wrenching gyrations. But 
safety officials, airlines and their employees are hoping it will 
go a long way toward reducing the dozens of serious injuries that 
occur annually. 
</P>
<P>
	``It'd give us a 60-second warning so we could get everybody  
seated and hanging on,'' Bill Cotton, United's manager of air 
traffic and flight systems, said Wednesday as the search for the 
warning system was announced. 
</P>
<P>
	``Right now, it's kind of like closing the door after you've let  
the horse out of the barn: turning on the seat belt sign after 
we've run into turbulence,'' said Cotton, a pilot for 32 years who 
flies 747s and 767s. ``The new radar would be far more valuable to 
pilots in knowing exactly when we were going to encounter 
turbulence than anything that's available today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Aviation Administration says that outside of fatal  
accidents, turbulence is the leading cause of injuries to 
passengers and flight crew. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great that United is taking the lead and developing  
technology to predict turbulence,'' said FAA spokeswoman Tammy 
Jones. ``Helping passengers avoid injuries caused by turbulence is 
one of the initiatives under the FAA's safer skies agenda and we 
support anything that would achieve that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pilots for decades have used airborne radar to steer clear of  
rain and thunderstorms often associated with turbulence, but there 
is no means for detecting bumpy weather that occurs in so-called 
clear-air conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	That has forced pilots to rely on the reports of airplanes that  
have flown the same route ahead of them, which could have 
disastrous consequences since clear-air turbulence often develops 
quickly and is concentrated over small areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Turbulence is created when the fastest winds in the jet stream  
slow down, causing upward air motion. Airflows over mountains and 
the heating of land masses during daytime are other causes. 
</P>
<P>
	While pilots often warn passengers to keep seat belts fastened  
while seated, there are few ways to enforce it. And turbulence 
often can cause loose objects to fly around the cabin. 
</P>
<P>
	In January alone, five people were injured when a Tokyo-bound  
United jumbo jet from Chicago hit severe turbulence. Ten days 
later, 22 were hurt when a Continental Airlines flight from Tokyo 
to Honolulu hit severe turbulence. 
</P>
<P>
	To combat that, a prototype developed by Coherent Technologies  
Inc. would use a newly developed infrared radar to transmit energy 
beams up to 18 miles ahead of the aircraft. 
</P>
<P>
	Those beams would be reflected by the microscopic particles  
suspended in the earth's atmosphere and would provide a picture of 
``wash'' or turbulent air patterns. 
</P>
<P>
	A systems test in March, sponsored by NASA's aviation safety  
program ``demonstrated we could see at significant range and showed 
we can measure strength (of turbulence) and provide time of impact 
predictions to pilots,'' said Paul A. Reveley, Coherent's director 
of business development. 
</P>
<P>
	The company now is working with AlliedSignal Inc. to combine its  
infrared radar with AlliedSignal Aerospace's new radar that is 
capable of better detecting turbulence during rainstorms. 
</P>
<P>
	Participants in the program still are working out the costs for  
the joint all-weather radar as well as key features, including 
whether warnings would be relayed to the cockpit or immediately 
into the cabin. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're talking to other major carriers to get a feel for their  
reaction because we want to develop a product that meets the needs 
of the industry as a whole,'' Reveley said. 
</P>
<P>
	If additional tests are successful and have a low false-alarm  
rate, the new radars likely would be installed on all of United's 
585 planes, said airline spokesman Joe Hopkins. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
