<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 21:13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Realtors Get More for Their Homes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- A new study showing that real-estate  
brokers sell their own houses for 3.1 percent more on average than 
their clients' homes isn't getting much credence from area brokers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that's baloney, I really do,'' said Janet Stahlman,  
co-owner of Linn Realty Group in Bellefonte. ``We don't determine 
the prices. Something is only worth what someone is willing to pay 
for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Added another Linn co-owner, JoAnn Knupp: ``The business is too  
competitive to have anyone pulling strings. We make money no matter 
which property we sell. If they don't want mine, they're going to 
want someone else's.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The new study of more than 21,000 home sales in Texas also  
indicates that brokers' homes do not languish on the market any 
longer to get those higher prices, either. 
</P>
<P>
	``Commissions fail to give agents an incentive to work hard to  
get a better price for you,'' explained Abdullah Yavas, a professor 
of business administration at Penn State, one of three universities 
that conducted the study. ``They would rather get the deal done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While brokers work to secure the best possible price for their  
clients, they are also motivated by a need to work quickly. At the 
same time they are selling homes, they are also competing for new 
clients -- and vying with other brokers to find buyers for listed 
houses. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissions from a sale range from 2 to 10 percent, although  
sometimes they must split that with their brokerage house. 
</P>
<P>
	If the average commission amounts to 6 percent, that means for  
an extra $1,000 in the sales price, they get a grand total of $60. 
</P>
<P>
	``But if it's their own property, that's $1,000 more for them,''  
Yavas said. 
</P>
<P>
	The study -- which also involved researchers from the University  
of Texas at San Antonio and the Florida Atlantic University -- 
examined the sale of 21,235 houses in Fort Worth between 1993 and 
1995. Nearly 400 houses were owned by brokers themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	The data included age, square footage and location of the  
houses. The listings also detailed the number of bathrooms, when a 
house was sold and whether someone lived there at the time of the 
sale. That information allowed the researchers to control for 
variables, Yavas said. 
</P>
<P>
	On average, brokers' houses were listed at prices 3 percent  
higher than the rest of the group. Yet they sold just as quickly, 
leading researchers to assume the brokers must have worked harder 
to sell their own. 
</P>
<P>
	If homeowners believe Yavas' research, why not simply force  
their broker to boost listing prices by 3 percent? Yavas said it's 
not that simple. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a trade-off between getting a high price and selling  
it quickly,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	As for Yavas, he hasn't had a chance to test his theory  
personally -- despite moving from Iowa to Illinois to Michigan to 
State College, Pa., in recent years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I still haven't bought a house yet,'' he said with a shrug.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0261 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 05:59:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Refugees Flood Out of Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MORINI, Albania (AP) -- Nearly 2,000 refugees from Kosovo fled  
into Albania early today, telling of a new Serb campaign to clear 
villages in southern Kosovo and alluding to a possible new 
massacre. 
</P>
<P>
	In neighboring Macedonia, aid officials warned that the refugee  
camps were so overcrowded that rioting could soon break out. 
</P>
<P>
	Several refugees told reporters in Albania that Serb police  
surrounded their villages Tuesday and told them to leave 
immediately. They made the 12-mile journey on tractors, wagons and 
other vehicles. 
</P>
<P>
	Several refugees claimed Serb troops had stopped some vehicles  
along the way and took away young and middle-aged men. 
</P>
<P>
	Zhen Berisha said he first tried to flee his village, Madanaj,  
on April 14 but he was stopped by Serb forces, who told him to 
return home because NATO was bombing near the border. 
</P>
<P>
	``They came to our houses and said `Now is the day. You have to  
leave,''' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Several refugees said they had seen bodies lying in the streets  
of Meje, a village near Djakovica, in southwestern Kosovo. One 
refugee, Lule Ndue, said she saw scores of bodies when she passed 
through the area between 3 p.m. and 4 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Another refugee, Rahime Becaj, said she saw Serb police rounding  
up young men when she traveled through the same village earlier 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, up to 5,000 ethnic Albanians entered Macedonia on  
Tuesday -- the highest single-day total in weeks. They were 
apparently the leading edge of a major exodus touched off by 
intensified Serb ethnic cleansing south and east of Kosovo's 
provincial capital, Pristina. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's huge. Many more are coming,'' said Azem Rrahmani, who  
said Serb police expelled him from the town of Urosevac. He was 
among more than 3,000 refugees that reached the Blace border post 
after being herded on to buses and trains. 
</P>
<P>
	As darkness fell, workers at the border pounded stakes and dug  
latrines as a tent city grew in a muddy riverside field intended as 
a transit point. Refugees were handed plastic sacks of water and 
food before being led to tents. 
</P>
<P>
	To the east, up to 2,000 others entered at the Lojane border  
post, out of the easy reach of aid groups, said Ron Redmond, a 
spokesman for the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	The new onslaught of more than 13,000 refugees in four days  
further stressed Macedonia. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.N. refugee agency warned today that camps packed beyond  
capacity in Macedonia were ``on the verge of rioting'' because of 
tensions. 
</P>
<P>
	``If we get another trainload or two and a few busloads again  
today, it's really going to be a horrific situation there in terms 
of overcrowding,'' said spokesman Kris Janowski in Geneva, 
Switzerland. 
</P>
<P>
	The Macedonian government, led by its Slavic majority, insists  
the country can accept no more refugees and worries about the 
demographic scales tipping in favor of ethnic Albanians, who 
comprised a third of the country's 2.1 million people before the 
Kosovo crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. officials estimate that at least 136,000 ethnic Albanians  
from Kosovo are presently in Macedonia: about 79,000 staying in 
private homes and the rest in six government-run camps. Macedonian 
officials place the refugee total at 183,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Although conditions in some camps have improved considerably,  
cases of measles, hepatitis and dysentery have surfaced recently. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm afraid this is a sign of things to come,'' said Redmond.  
</P>
<P>
	Efforts were being made to expand some of the existing camps and  
construct a new area for up to 15,000 people. But Macedonian 
officials have delayed plans to expand the refugee sites because of 
disputes over who will install sanitation and other systems, aid 
workers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are now jammed to the breaking point ... we will be seeing  
people sleeping in the open,'' said Redmond. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Radusa camp, 20 miles northwest of the Macedonian capital  
of Skopje, two buses carrying more than 150 refugees arrived early 
Tuesday. With no place to accommodate the newcomers, they were 
forced to sleep in makeshift shower areas and in a tent used as the 
camp's school. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0262 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 07:35:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Opens Up 41.23 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices were mostly higher in early Wall Street  
trading Wednesday as investors, feeling increasingly confident 
about the world economy, continued a buying spree that included a 
wide variety of stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	At 10 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 41.23 at 10,872.94 after rising 113.12 Tuesday to a new closing 
high of 10,831.71. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mostly higher. The Standard &AMP;  
Poor's 500 index was up 3.70 at 1,366.50, and the Nasdaq composite 
index was down 3.32 at 2,599.09 but regaining lost ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite some selling in technology issues, traders were  
optimistically picking up stocks on the growing belief that the 
second half of this year would bring strong corporate profits. The 
current crop of earnings reports has generally been very positive, 
including some pleasant surprises like IBM's first-quarter results, 
and analysts said that bodes well for the rest of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	A big impetus to buy has come from increasing signs that the  
global economy is recovering. That has increased trader appetites 
for economically-sensitive companies like Dow component Alcoa, 
which was up 2 7/8 at 58 1/4 today. Goodyear Tire &AMP; Rubber was up 1 1/8 at 
55 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Bryan Piskorowski, a market analyst with Prudential Securities,  
said there was some caution in the market today as traders awaited 
an earnings report from Amazon.com, scheduled to be released after 
the close of trading. Investors have been a little skittish about 
Internet stocks lately, and Amazon's results were being watched 
closely as a possible harbinger of what's to come for other online 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 6-to-5 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 114.36 million 
shares, down from Tuesday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was up 1.29 at 644.56, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index was down 0.04 at 774.03. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.09 percent. In  
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was down 4.07 percent, 
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.07percent, and France's CAC-40 was 
down 0.52 percent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
