<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Actors Lift 'Ring Around the Moon' </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *An AP Entertainment Review    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The champagne may not be served in the most  
stylish way possible, but there still is plenty of fizz in ``Ring 
Round the Moon,'' Christopher Fry's adaptation of French playwright 
Jean Anouilh's comedy. 
</P>
<P>
	Most of the effervescence is provided by two actors -- Toby  
Stephens, who fortunately plays twins, and Marian Seldes, 
Broadway's reigning interpreter of grandes dames -- of both the 
domestic and European varieties. 
</P>
<P>
	This elegant comedy demands the lightest of touches, something  
director Gerald Gutierrez doesn't always supply, either in his 
choice of supporting players -- whose acting varies wildly -- or in 
his uneven pacing of the play's three leisurely acts. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lincoln Center Theater production, which opened Wednesday at  
Broadway's Belasco Theater, looks delightful. Designer John Lee 
Beatty's setting of a winter garden in a French chateau is a giant 
white birdcage. The structure exudes an airiness and buoyancy that 
immediately lifts the audience, even before the story unfolds. 
</P>
<P>
	Anouilh's early 20th century fairy tale (the play is set in  
1912) concerns twins, two brothers with opposite personalities and 
philosophies. Hugo is the cynic, a petulant manipulator who wants 
to disrupt his brother's engagement to a wealthy young woman. 
Frederic is a romantic, insecure and perpetually trying to please. 
</P>
<P>
	Hugo hires a young ballet dancer to flirt with Frederic and win  
his heart. She does her job too well. It takes the intervention of 
the aunt, played by Seldes, to set everyone straight and pave the 
way for a happy ending, matching the right girl with the right boy. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephens, the son of Maggie Smith and Robert Stephens, does  
distinctive double duty. His Hugo is smugly confident, a peacock 
waiting to be plucked; his Frederic all a-quiver with trying to say 
and do the right thing. 
</P>
<P>
	Seldes' Madame Desmermortes may be confined to a wheelchair but  
she rules the stage. With a withering stare and a frosty voice just 
the right side of condescension, the actress tosses off Anouilh's 
bons mots with the authority of a championship tennis player. 
</P>
<P>
	The young ladies, played by Haviland Morris and Gretchen Egolf,  
are not nearly as memorable. A jarring Joyce Van Patten, as the 
ballet dancer's ambitious mother, seems to be in another play 
entirely, possibly a Neil Simon comedy rather than an elegant 
French comedy. 
</P>
<P>
	Anouilh's story eventually trips over itself, introducing too  
many subplots that are more confusing than they are funny. Such 
pros as Simon Jones and Fritz Weaver are defeated by the material, 
and Gutierrez has them pushing too hard for laughs. 
</P>
<P>
	Several veteran actors shine in minor roles, especially Frances  
Conroy as a dithering assistant to the despotic madame. Richard 
Clarke crumbles effectively as an aging butler. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, there is Seldes on hand to tie up all the loose plot  
points at the end of the evening. ``Ring Round the Moon,'' first 
done on Broadway in 1950, shows its age, but with her and Stephens 
around, this ``Moon'' often shines brightly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 19:32:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Arrest Made in Park-Ranger Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TILLAMOOK, Ore. (AP) -- A man accused of robbing two unarmed park  
rangers of their truck before marching them into dense forest and 
shooting them, killing one, was charged with murder Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Rangers Danny Blumenthal and John ``Jack'' Kerwin were  
inspecting a bathroom Tuesday at Oswald West State Park, about 65 
miles west of Portland, when they encountered Larry G. Cole inside. 
</P>
<P>
	Cole, 52, told the rangers he was tired of sleeping on the  
ground and wanted their truck, according to Candace Nelson, a 
neighbor of Kerwin's who talked to the ranger about the shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	He demanded their keys and wallets, which they gave him, then  
forced the rangers to walk across the highway and up a steep, 
wooded path about one-quarter mile. He tried to tie them to a tree, 
but apparently frustrated in his efforts, pointed a pistol at their 
heads and opened fire, police charge. 
</P>
<P>
	Blumenthal, 50, was killed. Kerwin, 51, lay motionless on the  
ground, feigning death, despite the gunshots to his jaw. When the 
gunman left, he made his way to the highway and flagged down a 
truck driver. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said Cole then fled the oceanside park in the ranger  
truck. He was arrested about an hour later. 
</P>
<P>
	Also Wednesday, police said a second man who was near the scene  
of the shootings was wanted for questioning. 
</P>
</TEXT>
