<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fortune Brands To Leave Connecticut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) -- Fortune Brands Inc. said moving its  
corporate headquarters from Connecticut to Illinois, and cutting 
about 60 jobs, will save $25 million to $30 million a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Fortune Brands Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Thomas C.  
Hays said the move from Greenwich to Lincolnshire, Ill., will be 
cost effective because the corporate office will then be located in 
the same building as the company's home and office businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's spirits and wine business is based in nearby  
Deerfield, Ill. Together, the three businesses represent more than 
80 percent of Fortune Brands' operations. 
</P>
<P>
	``But even with these compelling benefits, this was a difficult  
decision that will affect many dedicated associates and the 
community, and was only reached after extensive consideration,'' 
Hays said in a statement released Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The consumer products company now has about 185 corporate office  
employees, 150 of those at its corporate headquarters in Greenwich 
and the remainder in Deerfield and the United Kingdom. 
</P>
<P>
	Fortune Brands has operating companies with brands in home and  
office products, golf equipment, spirits and wine. Brands include 
Moen faucets; Titleist, Cobra and FootJoy golf equipment, and Jim 
Beam bourbon, Whyte &AMP; Mackay Scotch and Canyon Road wines. 
</P>
<P>
	The company plans to reduce corporate personnel by about a  
third. Spokesman Clarkson Hine said the company has offered 
employees a voluntary early retirement incentive program, which 
will be followed by a reduction in force. 
</P>
<P>
	Fortune Brands expects to record charges of approximately $60  
million to $70 million over the remainder of 1999 for 
restructuring, the move and other nonrecurring charges. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the corporate downsizing, the company plans to  
initiate further restructuring steps over the next 12 to 18 months 
to reduce its operational costs. The company said it expects an 
additional restructuring charge of between $100 million and $150 
million, but it said the moves will result in substantial savings 
when fully implemented. 
</P>
<P>
	Fortune Brands said it also has decided to change the method of  
accounting for evaluating the recovery of goodwill and other 
intangibles. The change, from an undiscounted cash flow basis to a 
discounted cash flow basis, will result in a noncash charge of 
approximately $1.2 billion in the second quarter. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
