<DOCNO> APW19990428.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 03:15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ill. Suburb OKs Anti-Gang Ordinance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CICERO, Ill. (AP) -- Leaders of this blue-collar Chicago suburb  
that mobster Al Capone once called home have a message for 
modern-day gangsters: Shape up or get out of town. 
</P>
<P>
	Under an ordinance approved Tuesday by the Town Board, anyone  
proved to be involved in illegal gang activity would be given 60 
days to leave Cicero or face a $500-a-day fine. 
</P>
<P>
	Gang members who promise not to commit more crimes could stay,  
but would be subject to a one-year probation. 
</P>
<P>
	``People in this town are petrified,'' said board member Mike  
Frederick. ``Some people are afraid to let their kids go outside 
because they're afraid they'll get shot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Town officials said the ordinance protects gang members' rights.  
Officials must hold a hearing and prove a person is a gang member 
and involved in crimes, said town attorney Barry Pechter. 
</P>
<P>
	Once banned, a gang member may not return, even to visit  
relatives. The ordinance also would apply to minors, whose parents 
either would have to move or give custody of their children to 
someone in another town, said town President Betty Loren-Maltese. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics say the measure is fraught with problems -- including the  
fact that the accused do not have to be convicted of their alleged 
crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	It also doesn't address crimes committed by people who are not  
gang members or whether a gang member can be kicked out for past 
crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	``This thing has so many holes in it, we don't know how it's  
going to all sort out,'' said Jay Miller, executive director of the 
American Civil Liberties Union's Chicago office. ``I don't 
understand what they're doing here and I don't think they 
understand it either. It's almost silly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller said his group has no plans to sue the town unless an  
ousted gang member asks for representation. 
</P>
<P>
	Town officials said they expect legal challenges but maintain  
the measure is necessary to fight crime in the Chicago suburb of 
70,000. The ordinance was endorsed by 95 percent of voters two 
weeks ago, and the seven-member Town Board unanimously enacted it. 
</P>
<P>
	Cicero has long had a reputation for mob activity. Capone, the  
Chicago mob boss during the Prohibition era, ran his bootlegging 
empire from the town after being driven from Chicago. And the 
federal government has been investigating corruption in the town 
for the last three years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0272 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 23:12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Jungle Fighting Camp To Close </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT SHERMAN, Panama (AP) -- It was a three-week trip to the  
tropics for the young man from Texas. The weather was hot and the 
water was close. But this was no vacation. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Avellaneda is a soldier. He came to this jungle base that  
once trained fighters for the Vietnam War to crawl through the mud 
and fight off mosquitos in one of the base's last military 
exercises. 
</P>
<P>
	After four decades, the base will be turned over to Panama on  
June 30 as part of the handover of all the U.S. installations here 
-- and finally the Panama Canal itself -- by the end of the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Fort Sherman, a 23,000-acre reservation on the Caribbean side of  
the canal, is the United States' only major jungle training camp. 
Located in the rain forest, it is home to snakes, monkeys, birds 
and wild cats. 
</P>
<P>
	But Avellaneda, a sergeant sent down from Fort Campbell, Ky.,  
wasn't admiring the scenery. 
</P>
<P>
	He was guarding a swamp with his M-4 carbine, his uniform  
covered in mud and his face painted. He dabbed insect repellent on 
his uniform, but it was no match for the mosquitos. He was tired 
after spending the night in the swamp. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a tough experience, but interesting, too,''  
Avellaneda said, catching his breath. ``It rains and it's sunny and 
hot. There are a lot of mosquitos.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sherman was built at the beginning of the century, but the Army  
started to use it for jungle training only in 1953. Many of the 
American soldiers who fought in Vietnam trained here, and the base 
also played host to joint exercises by U.S. and Latin American 
armies. 
</P>
<P>
	With its hot, humid climate and flat and hilly sections, Fort  
Sherman has been an ideal place for U.S. soldiers to learn the 
ropes of tropical combat. U.S. Navy sailors also have trained on 
the fort's Caribbean coast. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the only place to train in a tropical area with a  
structure like this,'' said Sgt. David Steward, an Ohioan in the 
Jungle Operations Training Battalion based at Ford Sherman. ``This 
has been like a school.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After Sherman closes, the U.S. Army plans to train its soldiers  
in joint exercises with other countries that have tropical rain 
forests, including Ecuador. 
</P>
<P>
	Panama, which doesn't have an army, plans to develop Fort  
Sherman into a resort for ecological and adventure tourism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 14:35:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Casino, Lottery Moratorium Urged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sharply divided, a panel studying gambling in  
America voted Wednesday to recommend a moratorium on the spread of 
casinos, lotteries and slot machines around the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Gambling Impact Study Commission cannot impose a  
moratorium, but its report will call for ``a pause'' in the growth 
of legalized gambling and encourage state and local governments to 
form their own gambling study commissions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some policy-makers at all levels may want to impose an  
explicit moratorium on gambling expansion while awaiting further 
research and assessment,'' reads language adopted by the 
commission, which has until June 18 to submit its report to 
Congress, the White House, governors and Indian reservations. 
</P>
<P>
	The nine-member panel split over the language, particularly the  
use of the word ``moratorium.'' Five commissioners approved the 
wording, while four voted no. At least one pro-gambling commission 
member, MGM Grand Inc. chairman J. Terrence Lanni, now plans to 
write a minority report. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a problem with the notion that we're going to stop the  
world or pause or create a moratorium'' just to wait for more 
research, said commissioner Robert Loescher, an Alaska businessman 
and native American. 
</P>
<P>
	Commissioner John Wilhelm, who represents casino workers as  
general president of the Hotel Employees and Restaurant Employees 
Union, said commissioners who support gambling endorse efforts to 
address its social costs, but the panel's gambling opponents 
``don't give a damn'' about jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Regarding the language encouraging a moratorium, Wilhelm  
proposed an additional sentence encouraging an expansion of 
gambling in ``economically depressed communities for which the 
economic benefits of gaming are most clear.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The commission defeated that language, leaving Wilhelm to warn  
that the report is becoming ``one-sided.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Our record is that in many kinds of communities in this  
country, including in particularly economically depressed 
communities -- urban and rural, as well as Indian reservations -- 
that there is a net positive economic impact'' from casinos, 
Wilhelm said. ``But you can't find that in any of these drafts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Commission Chairwoman Kay James pleaded for patience, saying,  
``We still have the ability'' to achieve consensus. The report is a 
work in progress, so ``anything can change,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Frank Fahrenkopf Jr., the casino industry's chief lobbyist in  
Washington, said he believes the commission will reconsider the 
disputed language at its final meetings in May or June. ``It's 
still just part of a draft,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In approving the moratorium idea, the commission called for what  
amounts to a national deep breath -- a moment to consider gambling's 
proliferation before more casinos are built and lottery games 
introduced. 
</P>
<P>
	``What we're saying is, there's not enough information, we need  
more research, we need more data, and whatever direction you're 
going to go, a pause is a prudent course at this point in time,'' 
James said. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress created the commission in 1997 to conduct a two-year  
study of the economic and social effects of legalized gambling, 
which has proliferated during the 25 years since the last national 
study. President Clinton and the congressional leaders of both 
parties divided up the nine commission appointments. 
</P>
<P>
	Numerous native American tribes refused to provide information  
on the casinos they operate, maintaining they are being asked to 
disclose proprietary financial information. Gambling commission 
members chose not to begin a court battle with the National Indian 
Gaming Commission, but James said the final report will note the 
lack of cooperation and recommend that Congress find a way to 
provide the information. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
