<DOCNO> APW19990428.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 15:35:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Conn. Gov. Says Pats Deal Is Solid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Gov. John G. Rowland dismissed the latest  
proposal Wednesday by Massachusetts lawmakers to keep the New 
England Patriots and compared it to Connecticut's dealings with the 
Hartford Whalers just before the team left for North Carolina in 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once a decision was made by the Whalers, they were gone,''  
Rowland said. ``Well, the Patriots are leaving (Massachusetts). 
They're gone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Massachusetts legislative leaders late Tuesday announced a plan  
to spend $70 million for roadways, sewer lines and other 
infrastructure for a new stadium in Foxboro. Under the plan, the 
Patriots would have to pay $1.4 million annually over 25 years in 
surcharges on off-site parking and stadium user fees. 
</P>
<P>
	Rowland said Connecticut's proposal to build a $374 million  
stadium and guarantee $13 million per year in luxury seat revenues 
dwarfs the offer by Massachusetts. 
</P>
<P>
	Rowland also pointed to the agreement the state had signed with  
Patriots owner Robert Kraft, the Connecticut Legislature's approval 
of the deal, and the environmental drilling that had already begun 
on the site of the proposed stadium to prove that the team's deal 
with the state was solid. 
</P>
<P>
	The Patriots submitted an application to the NFL last week for  
permission to move to Hartford. Kraft has until May 2 to back out 
if he decides Connecticut hasn't made sufficient progress. 
</P>
<P>
	The Patriots refused to comment on the Massachusetts proposal  
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	But Jay Malcynsky, a lobbyist representing the team in  
Connecticut, said he had spoken with Robert Kraft and his son 
Jonathan Wednesday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the Krafts didn't view the new plan as substantially  
different from an offer last year by Massachusetts House Speaker 
Thomas Finneran to spend $57 million in state money for 
infrastructure improvements near the stadium in Foxboro. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the same old dress on the same old dog,'' Malcynsky said.  
``Instead of $50 million, it's $70 million, and now they want Kraft 
to forfeit a portion of the parking revenues to pay the state's 
contribution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	None of the $70 million would help the Krafts pay for  
construction of a new stadium, Malcynsky said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Robert Kraft told me flat out, he's got the deal he wants, and  
it's in Hartford, Connecticut,'' Malcynsky said. 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL called the Massachusetts proposal ``a step in the right  
direction toward a Patriots alternative in Foxboro.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The statement said Massachusetts must also take other steps to  
keep the team, the most immediate of which should be a long-term 
commitment by the business community to buy luxury suites and club 
seats. 
</P>
<P>
	Legislative leaders in Massachusetts said they planned to pass  
the proposed legislation by May 25, when the NFL owners meet in 
Atlanta to vote on the Patriots' move, among other topics. NFL 
rules require the approval of three-quarters (24 of 31) of owners 
for a team to move. 
</P>
<P>
	Malcynsky said if the owners voted against a Patriots move to  
Connecticut, Kraft could sue the league, just as Raiders owner Al 
Davis did successfully when he moved his team from Oakland to Los 
Angeles in 1982. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 10:24:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nashville Sound: the ACM Awards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Country singer Jo Dee Messina fanned  
herself with her hand and fluttered her eyelids, doing a send-up of 
the classic Southern belle. 
</P>
<P>
	Messina, a Yankee from Massachusetts, was expressing her joy at  
receiving three nominations at this year's Academy of Country Music 
Awards, including best new female vocalist, best female vocalist 
and best album for ``I'm Alright.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The cool part is I get to sit on the ballot next to Faith  
Hill, Martina McBride, and all those people I love,'' the 
28-year-old singer said. 
</P>
<P>
	The ACM Awards show airs May 5 on CBS from 8-11 p.m. EDT from  
the Universal Amphitheater in Universal City, Calif. Nominees for 
best entertainer are Garth Brooks, the duo Brooks &AMP; Dunn, Tim 
McGraw, George Strait and Shania Twain. 
</P>
<P>
	Faith Hill leads all nominees with six. In addition to best  
female vocalist, she's up for best album for ``Faith''; song, 
single and video for ``This Kiss''; and best vocal event for her 
duet with husband Tim McGraw, ``Just to Hear You Say That You Love 
Me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The country music artist of the decade will be announced during  
the show. Previous winners were Marty Robbins for the 1960s, 
Loretta Lynn for the 1970s and Alabama for the 1980s. The smart 
money is on Garth Brooks for the 1990s, but Gene Weed, the show's 
producer, says George Strait and Reba McEntire also are strong 
contenders. 
</P>
<P>
	Messina's nominations cap a remarkable comeback for the country  
singer, who broke through in 1996 with two top 10 hits -- ``Heads 
Carolina, Tails California'' and ``You're Not in Kansas Anymore'' -- 
from her debut album, ``Jo Dee Messina.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She leased a bus, hired a band and hit the road after her debut.  
But expenses often ran higher than her paychecks. Then the release 
of a new album was delayed when Messina and her producers had 
trouble finding songs they thought could be hits. Bookings dried up 
and things became desperate. ``I owed everybody money. It was 
gross. I was so overwhelmed,'' Messina said. 
</P>
<P>
	Help from her record label, a local bank and a small endorsement  
deal with a trucking company got her through the end of last year. 
And ``Bye Bye,'' the first single from ``I'm Alright,'' went 
straight to No. 1. The album has already sold a million copies. 
</P>
<P>
	The ACM Awards is the first of three country music awards shows  
telecast each year. The fan-voted TNN Music City News Awards follow 
in June on The Nashville Network, and the Country Music Association 
hands out trophies in the fall. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in country music...  
</P>
<P>
	COUNTRY MILLENNIUM: Dolly Parton, Ray Charles, Jeff Foxworthy  
and Steve Wariner are among performers who will help bring in 2000 
at the Opryland Hotel in Nashville with four-days of performances 
from Dec. 30 to Jan. 3. Packages start at about $1,600. The Judds 
have already announced a New Year's Eve show in Phoenix, Ariz. 
</P>
<P>
	LIVE AT BILLY BOB'S: Famous Fort Worth, Texas, country music  
club Billy Bob's Texas is releasing a series of live albums 
recorded there. First up is Eddy Raven, Pat Green and Jon Conlee. 
Upcoming releases include Merle Haggard, Roy Clark, Waylon Jennings 
and Ray Price. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Nominees for Academy of Country Music Awards:  
</P>
