<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 1998 Campaign Spending Declined </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fewer competitive races meant fewer  
congressional candidates last year, and campaign spending declined 
for the first time in eight years. 
</P>
<P>
	Congressional candidates spent $740 million on their races in  
the 1997-98 election cycle, a decline of $25 million from what they 
spent in 1995-96, the Federal Election Commission reported 
Wednesday. The number of congressional candidates declined as well, 
from 2,605 in 1996 to 2,100 in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first drop in both the number of candidates and the  
money they spent running for Congress since 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Political observers said fewer candidates entered the races  
because many potential challengers felt they couldn't win. Many 
incumbents ran in districts with enrollment heavily tilted toward 
their political party, while others raised enough money to 
discourage strong challengers from taking them on. And party 
leaders focused only on those districts or states where they 
thought they had the best chances to win. 
</P>
<P>
	Ninety-four incumbents had no major party opposition in 1998,  
and another 114 faced opponents who raised $25,000 or less, 
according to Common Cause, an advocacy group that favors taxpayer 
financing of political campaigns. 
</P>
<P>
	``You have many people who feel they can't raise the money  
needed to reach the voters,'' said Kent Cooper, co-founder of 
Public Disclosure, an Internet consulting firm specializing in 
money and politics. ``At the same time, I don't think they really 
recruited in some of these districts. Someone on the national level 
said, 'We don't want to be spread too thin. Let's narrow our 
targets.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Democratic consultant Peter Fenn said the two parties had some  
problems lining up strong challengers. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the last cycle, it was harder for both parties to recruit  
challengers to incumbents because the conventional wisdom was that 
this was going to be a strong incumbent year,'' Fenn said. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest Senate spender in 1995-96 was Republican Alfonse  
D'Amato of New York, who lost his re-election bid to Democrat 
Charles Schumer despite spending $24.2 million. Schumer ranked 
third in spending with $16.7 million. Second was Republican Peter 
Fitzgerald of Illinois, who spent $17.7 million in ousting 
incumbent Democrat Carol Moseley Braun. 
</P>
<P>
	On the House side, former Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., spent  
$7.6 million, much of it to help fellow Republicans. But the next 
four biggest spenders all lost their races -- Democrat Philip Maloof 
of New Mexico; Democrats Christopher Gabrieli and John O'Connor of 
Massachusetts, both of whom lost a primary for the nomination to 
succeed retiring Rep. Joseph P. Kennedy II; and former Rep. Bob 
Dornan, R-Calif., who failed to win a rematch with Democratic Rep. 
Loretta Sanchez. 
</P>
<P>
	The average House candidate spent $247,268 last year and the  
Senate average was $1.1 milllion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
