<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Justices Ponder Meaning of Disabled </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court, trying to define the scope  
of a federal ban on discrimination, struggled Wednesday with a 
basic question: Who is disabled? 
</P>
<P>
	As the court heard arguments about two nearsighted women who  
want to be United Air Lines pilots and a truck driver blind in one 
eye, some justices questioned whether poor eyesight is a disability 
protected under the Americans With Disabilities Act. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have difficulty reading restaurant checks in dim light,''  
said Justice David H. Souter, who spoke of being ``at sea'' in 
trying to interpret the law. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Antonin Scalia added, ``I'm worried that everyone in the  
country is protected against discrimination based on a physical 
characteristic ... This statute wasn't meant to apply to all 
Americans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist asked whether someone who had  
an artificial leg but did not have a problem driving would be 
considered disabled. ``The employer says, you know, `I just don't 
want to take a chance with you.' Is he regarding that person as 
disabled?'' he asked. 
</P>
<P>
	By July, the justices are expected to use those cases and a  
third argued Tuesday to clarify who can sue under the ADA, a 1990 
law best known for requiring handicap access ramps in public 
buildings. Tuesday's case involves a Kansas man fired from his 
mechanic's job because of high blood pressure. 
</P>
<P>
	The ADA bars employers from discriminating against a ``qualified  
individual with a disability'' because of that disability. 
</P>
<P>
	A qualified person is defined as one who can perform a job when  
given reasonable accommodation, and a disability is a condition 
that substantially limits a major life activity. The ADA also 
protects people who are ``regarded as'' having a disability. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Aaron Hughes, the lawyer representing the two would-be  
pilots, argued that Karen Sutton and Kimberly Hinton were qualified 
to become pilots but were rejected because of United's 
``preconceived notion'' about nearsighted people. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Department lawyer Edwin S. Kneedler, arguing in support  
of the two women, said United tried to have it both ways by saying 
they were not disabled because their vision could be corrected, but 
refusing to hire them because of their poor vision. 
</P>
<P>
	Lower courts ruled the two were not protected by the ADA because  
their nearsightedness is fully correctable with glasses or contact 
lenses. 
</P>
<P>
	United's lawyer, Roy T. Englert Jr., said the airline's vision  
standard justified its decision not to hire the two women. 
</P>
<P>
	``This statute was absolutely not designed to make every  
employer ignore every disability,'' Englert said. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Stephen G. Breyer worried that some people with  
disabilities, such as those needing artificial limbs or deaf people 
with hearing aids, could be left out if their disabilities were 
viewed only in their corrected state. 
</P>
<P>
	Breyer also suggested that reading the law to protect people  
whose conditions easily are correctable might not lead to a large 
number of lawsuits because discrimination against such people 
``hardly exists.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The second case argued Wednesday was brought to the court by  
Albertson's supermarkets, which fired truck driver Hallie 
Kirkingburg after he failed a test to meet Transportation 
Department vision standards. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirkingburg performed well on a road test although he is almost  
blind in one eye. He sued Albertson's, saying it discriminated 
against him by refusing to let him go back to work after he got a 
waiver from the DOT standard. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal appeals court said Kirkingburg must be given a chance  
to prove his claim in a trial. 
</P>
<P>
	In his case, too, the justices seemed to have trouble reaching a  
comfortable definition of ``disabled'' or ``qualified.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This statute wasn't meant to apply to all Americans,'' said  
Scalia, but not before Justice Sandra Day O'Connor asked whether 
``Hooters'' restaurants could be sued for discriminating against 
some women because of physical characteristics if only women with a 
40 bra size were hired as waitresses. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
