<DOCNO> APW19990428.0288 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 12:34:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	House Votes To Limit Clinton on Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A divided House voted today to require  
President Clinton to get congressional approval before injecting 
``ground elements'' into the conflict in Yugoslavia. The 249 to 180 
vote to limit his ability to widen the war came despite Clinton's 
appeal to Congress that the United States must speak ``with a 
single voice'' on the crisis, as he said NATO had done. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Presses for Kosovo Funds  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton pressed Congress today to  
approve swiftly $6 billion to pay for the conflict with Yugoslavia, 
urging lawmakers to resist Republican-led efforts to double his 
request. A White House spokesman said that Clinton fears that ``any 
additional funding creates the potential for political fights and 
dangerous delay.'' Clinton accused Yugoslav President Slobodan 
Milosevic of waging a ``meticulously planned'' campaign to drive 
1.8 million ethnic Albanians from their homes in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Outspoken Yugoslav Official Is Ousted  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Yugoslavia's moderate deputy prime  
minister was fired today after urging Serb leaders to realize that 
``we cannot defeat NATO.'' Vuk Draskovic has been critical of 
President Slobodan Milosevic and urged compromise with NATO. 
Draskovic was once the main opposition leader before joining the 
government three months ago. A NATO spokesman has pointed to 
Draskovic's recent remarks as a sign of serious cracks in the 
Yugoslav regime. 

</P>
<P>
	White House Concerned About Jackson  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House expressed concern today about  
the Rev. Jesse Jackson's visit to Yugoslavia and indicated that 
NATO would not suspend its airstrikes while he is in Belgrade. 
Jackson and a delegation of U.S. religious leaders are to leave 
tonight to meet with three captive American soldiers and try to 
secure their freedom. The group is also expected to meet with 
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. 

</P>
<P>
	Marines Rejected Colorado Gunman  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- Columbine High gunman Eric Harris was  
rejected by the Marines just five days before the deadly attack for 
what the Pentagon described only as medical reasons, and he was 
said to be seeing a psychiatrist and taking psychiatric medicine. 
Harris had tried to enlist but was told by a recruiter visiting his 
home on April 15 that he had been rejected. Harris failed to 
disclose that medical factor during a telephone screening April 2. 

</P>
<P>
	Colorado Senate Condemns Stern  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- The Colorado senate passed a resolution  
today condemning radio personality Howard Stern for his wisecracks 
about the Columbine High School massacre. The censure called on 
KXPX to drop Stern's show. The day after the shootings, Stern 
reportedly wondered on his show whether the gunmen tried ``to have 
sex with any of the good-looking girls'' who fled the school. Also, 
a Denver TV station is pre-empting Stern's Saturday night show for 
a special on the rampage. 

</P>
<P>
	Second Dragging Death Trial To Move  
</P>
<P>
	JASPER, Texas (AP) -- A judge today approved a deal to move the  
second trial in the dragging death of a black man away from Jasper. 
Attorneys for Lawrence Russell Brewer claimed that Jasper County 
residents have a vested interest in convicting all three suspects 
in an effort to vindicate the town's image. Brewer is one of three 
white men accused of capital murder in the brutal slaying of James 
Byrd Jr., who was chained to the back of a pickup truck and dragged 
three miles along a rural road. John William King was convicted in 
February of capital murder and sentenced to death. 

</P>
<P>
	Study of Brain Comprehension Done  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A new study shows that humans' ability to  
understand speech is so deeply ingrained that people can even 
decipher sentences that have been recorded, chopped up into brief 
segments and played backwards. Researchers said the study shows 
that even if the message is distorted, ``other parameters are still 
able to convey the message.'' One professor said the research 
demonstrates that many areas of the brain are used to handle 
complicated auditory signals. 

</P>
<P>
	Building Collapses in Nigeria  
</P>
<P>
	LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) -- A building collapsed today in Nigeria,  
trapping dozens of people who sought shelter in the structure from 
a downpour, state radio reported. As many as 120 people could be 
trapped in the building in Lagos, the report said. At least two 
bodies had been recovered. The report said that the people were 
standing at a bus stop when it began to rain. Trying to get out of 
the downpour, they fled to the nearby building, which was under 
construction. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 94  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 94.21 to 10,925.92. Gainers on the New York Stock Exchange led 
losers 1,765-1,169. The Nasdaq was down 15.78 to 2,586.63. 

</P>
<P>
	Brewers' Vina Suspended  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Fernando Vina of the Milwaukee Brewers has been  
suspended for two games for putting a finger in the face of umpire 
Mike Winters during a dispute over balls and strikes. Vina was 
called out on strikes in a game in Pittsburgh on April 23. He 
angrily pointed his finger and apparently touched the umpire's 
face. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
</P>
