<DOCNO> APW19990428.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 15:25:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Budget Announces Online Bid Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LISLE, Ill. (AP) -- Budget Rent a Car will allow its customers to  
bid online to get the best price available, a move that extends the 
growing Internet auction business further into the travel industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Web surfers can already name their own prices for airline  
tickets, hotel rooms, new cars and home mortgages on priceline.com, 
a popular Internet site that links buyers with sellers willing to 
meet their bids. 
</P>
<P>
	Budget Group Inc., the parent of Budget Rent a Car, said  
Wednesday it will offer the car rental industry's first online 
bidding, beginning next month. 
</P>
<P>
	The program will give customers a chance at bargain prices and  
give Budget a way to rent cars that otherwise would have sat in a 
garage. 
</P>
<P>
	``It gives us an opportunity to control our fleet and enhance  
both revenue and utilization per vehicle,'' Sandy Miller, Budget 
Group's chairman and CEO said Wednesday. ``The notion of renting 
just one more car each day, in each city, will have a very positive 
financial impact on Budget. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like a hotel room. If it goes empty, you never get that  
day back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To make their bids, customers would go to the Budget Web site  
and click on the BidBudget icon. They would then fill out a short 
form showing location and dates they want the car picked up and 
returned, as well as the car type and the desired price. 
</P>
<P>
	Budget officials promise to respond within a day with an e-mail  
notifying the customer if the bid was accepted. 
</P>
<P>
	Budget Rent a Car, headquartered in the west Chicago suburb of  
Lisle, has more than 3,200 airport and local market locations in 
more than 120 countries and territories. 
</P>
<P>
	The Web site is www.drivebudget.com  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
