<DOCNO> APW19990428.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 15:15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stunned Senators Clean Out Lockers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANATA, Ont. (AP) -- After being swept in four games by the  
Buffalo Sabres, the Ottawa Senators talked of progress Wednesday, 
of learning how to make the next step toward becoming an elite 
hockey team. 
</P>
<P>
	``We realized how good we can be,'' said defenseman Wade Redden,  
heading for Norway to play for Canada at the world championships. 
``But what counts is the playoffs. Everyone is very disappointed 
after the way this ended. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got a lot to think about.''  
</P>
<P>
	After just barely qualifying for the playoffs for two seasons,  
the Senators raised the bar this year, amassing 103 points and 
finishing the regular season as the second best team in the Eastern 
Conference. But the second quickest team to clinch a post-season 
spot was the first to be eliminated after Tuesday's 4-3 loss in 
Buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
	Ottawa has the youngest average age of any NHL club, and  
defenseman Lance Pitlick says the experiences the team goes through 
now will make them a better club soon. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is the first time that we've had some kind of  
disappointment,'' he said. ``But it's no different than anything 
else. They say the best way to learn is from the school of hard 
knocks. We missed a few classes this year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ottawa coach Jacques Martin made reference to one of his old  
teams, the 1994-95 Quebec Nordiques. Martin was an assistant coach 
there when the Nordiques lost in the conference quarter-finals 
after finishing first in the Northeast Division with 104 points. 
The next season, after moving to Colorado, the former Nordiques won 
the Stanley Cup. 
</P>
<P>
	``The experience we've gained this year will help us in our  
progress next year,'' Martin said. ``Unfortunately, we had to take 
a step back with the loss to Buffalo. We've learned that success in 
the regular season doesn't automatically mean you'll be successful 
in the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems that it's a step for whatever reason. You have to  
learn from these experiences.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Senators could have other problems. Nine players -- Redden,  
Pitlick, Janne Laukkanen, Jason York, Bruce Gardiner, Ted Donato, 
Nelson Emerson, Radek Bonk and Magnus Arvedson -- will become 
restricted or unrestricted free agents this summer, and a handful 
more have options being held by the club. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
