<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Skin Cancer Ad Campaign Launched </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Donald Biederman lost his nose to skin cancer.  
Now, a picture of his face is the central feature of a highly 
graphic public service campaign designed to shock people into being 
more careful about exposure to the sun. 
</P>
<P>
	Biederman, a 64-year-old Los Angeles attorney is shown in TV and  
magazine ads removing his prosthetic nose, revealing a gaping hole 
left by 30 skin cancer operations. Above that image, in print ads, 
reads: ``Skin Cancer Can Kill You. And Now For the Really Bad 
News.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign was launched Wednesday by the American Academy of  
Dermatology, which represents 12,000 skin specialists. 
</P>
<P>
	However, whether most Americans will see it remains in question.  
The academy is asking media to run the ads for free as a public 
service. 
</P>
<P>
	ABC Television has already refused because of the content, but  
other networks are still considering them, according to the public 
relations firm that designed the campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	The effort aims to persuade Americans to protect themselves from  
harmful sun exposure and to visit a dermatologist at the first sign 
of any skin abnormalities. ``It certainly is an attention 
grabber,'' said Dr. Darrell Rigel, academy president and a 
dermatologist in New York City and Vail, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign is not meant to instill fear, he said. ``Fear has  
to do with something not factual, we are trying to get the facts 
across about what really might happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Skin cancer is the most common type of cancer; about 1 million  
Americans are expected to be diagnosed this year, including 44,200 
with the most deadly form called melanoma, according to the 
American Cancer Society. About 80 percent of the 9,200 skin cancer 
deaths expected this year come from melanoma. 
</P>
<P>
	A big reason behind the graphic nature of the campaign was  
Biederman's willingness to participate. 
</P>
<P>
	Biederman's saga began in 1995 when he noticed a red spot at the  
end of his nose. When it didn't go away after a few days, he had 
his dermatologist remove it. Doctors determined the growth was 
malignant. Since then Biederman has endured numerous surgeries as 
doctors tried to remove all the cancer, and then rebuild his face. 
</P>
<P>
	Since early 1997, doctors have told Biederman that he is  
cancer-free. Biederman thinks he knows what caused his cancer: 
Endless days on the beach and on his father's boat while growing up 
in Long Island, N.Y. He said he never used sun screen because his 
friends thought burning was the best way to ensure a healthy tan. 
</P>
<P>
	``We baked like lobsters,'' he said. ``It never occurred to me  
that I would pay a price years later.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some marketing experts caution that youngsters -- the main  
targets of the ads -- will ignore them. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the academy's assertion that the ads don't play to fear,  
Roland Rust, a professor of marketing at Vanderbilt University in 
Nashville, Tenn., said that's exactly what they do. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fear appeals have been used for years with varying success,''  
Rust said. ``Young people have a natural skepticism toward them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign's developer acknowledged that threats of death are  
often ineffective because of overuse. 
</P>
<P>
	``We felt a stronger wake-up call is that you may end up living  
with skin cancer and its highly destructive results,'' said Bill 
Johnson, creative director at Campbell Mithun Esty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
