<HEADLINE> Bishop Estate Resignations Sought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONOLULU (AP) -- The Internal Revenue Service is threatening to  
revoke the tax-exempt status of a wealthy trust for Hawaiian 
schoolchildren unless its five trustees resign, two newspapers 
reported Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRS made the mass resignation a condition for concluding its  
three-year probe into the Bishop Estate trust, The Honolulu 
Advertiser and the Honolulu Star-Bulletin reported, citing 
unidentified sources. 
</P>
<P>
	The trust, established to educate ``the children of Hawaii'' in  
1884 by the will of Princess Bernice Pauahi Bishop, has assets 
valued at up to $10 billion, making it one of the nation's richest 
private charitable trusts. 
</P>
<P>
	The state says the trustees invested $350 million in income  
instead of following the trust's direction and spending it on its 
beneficiary, the Kamehameha Schools, a 600-acre campus for 3,100 
students of Hawaiian descent on a wooded hillside overlooking 
downtown Honolulu. 
</P>
<P>
	Since 1997, the trustees have been involved in a melodrama of  
boardroom intrigue, questionable investments, IRS audits and 
criminal investigations. Several petitions seeking their removals 
have been filed. 
</P>
<P>
	Its tax-exempt status allows it to avoid paying millions of  
dollars a year in federal taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	The trustees, Henry Peters, Richard ``Dickie'' Wong, Gerard  
Jervis, Lokelani Lindsey and Oswald Stender, met Tuesday night to 
discuss the IRS demand. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRS in Honolulu did not return several calls from The  
Associated Press seeking comment. In the past, the agency has 
refused to confirm or deny that it was auditing the Bishop Estate. 
</P>
<P>
	Wong said Wednesday he had no immediate plans to resign. He also  
said trustees still are obtaining more information about the audit 
and were surprised by the IRS' stance. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not resigning because I'm not sure what I'm being accused  
of,'' Wong said. 
</P>
<P>
	A Bishop Estate spokesman did not return a message from The  
Associated Press seeking comment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
