<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Prostate Cancer Screening Faulted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Years after receiving good news about their  
prostate exams, 18 men were recently called by a suburban hospital 
and told there had been a mistake and they had cancer. Two other 
men had already died of what the hospital said were unrelated 
causes. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the errors, the cancer was left undiagnosed and  
untreated in the 20 men, perhaps lowering their chances of 
survival. 
</P>
<P>
	A pathologist at Sturdy Memorial Hospital in Attleboro had  
misread the men's biopsies, The Sun Chronicle of Attleboro 
reported. 
</P>
<P>
	``We feel shock, anger, disbelief -- there's nothing we can do,''  
said the wife of one misdiagnosed patient Wednesday, requesting 
that the family's identity and hometown be kept anonymous. ``We 
don't know what's going to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said her 62-year-old husband was told two weeks ago that his  
test had been misread. Her husband was told by his urologist to 
seek immediate aggressive radiation. It isn't clear yet how far the 
cancer has progressed, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The biopsies were performed between 1995 and 1997, The Sun  
Chronicle reported. The hospital said it reviewed 279 tests and 
discovered that 20 had been inaccurate. Of those 20, two patients 
have apparently died of unrelated causes, the hospital told the 
newspaper. 
</P>
<P>
	The biopsies were supposed to detect malignant cells in the  
prostate, a walnut-sized organ in men located just below the 
bladder. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at Sturdy Memorial refused to comment Wednesday and  
would not release the identities or conditions of the misdiagnosed 
men, or say what prompted the review. The hospital planned a news 
conference Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	The mistakes are under investigation by state medical  
authorities, who refused to comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Approximately 179,000 men are diagnosed with prostate cancer  
nationwide every year. About 37,000 men die of the disease each 
year, according to the American Cancer Society. 
</P>
<P>
	The five-year survival rate in men whose cancer is detected  
early and has not spread is nearly 99 percent, said Kara Smigel, a 
spokeswoman for the National Cancer Institute. If the cancer has 
spread to bones or organs, that figure drops to 32 percent, she 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	At least one recent cancer misdiagnosis case resulted in  
criminal action. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, a Wisconsin laboratory pleaded no contest to reckless  
homicide after failing to find obvious signs of cancer in Pap 
smears of two women who later died. Lawsuits against the lab, 
health maintenance organization and individuals were settled for a 
total of $9.8 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Sturdy Memorial is a small community hospital about 30 miles  
south of Boston. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
