<HEADLINE> Author Michi Weglyn Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Michi Nishiura Weglyn, who wrote a widely  
acclaimed book on the internment of Japanese-Americans during World 
War II, has died at age 72. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Weglyn died in New York on Sunday after a yearlong battle  
with cancer, according to a friend, Julie Azuma. 
</P>
<P>
	Her 1976 book, ``Years of Infamy, The Untold Story of America's  
Concentration Camps,'' described the experiences of some of the 
120,000 Japanese-Americans who were rounded up by the U.S. 
government in the early days of World War II and interned as 
security risks. 
</P>
<P>
	While the book was coolly received at first and even rejected by  
some bookstores, its powerful prose and solid documentation 
eventually helped spur demands for redress and a national apology 
by President Gerald Ford. In 1988, Congress granted $20,000 
settlements to thousands of former internees and their heirs. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Weglyn was born to Japanese immigrant farmers in Stockton,  
Calif. After Japan attacked Pearl Harbor, her family was sent with 
thousands of others to a desert camp in Gila River, Ariz. 
</P>
<P>
	A Quaker group gained her release so she could attend Mount  
Holyoke College in Massachusetts, which she eventually left due to 
illness. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Weglyn later became a New York costume designer and was  
drawn to social causes in the 1970s. She then became a familiar 
figure at the National Archives in Washington, D.C., poring over 
dusty documents from opening to closing time, pausing only to eat 
lunch. 
</P>
<P>
	Her research discredited President Roosevelt's 1942 claim that  
``military necessity'' justified the internments, and revealed that 
thousands of Japanese people from Latin American countries were 
also held in the U.S. camps. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Weglyn ``always had the people who had suffered inequities  
uppermost in her mind,'' said a friend, Bob Suzuki, president of 
California State Polytechnic University at Pomona. ``She was a hero 
to so many people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Weglyn's husband, Walter Weglyn, a Jewish refugee from the  
Netherlands, died in 1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0303 </DOCNO>
