<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teaching Hospitals Facing Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Some of the nation's top teaching hospitals say  
they are paying the price for the Balanced Budget Act of 1997, 
struggling to survive under a law designed to rein in Medicare 
costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Together with shrinking HMO reimbursements, the government  
budget cuts have led to thousands of layoffs, operating losses, 
deficits -- and could lead the hospitals to abandon their teaching 
and research missions. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is very accurate to call it an absolute crisis,'' said Neil  
Rudenstine, president of Harvard University. 
</P>
<P>
	Harvard's five major teaching hospitals have deficits totaling  
$150 million this year. Detroit's ailing hospitals have eliminated 
4,500 jobs since January. The University of Texas medical branch at 
Galveston projects a $110 million deficit next year. 
</P>
<P>
	All of the nation's 400 major teaching hospitals are on the same  
downward slope, Rudenstine said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``Two or three more years like this and you would have some  
institutions either going out of business or turning from their 
current mission to turning to for-profit,'' Rudenstine said. ``They 
wouldn't do teaching and they wouldn't do research because you 
can't have a for-profit that does that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Teaching hospitals train 75 percent of the nation's doctors,  
provide 44 percent of indigent care and perform the vast majority 
of clinical research. 
</P>
<P>
	``Burn units, trauma units, cardiac care units -- those are  
unique services you're more likely to find at a major teaching 
hospital,'' said John Parker, spokesman for the Association of 
American Medical Colleges. 
</P>
<P>
	Teaching hospitals in regions where managed care dominates the  
market are feeling the pain earliest. Georgetown University Medical 
Center in Washington, D.C., for example, has laid off workers under 
a strict cost-control plan. The center had a loss of $62.4 million 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Some hospitals have been further hit by state Medicaid cutbacks.  
</P>
<P>
	Welfare changes in Pennsylvania, which lowered payments for  
Medicaid patients, contributed to big losses at Philadelphia's 
teaching hospitals: In 1998, the University of Pennsylvania Health 
System lost $90 million on operations; the Temple University Health 
System lost $24.7 million; and the Jefferson Health System lost 
$30.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest looming problem, however, is the deepening cutback  
in Medicare, the single biggest source of revenue for teaching 
hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
	From 1998 to 2003, the Balanced Budget Act of 1997 ratchets down  
Medicare payments to hospitals, with the biggest hits coming in 
later years. So far, only 10 percent of the $9 billion in scheduled 
cuts have taken place. 
</P>
<P>
	The law will cost Massachusetts teaching hospitals alone $900  
million over five years, according to the Conference of Boston 
Teaching Hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's an extraordinarily painful and difficult issue,'' said  
Peter Van Etten, president and CEO of UCSF Stanford Health in San 
Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people have accused us of crying wolf in the past,'' he  
said. ``Given what we're going through with these reductions, 
that's not the case now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	UCSF Stanford recently announced plans to eliminate 2,000  
positions, or 15 percent of its work force, because of the Balanced 
Budget Act, state cuts in Medicaid and managed care. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
