<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obesity Risks Decline With Age </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Obesity is not as dangerous for elderly people as  
it is for the middle-aged or young adults, researchers reported 
today in the Journal of the American Medical Association. 
</P>
<P>
	The findings are similar to those in a study reported last year  
that indicated being overweight shortens life expectancy up to age 
75, but does not make much of a difference afterwards unless people 
are extremely obese. 
</P>
<P>
	``The absolute risk of dying gets higher and higher as you get  
older until you die, but the importance of obesity as a risk factor 
decreases,'' said Ralf Bender, an obesity researcher at the 
University of Bielefeld in Germany and principal author of the 
latest study. 
</P>
<P>
	Other researchers said the findings are not that meaningful.  
</P>
<P>
	``Obesity is a major public health problem at any age, and this  
study does nothing to suggest that that has changed,'' said Dr. 
JoAnn Manson, an endocrinologist at Harvard Medical School. 
</P>
<P>
	In the latest study, researchers studied 6,193 obese men and  
women who ranged in age from 18 to 74, following them for an 
average of 14.8 years. The patients, who were referred to an 
obesity clinic between 1961 and 1994, were grouped by their age and 
body mass index. 
</P>
<P>
	Body mass index, or BMI, is increasingly becoming the standard  
way of talking about obesity, since it is an easy way to compare 
the girth of people of different heights. BMI is body fat in 
kilograms divided by height in meters squared. 
</P>
<P>
	According to dietary guidelines issued by the Department of  
Agriculture, a BMI of 25 to 29.9 is considered overweight and 30 
and above is obese. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers found that the mortality risk for a really obese  
person -- with a BMI of 40 or more -- was highest for those age 30 or 
younger. Moderately obese men and women -- with a BMI between 32 and 
40 -- who were age 50 or older had the lowest mortality risk, the 
study says. 
</P>
<P>
	Some researchers not involved with the study argued that BMI is  
a limited measure of obesity in the elderly because bone density 
declines with age. They also noted that the study participants were 
recruited rather than randomly selected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 21:13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Execs Convicted of Trade Espionage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	YOUNGSTOWN, Ohio (AP) -- The conviction of two Taiwanese  
executives in the first trial under the 1996 Economic Espionage Act 
may deter others who consider spying on a competitor, a security 
managers trade group said. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, a federal jury convicted the two adhesive industry  
executives of paying an Ohio-based Avery Dennison Corp. researcher 
to slip them confidential reports. 
</P>
<P>
	Pin Yen Yang, 72, president of Four Pillars Enterprise Co. Ltd.,  
and his daughter, Hwei Chen ``Sally'' Yang, 40, were each found 
guilty of two counts of economic espionage. The jury also found 
Four Pillars guilty of the same charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph Ricci, a spokesman for the American Society for  
Industrial Security in Alexandria, Va., said the case is important 
because it means the federal law worked in its first real test. 
</P>
<P>
	``This will deter people from getting involved in economic  
espionage, and it gives us more power to protect our secrets,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities say the Yangs received secrets about adhesives used  
in products such as self-stick postage stamps, name labels, diaper 
tape and battery labels. 
</P>
<P>
	Defense attorneys immediately filed for a mistrial, arguing that  
federal prosecutors did not prove their case. U.S. District Court 
Judge Peter Economus did not immediately rule on the motion and did 
not say when he would make a decision. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yangs face a maximum penalty of 10 years in prison. No  
sentencing date was set. The company will be fined according to how 
much Economus determines Avery Dennison lost because of the spying. 
</P>
<P>
	When the Yangs were arrested in 1997, the FBI estimated the  
company lost as much as $200 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Philip Neal, Avery Dennison's president and chief executive,  
released a statement saying he was ``extremely pleased'' with the 
verdicts. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice Department spokesman John Russell said ``the statute was  
used here as Congress intended -- to stop corporations from stealing 
trade secrets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But defense attorney Nancy Luque said the law was misused  
against the Yangs and Four Pillars. 
</P>
<P>
	``Prosecutors in this case jumped at the chance to participate  
in the first court test of the Economic Espionage Act, which was 
enacted to keep high-tech secrets out of the hands of foreign 
governments,'' she said. ``But we have maintained all along that 
this case was a gross misapplication of the EEA and we plan to 
appeal the jury's verdict.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan-based Four Pillars is an adhesives maker that competes  
with Avery Dennison, based in Pasadena, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors said Yang and his daughter paid about $160,000 over  
eight years to Avery Dennison researcher Ten Hong ``Victor'' Lee, 
who worked at a laboratory east of Cleveland. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee, a Taiwanese native, testified he struck a deal to pass  
information to the Yangs while on a trip to his homeland in 1989. 
Lee said he worked with the Yangs until 1997, when he was caught. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee pleaded guilty to wire fraud and began cooperating with the  
FBI. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors' case hinged on a secretly record FBI videotape  
showing a September 1997 meeting between the Yangs and Lee, in 
which Sally Yang cuts the ``confidential'' stamp off an Avery 
Dennison report. Pin Yen Yang then instructs Lee to dispose of the 
clipping. 
</P>
<P>
	But in closing arguments, defense attorneys said Avery Dennison  
indiscriminately marked documents as confidential. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yangs originally were charged with 21 counts each but  
Economus dismissed 18 of them before the jury began deliberating. 
The jury worked for three days before delivering a verdict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0309 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 16:05:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mrs. Clinton Takes On Afghan Gov't </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The predicament of women living under tight  
restrictions imposed by Afghanistan's Taliban leaders must not be 
forgotten, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We cannot go into the 21st century without doing everything  
within our power to try to stand against such human rights 
violations and against the perils of indifference,'' Mrs. Clinton 
said at a Capitol Hill luncheon honoring Sen. Dianne Feinstein, 
D-Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	The Taliban, who seized control of the government in 1996,  
follow a strict and disputed interpretation of Islamic law that 
requires women to wear the burqa, a garment covering them from head 
to toe, while out in public or risk being beaten. Women must stay 
indoors unless accompanied by a close male relative. 
</P>
<P>
	``When women are savagely beaten by so-called religious police  
for not being fully covered by the burqa or for making noises while 
they walk, we know that it is not just the physical beating that is 
the objective. It is the destruction of the spirit of those women 
as well,'' Mrs. Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The government also has banned girls from going to school. Male  
doctors are prohibited from treating sick women in Afghanistan, and 
women are not allowed to work, let alone practice medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	``The women of Afghanistan, while other women are moving  
forward, are being pushed brutally backward in time,'' Mrs. Clinton 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The group Physicians for Human Rights honored Feinstein for her  
work on the issue a day after it released a report critical of 
diminishing health care and human rights for women in Afghanistan. 
</P>
<P>
	``Today we honor especially what (Feinstein) has done to bring  
to public attention and work toward the end of the widespread 
violations of women's rights in Afghanistan,'' Mrs. Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Feinstein has spearheaded efforts to pass a Senate resolution  
calling for an end to the abuse of woman and girls in that country. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton told the story of an Afghan teacher who was shot to  
death over a year ago in front of her students after refusing to 
close down a home school for girls. 
</P>
<P>
	Relatives living in refugee camps in Pakistan told human rights  
observers the woman was shot in the head and stomach in front of 
about 40 students and her family after Taliban militia burst into 
her home demanding that the school be closed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can honor her memory ... by not forgetting her story and  
her willingness to stand against the forces of violence and 
oppression,'' Mrs. Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	The health of Afghan women and girls has worsened in the past  
year with the addition of new restrictions, the report said. 
Foreign humanitarian groups have been expelled from the country and 
the government has closed the few health care facilities that were 
open to women. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
