<HEADLINE> 3 Charged With Tomato-Field Slavery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IMMOKALEE, Fla. (AP) -- Three men were arrested on extortion and  
slavery charges Wednesday for allegedly smuggling Mexican migrants 
into the United States and forcing them to work in southwest 
Florida tomato fields. 
</P>
<P>
	Twenty-seven migrant workers were freed following the arrests.  
</P>
<P>
	``This effectively dismantles an alien smuggling enterprise,''  
U.S. Attorney Charles Wilson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brothers Abel Cuello Jr. and Brasillo Cuello, both of Immokalee,  
and Herman Covarrubias of Bonita Springs were arrested early 
Wednesday by U.S. Border Patrol agents. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities also were searching for a fourth suspect, whose name  
was not released. 
</P>
<P>
	A criminal complaint charges the four men with conspiracy to  
hold individuals in involuntary servitude, extortion and harboring 
aliens. 
</P>
<P>
	Harboring illegal aliens is punishable by up to 10 years per  
immigrant. The maximum penalty for the other charges is 36 years in 
prison and a $250,000 fine. 
</P>
</TEXT>
