<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Durable Goods Orders Rise 2 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Orders to U.S. factories for big-ticket  
manufactured goods jumped a larger-than-expected 2 percent in 
March, raising hopes that better days may be ahead for America's 
beleaguered manufacturing sector. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department reported Wednesday that the March  
increase in orders for durable goods followed a 3.9 percent decline 
in February, which was revised upward to show more strength than 
the initial estimate of a 4.9 percent plunge. 
</P>
<P>
	The currency crisis that has pushed one-third of the globe into  
recession has severely cut into American exports and also opened up 
U.S. manufacturers in such sectors as steel to increased 
competition from cheaper priced foreign goods. 
</P>
<P>
	While the overall U.S. economy has been performing well,  
manufacturers have been forced to cut more than 300,000 jobs in the 
past year as America's trade deficit hit record levels. 
</P>
<P>
	But analysts noted that the better-than-expected March rise in  
orders represented the fourth gain in factory demand in the past 
five months. 
</P>
<P>
	``The manufacturing sector may be turning the corner,'' said  
Joel L. Naroff of Naroff Economic Advisers in Holland, Pa. ``It is 
too soon to declare an end to manufacturing's long hard winter, but 
spring appears to be bringing a new bloom to this sector.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gordon Richards, chief economist of the National Association of  
Manufacturers, said that while the rebound in March was skewed by 
strength in the volatile transportation sector, there were 
encouraging signs of strength in other sectors, including consumer 
electronics. 
</P>
<P>
	The indication of new life in manufacturing helped lift spirits  
even higher on Wall Street. The Dow Jones industrial average closed 
at another record, although prices fell on the inflation-sensitive 
bond market as traders adopted a more cautious approach before 
release of a report Thursday on wage pressures in the U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The overall 2 percent in durable goods orders was led by a 3.6  
percent jump in demand for autos, airplanes and other 
transportation goods. Without this increase, the overall advance 
would be been a smaller 1.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Demand for industrial machinery rose 2.9 percent last month  
while orders for electronic equipment were up 3.1 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The one area of weakness was primary metals, including steel, a  
sector that is petitioning the government for higher tariffs to 
slow a flood of cheaper foreign steel from coming into the United 
States. In March, orders for primary metals for U.S. plants fell 
1.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Orders for military goods soared 36.2 percent in March.  
Excluding defense items, orders for all other goods rose 1 percent 
for the month. 
</P>
<P>
	Shipments of durable goods, which economists closely watch for  
signals about current conditions, rose 1.3 percent in March, 
following a much weaker 0.1 percent February gain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
