<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Doc Apologizes for Taking Research </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) -- A Japanese doctor apologized for taking  
medical research from the Mayo Clinic and agreed to help the 
prestigious institution validate years of study that were 
compromised by his actions. 
</P>
<P>
	All charges against Dr. Yoichi Ito will be dismissed if he  
fulfills the conditions of a negotiated agreement within six 
months, said Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael Ward. The agreement 
was reached Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ito, 32, downloaded research information dating back to 1990  
onto disks, photographed the laboratory and took tissue samples, 
gene-sequencing data and original research books critical to the 
lab's work. 
</P>
<P>
	The orthopedic surgeon had nearly completed a two-year research  
fellowship at Rochester-based Mayo when he was arrested March 25, 
days before his scheduled return to Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not clear why Ito took the research, the U.S. attorney's  
office said. In his apology, Ito said that taking the material was 
``reckless'' because the tissue samples could have been lost or 
stolen. 
</P>
<P>
	Ito's attorney, Charles Hawkins, said his client had permission  
to take some tissue and slides with him to continue his research in 
Japan, but mistakenly thought he could also take data and 
additional samples. 
</P>
<P>
	He now expects to finish the required work at Mayo within two  
weeks and then return home, Hawkins said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
