<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 1998 Campaign Spending Declined </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The number of congressional candidates dropped  
last year, when many challengers who didn't have a real chance to 
win decided not to run. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Election Commission said 2,100 candidates ran for  
the House and Senate in 1998, down from 2,605 in 1996. The amount 
of money they spent declined as well, from $765 million in the 
1995-96 election cycle to $740 million in 1997-98. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first drop in both the number of candidates and the  
money they spent running for Congress since 1989-90. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican political consultant Jack Cookfair said some  
candidates figured that if they couldn't win in 1996, a 
presidential election year when voter turnout is higher, they 
weren't going to win the next time. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you couldn't get it done in '96, you couldn't get it done  
in '98,'' Cookfair said. ``I assume there were many districts like 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other political observers said prospective candidates saw that  
they couldn't raise the money to run a competitive race. 
</P>
<P>
	Overall, 94 incumbents had no major party opposition in 1998,  
and another 114 faced opponents who raised $25,000 or less, 
according to Common Cause, an advocacy group that favors 
overhauling the way congressional campaigns are funded. 
</P>
<P>
	``The money is typically so dominated by incumbents that  
challengers can't compete or they don't even run at all,'' said 
Donald Simon of Common Cause. ``We're simply having fewer and fewer 
real elections.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest Senate spender in 1995-96 was Republican Sen.  
Alfonse D'Amato of New York, who lost his re-election bid to 
Democrat Charles Schumer despite spending $24.2 million. Schumer 
ranked third in spending with $16.7 million. Second was Republican 
Peter Fitzgerald of Illinois, who spent $17.7 million in ousting 
incumbent Democratic Sen. Carol Moseley-Braun. 
</P>
<P>
	On the House side, former Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., spent  
$7.6 million, much of it to help fellow Republicans. But the next 
four biggest spenders all lost their races -- Democrat Philip Maloof 
of New Mexico; Democrats Christopher Gabrieli and John O'Connor of 
Massachusetts, both of whom lost a primary for the nomination to 
succeed retiring Rep. Joseph P. Kennedy II; and former Rep. Bob 
Dornan, R-Calif., who failed to win a rematch with Democratic Rep. 
Loretta Sanchez. 
</P>
<P>
	The average House candidate spent $247,268 last year and the  
average Senate candidate spent $1.1 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
