<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 200 Arrested in Car Theft Crackdown </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- FBI agents have launched a crackdown on auto  
theft rings across the nation, setting stings with the help of 
state lawmen against dozens of traders in the international market. 
</P>
<P>
	State and federal agents have targeted more than 200 people for  
arrest in 22 cities in Operation Sudden Stop; almost 100 are 
suspected of running major operations in the San Antonio region, 
150 miles from Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	``We felt like a lot of the cars we weren't recovering were  
going into Mexico,'' police Lt. Mike Ross said Tuesday. ``They 
would go out all in one day and steal this number of cars that were 
on their shopping list.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Auto thefts are declining -- down 3.8 percent in 1997 and 16.5  
percent since 1993. But FBI Assistant Director Thomas Pickard said 
recoveries of stolen vehicles also are down, and only 14 percent of 
auto thefts result in arrests, ``the lowest success rate for any 
major crime.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pickard blamed the low rate in part on the FBI's ``lack of focus  
on it due to violence in the cities.'' He said in the early and 
mid-1990s, the FBI and state and local police shifted agents from 
interstate theft work to higher priority operations against violent 
street gangs and drug traffickers. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, 1.4 million vehicles worth $8 billion were stolen and  
nearly 447,000 were never recovered. Pickard said the FBI and 
Customs Service estimate that 200,000 of these were shipped 
overseas for resale. 
</P>
<P>
	Pickard said they found theft rings whose members came from  
traditional 1930s organized crime groups and others made up 
primarily of Russian or Asian organized crime figures. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI worked in task forces with the Customs Service; the  
National Insurance Crime Bureau, a nonprofit insurance industry 
group; and state and local police and U.S. attorneys. 
</P>
<P>
	They used surveillance, informants, wiretaps and even set up  
undercover storefronts to buy stolen parts. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to San Antonio, authorities said arrests had  
happened or were expected in Cleveland; Columbia, S.C.; Detroit; 
Houston; Indianapolis; Las Vegas, Nev.; Little Rock, Ark.; Memphis, 
Tenn.; Miami; Mobile, Ala.; Oklahoma City; Salt Lake City; San 
Diego; San Juan, Puerto Rico; Springfield, Ill.; St. Louis; Tampa, 
Fla.; Pittsburgh; Omaha, Neb.; Sacramento, Calif.; and Los Angeles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
