<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Futures Soar on Inventory Data  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Crude oil futures soared back above $18 a barrel Wednesday on  
the New York Mercantile Exchange after weekly inventory figures 
showed sharp declines, signalling producers are adhering to 
promised cutbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, palladium futures fell sharply, while grains  
and soybeans advanced. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude jumped after the American Petroleum Institute reported  
U.S. inventories tumbled 4.7 million barrels last week to 336.4 
million barrels after a sharp decline in imports. 
</P>
<P>
	The decline -- nearly four times the size of analysts'  
expectations -- was the first strong indication that world oil 
producers are finally serious about slashing daily output to 
sustain higher prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries and  
other key producers agreed to remove 2.1 million barrels daily from 
the market beginning April 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts have said if they succeed at reducing about two-thirds  
that amount, supplies would be cut enough to force prices higher. 
</P>
<P>
	American inventories now are 6.6 million barrels lower than this  
time a year ago and could get smaller. Venezuela, widely considered 
one of the weak links in meeting quotas, announced its output will 
fall below current production targets as some refineries undergo 
maintenance. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, some analysts cautioned that reports of tanker loadings  
show an increase in activity that could cause supplies to rebound 
in May. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude for June delivery rose 62 cents to $18.45 a barrel; May  
heating oil rose 1.06 cents to 44.11 cents a gallon; May unleaded 
gasoline rose 1.29 cents to 53.89 cents a gallon; May natural gas 
rose 1.7 cents to $2.348 for each 1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Palladium futures tumbled 4 percent on the New York Mercantile  
Exchange after Russia's main producer of the industrial metal said 
it had resumed shipments after a long halt. 
</P>
<P>
	The giant Norilsk Nickel mine, the main Russian producer, said  
Monday it had resumed shipments after a four-month absence from the 
market that had driven prices sharply higher. 
</P>
<P>
	Western manufacturers, particularly Japan, used palladium in  
cleaner-burning emissions controls for cars and in electronics. 
Russia, which producers about two-thirds of the world's supply, 
however, has not shipped the metal since December amid bureacratic 
wrangling. 
</P>
<P>
	June palladium fell $15.50 to $335.50 an ounce.  
</P>
<P>
	Grain and soybean futures advanced on the Chicago Board of Trade  
after the Clinton administration moved to ease some sanctions 
against foreign buyers. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices rose after President Clinton acted to exempt food and  
medicine from future sanctions, a decision that could significantly 
boost export demand for beleaguered American farmers. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the new policy, commercial licenses to sell agricultural  
and medicinal products under existing U.S. sanctions -- against 
Cuba, Iran, Iraq, Libya, North Korea and Sudan -- will be reviewed 
on a case-by-case basis. 
</P>
<P>
	Futures prices also rose amid continued uncertainty about  
weather conditions in Midwest growing regions. The National Weather 
Service is calling for normal temperatures and above-normal 
rainfall over the next week, while some private forecasters say 
showers will only be scattered. 
</P>
<P>
	The answer will determine whether farmers will be able to  
proceed with fieldwork already delayed by heavy recent rains. 
</P>
<P>
	July wheat rose 3 1/2 cents to $2.63 1/2 a bushel; July corn fell 1/4  
cent to $2.19 1/2 a bushel, while other contract months rose; July 
soybeans rose 2 cents to $4.89 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
