<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chief Khmer Rouge Torturer Found </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) -- The feared chief of the Khmer  
Rouge's security service, who ordered the torture and killing of at 
least 14,000 men, women and children in the late 1970s, has been 
found, a newsmagazine reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The discovery of the man known as Duch was to appear in  
Thursday's issue of the Hong Kong-based Far Eastern Economic 
Review, the weekly said. 
</P>
<P>
	British photographer Nic Dunlop and Review reporter Nate Thayer,  
who in 1997 became the first outsider to see the notorious Khmer 
Rouge leader Pol Pot in 18 years, met Duch. 
</P>
<P>
	Duch disappeared when the Khmer Rouge were toppled in 1979 and  
has long been presumed dead. Actually, he converted to Christianity 
and worked until late last year with various international aid 
organizations who were unaware of his identity. 
</P>
<P>
	The government privately confirmed awareness of Duch's general  
whereabouts two years ago, though no move was made to take him into 
custody. 
</P>
<P>
	Duch, 56, told the Review that he was deeply sorry for the  
killings and was willing to face an international tribunal. Genuine 
remorse would contrast with the grudging apologies offered by some 
Khmer Rouge leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Duch's emergence could increase pressure on Prime Minister Hun  
Sen to bring Khmer Rouge leaders to trial. In theory, he could be 
the key witness, able to implicate those above and below him. 
</P>
<P>
	Youk Chhang, director of a documentation center that has  
gathered evidence for such a trial, shook his head in amazement 
today when shown a recent image of Duch by Associated Press 
Television News, which has obtained exclusive video shot by Dunlop. 
</P>
<P>
	``What's important is to have him alive,'' Youk Chhang said.  
``He's the key person who could testify as to how the leaders 
advised him, in terms of security, on assassination and killing of 
the so-called enemies of the revolution.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duch brought the organizational abilities of the teacher he once  
was to his job as security chief, helping create the Khmer Rouge 
nightmare. 
</P>
<P>
	The best estimate -- made by the U.S.-funded Cambodian Genocide  
Program -- is that 1.7 million Cambodians out of a population of 7.9 
million were killed, tortured, starved or worked to death during 
the 1975-1979 Khmer Rouge reign. 
</P>
<P>
	Duch -- born Kaing Khek Iev in 1942 -- headed the internal  
security organization and was the director of Tuol Sleng, a Phnom 
Penh high school transformed into an interrogation prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Victims were chained to bed-frames and tortured to force false  
``confessions'' -- often to spying for the United States and Vietnam 
-- and then executed in a field outside the capital, where a pile of 
skulls serves as their memorial. 
</P>
<P>
	Only seven people out of thousands survived Tuol Sleng.  
</P>
<P>
	One, artist Vann Nath, 53, was kept alive to paint propaganda  
pictures. After the Khmer Rouge fell, he painted scenes of the 
horror that now hang on the walls of Tuol Sleng, which has been 
made into a genocide museum. 
</P>
<P>
	Shown a recent photograph, Vann Nath had no problem recognizing  
his former jailer. 
</P>
<P>
	``Duch,'' Vann Nath said, pointing. ``Even though he is old, I  
recognize him. He's alive.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked whether Duch and other Khmer Rouge should be prosecuted,  
Vann Nath said: ``That's up to the government, not to me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Experts say prosecution would be easy. His signature is  
everywhere. A 1978 document shows that 17 children whose parents 
were suspected of treachery were brought to Tuol Sleng. Duch signed 
an order saying, ``Kill them all.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Such notes went to Pol Pot, the Khmer Rouge leader who was  
himself toppled in a power struggle in 1997 and died a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Mass executions of members of the old government followed the  
Khmer Rouge victory over a U.S.-backed regime in 1975. The cities 
were emptied and the entire population forced into rural slave 
labor camps. 
</P>
<P>
	Vietnam invaded Cambodia on Christmas Day 1978, and took Phnom  
Penh two weeks later. Hanoi's troops found the last victims of Tuol 
Sleng, executed while still chained to the beds, blood smearing the 
floor. 
</P>
<P>
	Duch reportedly fled just ahead of them, but not before  
executing a prisoner who had helped him destroy documents. 
</P>
<P>
	Supported by the United States, China and Thailand, the Khmer  
Rouge fought from the jungles against Vietnam's occupation through 
the 1980s. They rejected a U.N. peace plan and kept fighting 
against a Cambodian government elected in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Only one senior Khmer Rouge figure, hard-line general Ta Mok, is  
in custody awaiting trial. Most other leaders are living in freedom 
in exchange for making peace with the government. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors indicated this week that they may charge Nuon Chea  
and Khieu Samphan, two close lieutenants of Pol Pot. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0332 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 23:32:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Changing Sanctions Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Government experts believe an easing of  
restrictions on the sale of humanitarian items to adversary 
countries could increase American wheat and corn exports by 1 
million tons. 
</P>
<P>
	One such country, Iran, has a pending request for the purchase  
of $500 million worth of American grain and sugar. U.S. officials 
said there was no certainty the request would be approved, despite 
the easing of sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
	Other countries eligible to purchase humanitarian items under  
the rules change announced Wednesday are Libya and Sudan. The three 
countries are on a State Department list of state sponsors of 
terrorism, but the Clinton administration concluded that sanctions 
on exports of food and medical items were counterproductive. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sales of food, medicine and other humanitarian necessities do  
not generally enhance a nation's military capacity or support 
terrorism,'' Undersecretary of State Stuart Eizenstat told 
reporters. ``On the contrary, funds spent on agricultural 
commodities and products are not available for other, less 
desirable uses. Our purpose in applying sanctions is to influence 
the behavior of regimes, not to deny people their basic 
humanitarian needs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barring such sales usually fails to hurt targeted regimes while  
depriving American companies of export opportunities, officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new policy is part of a broader attempt at comprehensive  
sanctions reform. The goal is to resort to unilateral sanctions 
only after all other options, including diplomacy and multilateral 
sanctions, have been exhausted. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., welcomed the policy shift, saying in  
a telephone interview that the administration has, in effect, been 
telling farmers, ``You pay the cost of our foreign policy.'' He 
added: ``Fidel Castro and Saddam Hussein have never missed a meal 
because of our sanctions policy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Under the changed approach, humanitarian items will be exempted  
from future sanctions. Wednesday's announcement will not affect 
Iraq, North Korea and Cuba, all sanctioned countries where 
conditioned sales of certain items are already permitted. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Foreign Relations Committee Chairman Jesse Helms, R-N.C.,  
said the new policy entails only modest changes that he could 
support. Helms said he had received assurances that food and 
medical sales to affected countries will be carried out only if 
there are no U.S.-backed subsidies of any kind. 
</P>
<P>
	``If Iran wants to pay cash-on-the barrel for American grain,  
that's fine with me,'' he said. ``Every dollar that Iran spends on 
U.S. farm products is a dollar that Iran cannot spend on terrorism 
or weapons of mass destruction.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
