<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990428.0333 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 10:05:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A Recluse No More: Salman Rushdie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It was no ordinary reading. Bags, briefcases and  
knapsacks were banned. Picture IDs were required. The hundreds of 
people entering the Great Hall at Cooper Union were frisked and 
scanned like airline passengers during a state of alert. 
</P>
<P>
	When the theater lights dimmed, the audience snapped into  
silence. A few minutes and two short introductions later, a smiling 
Salman Rushdie walked on stage. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sorry about the inconvenience,'' the author said mildly, his  
voice accented more by his adopted country, England, than by his 
native India. ``But we're all inside now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He had plotted this drama. The location was revealed days in  
advance. He chose a setting where previous speakers include 
anarchist Emma Goldman and statesman and journalist Frederick 
Douglass. He was undeterred by the fate of one predecessor, whose 
picture hung on the back wall: Abraham Lincoln. 
</P>
<P>
	Rushdie read for half an hour from his new novel, ``The Ground  
Beneath Her Feet,'' a reworking of the myth of Orpheus and Eurydice 
as lived out by an Indian rock band. He sounded confident, 
determined. ``I'm still alive,'' one passage from the book read, 
``and I've been spat at and called names only a couple of hundred 
times.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For another half hour, Rushdie took questions. He was  
congratulated, analyzed, criticized. The tensest moment came after 
one woman offered a few complimentary words. She then approached 
the stage, security men responding in kind, and held up what 
appeared to be a bouquet of carnations. 
</P>
<P>
	It was indeed a bouquet of carnations.  
</P>
<P>
	``There are writers who don't like reading their work and there  
are writers who do,'' Rushdie said to applause. ``I am one of the 
latter.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With each question, he seemed less a myth, more a writer.  
Audience members had actually read him, not simply about him. One 
said his books were difficult (Rushdie didn't disagree). Another 
asked why his female characters were so loud and devouring, so 
larger than life. (Rushdie cited his three sisters as inspiration.) 
</P>
<P>
	Like his characters, Rushdie is not quite a man of this world.  
He is famous, controversial, an object of morbid fascination. He 
can write about rock stars not only because he knows some -- Lou 
Reed and U2's Bono are among his friends -- but because he has some 
idea what it is to be one. 
</P>
<P>
	And just as rock stars like the road, so does Rushdie. The  
``fatwa'' ordering his death came as he was about to tour the 
United States to promote ``The Satanic Verses.'' Now the threat is 
at least partly lifted and he's touring again, as if resuming a 
conversation cut off a decade ago. 
</P>
<P>
	``When the fatwa came down,'' said his friend, John Irving, ``I  
remember thinking it couldn't have happened, for a lot of reasons, 
to a worse person. 
</P>
<P>
	``The kind of solitude that was suddenly imposed, the  
reclusiveness that became mandatory. I know a lot of writers for 
whom this wouldn't have changed their lives so traumatically. But 
Salman went everywhere and did everything and was a real social, 
urban guy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A few days before his reading, Rushdie sat for an interview. He  
was supposed to meet for dinner at a midtown Manhattan cafe, but at 
the last moment thought it wiser to avoid crowds. A snag had 
developed that no security measures could prevent: The author had 
the flu. 
</P>
<P>
	So, instead, he remained safely at the midtown offices of his  
agent, Andrew Wylie, a celebrity among agents whose clients include 
Saul Bellow, Norman Mailer and Philip Roth. 
</P>
<P>
	Without so much as a quick frisk, a reporter entered the office  
suite, the only visible security a large man in the reception area 
who wore a blue suit and did not smile. 
</P>
<P>
	Seated on a couch in a back room, Rushdie at 51 looks like a  
hip, tenured professor: round face and salt-and-pepper beard, 
wrinkled blazer, wrinkled khakis, unwrinkled T-shirt. He is relaxed 
and friendly, an articulate man who, but for his flu, likely could 
have talked into the night. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he feels ``80 percent'' safe, a change from last fall  
when he joyously, perhaps prematurely, told the media that his 
troubles were over. The Iranian government had distanced itself 
from the fatwa and Rushdie declared that the ``last chapter'' of 
his ordeal was complete, even boasting he was ``happy'' not to be a 
Muslim. 
</P>
<P>
	But now he shares the concerns that friends like authors Susan  
Sontag and Paul Auster have expressed about him. Religious leaders 
and others in Iran and elsewhere still wish him dead. He remains a 
prize both for determined enemies and misguided fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``Individual crazies are things lots of so-called well-known  
people have to deal with,'' Rushdie said. ``And there are ways of 
dealing with it, as individuals. It doesn't always work -- John 
Lennon, Gianni Versace -- but usually you can construct a private 
life and guard yourself against the individual crank.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There is murder in his new novel, and disasters of a more  
natural kind. ``The Ground Beneath Her Feet'' is set in Bombay, 
London and New York City. It has three main characters: Vina 
Apsara, a world famous rock singer; guitarist and songwriter Ormus 
Cama, her lover and band mate; and the narrator, a tone-deaf 
photographer known as Rai. 
</P>
<P>
	Just as Eurydice died and Orpheus descended to the underworld to  
retrieve her, Vita is lost in an earthquake in Mexico and Ormus 
tries to bring her back, even finding someone else he thinks is 
her. In this book, reality itself rests on a fault line. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Ground Beneath Her Feet'' is, and is not, a work of  
fiction. It is set in the counterculture of the 1960s, '70s and 
'80s. But this culture lives only in the author's mind. President 
Kennedy survives Dallas, John Lennon sings Rolling Stones music and 
Nathan Zuckerman writes a controversial novel called ``Carnovsky'' 
(both fictional creations of Philip Roth). 
</P>
<P>
	Rushdie also reinvents some personal history. The fictional  
earthquake happens on Feb. 14, 1989, the day the late Ayatollah 
Ruhollah Khomeini's fatwa was announced. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted the date to mean something different for me. I didn't  
want it to have just this terrible meaning. And I thought, `Now, 
it's the date my novel begins.' It's a way of repossessing my 
life,'' Rushdie said. 
</P>
<P>
	Before his name was in headlines, it was in bookstores. He was a  
gifted young writer, admired for his uninhibited language, his 
storytelling and his humor, likened to Gunter Grass and Gabriel 
Garcia Marquez. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's just such a wonderful writer,'' said Nobel laureate  
Nadine Gordimer, ``somebody who's extravagant, wild, full of 
wonderful imagination, bursting with ideas. 
</P>
<P>
	``And as he himself has said, `What a writer is for, is to say  
the unsayable.' And that's what he has done and that's what brought 
him so much trouble. But there is so much tenderness and love of 
life in his book. People simply know about the fatwa and the 
offense he has supposedly caused. But they haven't read the 
books,'' the South African writer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rushdie has written seven novels, a collection of short stories  
and three nonfiction books. His second novel, ``Midnight's 
Children,'' won the Booker Prize and is regarded by many as among 
the finest works of fiction of the past 30 years. ``The Satanic 
Verses'' and ``The Moor's Last Sigh'' are nearly as acclaimed. 
</P>
<P>
	The odd experience of reading his work is that you can't always  
tell what preceded the fatwa and what came after. In ``Midnight's 
Children,'' published in 1981, the narrator defines himself as 
``destined to forsake privacy, and be sucked into the annihilating 
multitudes.'' He is a man ``handcuffed to history.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The narrator is, and isn't, Salman Rushdie. Both were born in  
Bombay in 1947. But his character was born in August, at the very 
moment of India's independence. Rushdie was born two months before. 
</P>
<P>
	His father was a businessman, both parents storytellers. They  
were Muslim, but remained so more out of convenience than creed. 
One reason the fatwa shocked him was that Rushdie had grown up in a 
household that tolerated the most blasphemous thoughts. 
</P>
<P>
	``My grandfather was very religious. He said his prayers five  
times a day. (But) ... he was the most open-minded man,'' Rushdie 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	``You would sit down next to him and you would say,  
`Grandfather, I don't think there's a God.' And he'd say, `Really? 
Tell me all about it.' And I'd say, `Well, where does he live? He 
doesn't live in the sky. There are airplanes in the sky.' And he'd 
say, `That's true,' and he'd just hear you out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What Rushdie considered an ordinary childhood changed as a  
teen-ager when he went to mission school in England. Racism rudely 
expanded this bright kid's mind. He was aware for the first time of 
being separated by color and culture, themes that appear in 
virtually all of his work. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Rushdie remained in England, studying history at his  
father's alma mater, King's College, Cambridge. He worked in 
underground theater, then as an advertising copywriter, writing 
fiction in his spare time. 
</P>
<P>
	Like the narrator of ``The Moor's Last Sigh,'' Rushdie is an  
``information magpie.'' His influences include Greek and Roman 
literature, ``The Wizard of Oz,'' Shakespeare, Indian mythology, 
Elvis Presley and ``The Thousand and One Nights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His first novel, the science fiction story ``Grimus,'' was  
published in 1975 and soon forgotten, likely the only uneventful 
book he will write. Over the next few years, Rushdie said, he 
realized that the best way to free his mind was to begin with 
something he knew. 
</P>
<P>
	The result was ``Midnight Children,'' in which he re-created his  
childhood Bombay and then narrated the city's downfall. Acclaimed 
worldwide, the novel was especially influential in India, a 
statement of literary independence the way ``Leaves of Grass'' was 
for American writers. 
</P>
<P>
	``In India, the English language had come to be considered a  
symbol of the shame of colonialism,'' fellow Indian author Anita 
Desai later wrote. Rushdie transformed it into a symbol of India's 
energy and diversity, ``revitalized what had seemed faded, dormant 
and close to decay.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rushdie said he never intended to be controversial (he naively  
thought everyone shared his opinions), but even before ``The 
Satanic Verses'' he was getting in trouble. The Gandhi family took 
offense to his portrayal of Prime Minister Indira Gandhi in 
``Midnight's Children.'' His next novel, ``Shame,'' was no kinder 
to the government in Pakistan, where the book was banned. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he meant ``Satanic Verses'' to be based on his  
experiences in England. Religion was part of it -- the Prophet 
Mohammed and the origins of the Koran are duly satirized -- but 
hardly all of it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Satanic Verses'' was published in England in the fall of  
1988 to rave reviews. India, South Africa and other countries 
banned it. Protesters burned it. Riots killed five in Pakistan. In 
India, one person was killed and over 100 injured. 
</P>
<P>
	Khomeini then announced the fatwa, which promised Rushdie's  
killer a place in heaven, and several Iranian leaders put a $5.2 
million bounty on Rushdie's head. The novel rushed to the top of 
best-seller lists. The author rushed into hiding. 
</P>
<P>
	``At first, I was less scared than disappointed,'' Rushdie said,  
who hid in Britain. ``You spend five years, which is what `Satanic 
Verses' took to write, really breaking yourself apart, stretching 
yourself, trying to utter something you hope is of interest and 
value. 
</P>
<P>
	``Then you're told that all you've done is insult someone. ...  
And I thought, all that work and is this what I get?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Writers throughout the world defended him. Petitions were  
signed. Rallies staged. Committees established. A memorable 
reaction was a poem from ``Invisible Man'' author Ralph Ellison: 
``Keep to your convictions/Try to protect yourself/A death sentence 
is a rather harsh review.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But support was not universal, even among non-Muslims, even  
among writers. Former President Jimmy Carter thought his book ``a 
direct insult.'' Author Roald Dahl called him a ``dangerous 
opportunist.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Personal feuds developed. In 1993, Rushdie divorced his wife,  
American author Marianne Wiggins, who initially joined him in 
hiding. She later said that Rushdie was self-obsessed and failed to 
help lesser-known authors in danger, a charge he called ``a serious 
defamation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, novelist John le Carre said Rushdie was ``arrogant''  
and that ``there was no law in life or nature that says great 
religions may be insulted with impunity.'' Rushdie called le Carre 
``pompous'' and a ``philistine.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I never used to be called arrogant until I started to defend  
`Satanic Verses,''' Rushdie says now. ``When you write a book and 
commit a public act, if you can't stand up for it then you're an 
idiot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His revenge, and his salvation, was to keep writing. In 1990, he  
published ``Haroun and the Sea of Stories,'' a short fable about a 
storyteller battling the evil opponents of imagination. Then came a 
collection of stories, ``East, West.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, he published ``The Moor's Last Sigh,'' his first  
full-length work since the fatwa. The book is narrated by an exiled 
storyteller whose body ages at double speed. Its tone is urgent, 
defiant. ``Fear,'' Rushdie wrote, is ``like any bullying tyrant, it 
rules your life with a stupid blinding omnipotence, or else you 
overthrow it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I always knew that before the page could be turned I actually  
had to write the next big novel,'' Rushdie said during the 
interview. ``I had to show myself that I hadn't been wrecked by it. 
... There was a lot riding on it. And there were a lot of people 
waiting for me to take a tumble.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ten years after the fatwa, Rushdie says he has never been  
happier. He is remarried, with a daughter who is nearly 2. He is 
deeply grateful to those who spoke out on his behalf. He is proud 
that he avoided two traps set by the fatwa: writing timid novels, 
or writing bitter ones. 
</P>
<P>
	What he learned, he says, is not how bad people can be but how  
good. If Rushdie were to write a memoir, it would resemble, of all 
things, what he calls ``The Ground Beneath Her Feet'': a love 
story. 
</P>
<P>
	``The mayhem continues, I don't deny it, but we're also capable  
of this,'' he writes near the end of the novel, when the narrator 
winds up in a calm, happy relationship. ``(D)rinking o.j. and 
munching muffins. Here's ordinary human love beneath my feet. Fall 
away, if you must, contemptuous earth; melt, rocks, and shiver, 
stones. I'll stand my ground, right here.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
