<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Yugoslav President's Hometown Bombed  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Belgrade television is reporting  
that a NATO missile struck the Yugoslavian President's Slobodan 
Milosevic's hometown. The Beta news agency said a ``powerful 
blast'' shattered windows in Pozarevac, 40 miles southeast of 
Belgrade. Last week, NATO missiles demolished one of Milosevic's 
Belgrade residences, although he had not been staying there. 
Meanwhile, Milosevic's regime has fired a deputy premier who 
suggested Belgrade was ready to accept key NATO demands for ending 
the crippling air campaign. 

</P>
<P>
	House Denies Support for Airstrikes  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A divided House Wednesday night withheld its  
support for U.S. airstrikes in Yugoslavia after voting to limit 
President Clinton's authority to use ground troops. The House first 
voted 249 to 180 to make Clinton obtain congressional approval 
before sending ``ground elements'' to Yugoslavia. Then Democrats 
sought approval of a resolution to bestow after-the-fact blessings 
on the NATO bombing campaign. Despite the support of Republican 
Speaker Dennis Hastert, it failed on a 213-213 tie. 

</P>
<P>
	Teen Pregnancy Rate Keeps Falling  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Teen pregnancy plummeted 17 percent in the  
1990s to the lowest level since 1973, and teen abortion rates were 
down, too. Researchers point to a mix of reasons, including more 
reliable contraception, fear of AIDS, a new focus on abstinence and 
even the strong economy. New statistics from the Department of 
Health and Human Services show that births to teen-agers fell 4 
percent in 1997, helping to push the national birth rate for all 
women to a record low. 

</P>
<P>
	IMF To Resume Lending to Russia  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The International Monetary Fund announced late  
Wednesday it had reached an agreement in principle with Russia on a 
new economic reform program. IMF Managing Director Michel Camdessus 
said negotiations had resolved the major issues that had prevented 
the IMF from resuming a lending program cut off in August. After a 
few ``technical elements'' are resolved, Camdessus said he would 
take the request for loan approval to the board and expected 
endorsement for $4.5 billion in new IMF loans. 

</P>
<P>
	Police Link Teen to Colo. Shooting  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- Authorities linked an 18-year-old  
student to the Columbine High School gunmen, saying she bought 
three of the four guns used in the massacre. Investigators had said 
gunman Dylan Klebold's girlfriend, Robyn Anderson, bought two 
shotguns and a rifle last fall. A semiautomatic TEC DC-9 handgun 
has not yet been traced. Authorities have repeatedly said Anderson 
is considered a witness and not a suspect. A sheriff's spokesman 
also reaffirmed that three young men detained near the school 
shortly after the attack had been cleared of any involvement. 

</P>
<P>
	Bush Headlines $14M GOP Fund-Raiser  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The last Republican president is helping the  
GOP raise $14 million to try to win back the White House, and the 
beneficiary may be his son. Former President Bush was the scheduled 
big draw at the Republican National Committee's annual black-tie 
gala Wednesday night, which party officials said would set a 
fund-raising record. Texas Gov. George W. Bush is the front-runner 
for the GOP presidential nomination. 

</P>
<P>
	Ford Cancels Plans for Brazil Plant  
</P>
<P>
	DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- Ford Motor Co. announced Wednesday that  
it has canceled plans to build a new auto plant in a southern 
Brazilian state, a month after the government pulled a financial 
incentive package for the project. The Rio Grande do Sul state 
government said the $257 million incentive package extended to the 
Brazilian subsidiaries of Ford and General Motors Corp. was needed 
for infrastructure projects. 

</P>
<P>
	Stocks Mixed; Dow Closes Up 13.74  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices were mixed Wednesday but the Dow  
industrials gained 13.74 to close at 10,845.45, another record 
high. The Nasdaq fell 52.04 to 2,550.37. Japan markets were closed 
Thursday for Greenery Day. 

</P>
<P>
	Walker Hits 3 Homers, Drives in 8  
</P>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Larry Walker of the Colorado Rockies hit his  
first three home runs of the season and drove in eight runs 
Wednesday night against the St. Louis Cardinals. Walker hit a 
three-run homers in each his first two at-bats against Jose 
Jimenez. After singling in the fifth, he hit a two-run homer off 
Scott Radinsky in the seventh for a 9-6 lead. With a chance to tie 
the major league mark for home runs in a game, Walker grounded out 
in the ninth. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAN BOYLAN  
</P>
</TEXT>
