<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Lighter Side of Business /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *Tidbits From the Business World    	
</P>
<P>
	REVAMPING THE ANNUAL REPORT: Most corporate annual reports are  
slick publications, filled with stunning photos of corporate 
headquarters and research labs and shots of beaming customers and 
contented workers. Cognex Corp., which makes machines that inspect 
products during manufacturing, takes a different approach with its 
1998 report. Printed on plain brown paper and illustrated with line 
drawings and graphs that use pine trees instead of bars, the report 
is set up like an adventurer's guide. It has chapters called 
``Terrain,'' ``Navigation'' and ``Climate'' to detail its 
performance. The report has quotes from well-known people such as 
Oliver Wendell Holmes and Alexander Graham Bell (``leave the beaten 
track occasionally and dive into the woods''), and the only photo 
is of chairman Robert Shillman, wearing safari garb. The report 
does say Cognex's results dropped last year due to the Asian 
economic crisis, and says business should be better this year 
although ``it's still going to be chilly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	VANISHING BONUSES: While many Americans hope for a big cash  
bonus at work, most of them don't seem to have too much fun with 
the money once they get it. A survey of 1,000 Americans taken by 
the polling company Wirthlin Worldwide for American Express found 
that 29 percent of the respondents used their last cash bonus or 
reward to pay bills. Another 18 percent don't remember where the 
money went. Only 9 percent used the money for something special, 
and 5 percent took a vacation. Other uses for the money included 
gifts for family members, the purchase of household items and 
deposits to savings. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	BUSINESS IS GOING SWIMMINGLY: The booming economy and more  
secure paychecks has prompted more homeowner to install swimming 
pools, reports the National Spa &AMP; Pool Institute. The trade group 
says inground pool sales rose 14 percent last year, a big increase 
over a 0.6 percent increase in 1997. Installation of the pool 
itself can cost up to $25,000, with decking, landscaping and other 
features adding to the price. The institute says there are 
currently about 3.8 million residential inground pools in the 
United States. 



</P>
</TEXT>
