<DOCNO> APW19990428.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-28 16:05:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coyotes Look To Finish Off Blues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- Nobody understands better than the Phoenix  
Coyotes how difficult it is to go from where they are to where they 
want to be. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coyotes have a 3-1 lead on the St. Louis Blues and could  
close out the first-round series and move into the second round for 
the first time in 12 years with a victory in Game 5 Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	But their pursuit of the Stanley Cup has ended in the first  
round seven times since 1987, and the Coyotes have been 
tantalizingly close. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1990, the then Winnipeg Jets had a 3-1 lead on Edmonton but  
lost the next three games while the Oilers went on to win the 
championship with a goaltender named Grant Fuhr. 
</P>
<P>
	Winnipeg was ahead of Vancouver 3-1 in 1992, and the Coyotes had  
a 2-1 lead on Detroit last year. 
</P>
<P>
	In each case, the other team swept the last three games and took  
momentum into the second round while the Coyotes cleaned out their 
lockers for the summer. 
</P>
<P>
	``This isn't over by any means,'' said Rick Tocchet, who helped  
Pittsburgh win the Cup in 1992. ``It's a long series, and they're 
not going to quit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Winning that fourth game is going to be a bear,'' coach Jim  
Schoenfeld said. ``As well as we played, and I'm extremely pleased, 
I think we're going to have to play much better.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Coyotes earned their commanding lead with a 2-1 victory  
Tuesday night, their third straight one-goal victory since the 
Blues beat them 3-1 in the series opener. 
</P>
<P>
	Displaying the kind of self-sacrifice that Schoenfeld called  
for, Phoenix players blocked 14 shots and blanked St. Louis in four 
power plays, an area in which the Blues were dominant the first 
three contests. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Adams, back after two games out to rest a groin pull,  
scored the first goal, and Dallas Drake got the winner with 35 
seconds left in the second period, deflecting a shot by Teppo 
Numminen as Fuhr gave up his 11th goal of the series. 
</P>
<P>
	In the third period, Keith Tkachuk frequently braved the hardest  
slap shot in the NHL, flopping crosswise on the ice in front of St. 
Louis' Al MacInnis to keep MacInnis from unleashing his 100 mph 
blasts on Phoenix goalie Nikolai Khabibulin. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's real frustrating,'' Blues center Terry Yake said. ``We  
were in good position in Game 2 to maybe take a 2-0 lead and come 
home and take control of the series, and here we are in just the 
opposite situation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Numminen is the only Coyote who played a full season with  
Winnipeg in 1991-92. 
</P>
<P>
	Tkachuk, the team captain, played in 17 games that season, and  
believes the past means nothing because of the turnover. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are 20 other guys here,'' Tkachuk said.  
</P>
<P>
	Blues defenseman Chris Pronger sees hope for extending the  
series and returning to St. Louis for a sixth game on Sunday -- not 
in the Coyotes' past but in his team's 14-4-1 record in its last 19 
regular-season road games. 
</P>
<P>
	``Over the last 20 games or so, we've shown we can win on the  
road,'' Pronger said. ``We've won in there before, and now we've 
got to win two there to win the series. It will be an uphill 
battle. We just have to take the next game and not look too far 
ahead.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
