<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Marfan Patients Urged On Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Surgery to correct a life-threatening heart defect  
in people with Marfan's syndrome is far safer if done before 
symptoms develop. 
</P>
<P>
	Marfan's is an inherited disorder of the connective tissue.  
Those who inherit it are often unusually tall and are likely to 
have weakened aortas that can rupture disastrously, causing death. 
</P>
<P>
	In the early 1970s, the average life expectancy of people with  
the disorder was about 45. But it is now in the 70s, in part 
because of the use of open-heart surgery to repair weakened aortas. 
</P>
<P>
	New research concludes that this repair should be performed as  
soon as the defect is diagnosed. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Vincent L. Gott and others from Johns Hopkins University  
compared the results of routine aorta repair with waiting until the 
condition causes symptoms, when the surgery often must be done as 
an emergency operation. They reviewed the records of 675 patients 
who underwent aorta repair between 1968 and 1996. The study was 
published in Thursday's New England Journal of Medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those who got elective surgery, about 2 percent died  
during the month following the operation. However, when the 
operation was considered an emergency, 12 percent died. 
</P>
<P>
	About 200,000 people in the United States have Marfan's  
syndrome. If they are found to have weak spots in the aorta, the 
body's main blood vessel, the defect can be fixed with Dacron 
replacement tubes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
