<HEADLINE> 4 Die in Florida Small Plane Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	VERO BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- Four people on their way to the Bahamas  
were killed on Wednesday when their small plane crashed into a 
neighborhood shortly after takeoff. 
</P>
<P>
	The single-engine Cessna 210 crashed between three homes near  
Vero Beach Municipal Airport, where the pilot had attempted to 
return after reporting mechanical trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane lost its wings as it hit a tree and a power pole  
before landing in the neighborhood and bursting into flames. No one 
on the ground was injured. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could hear the people moaning and we tried to help,'' said  
Keith Chisholm. ``But at that point there was nothing we could 
do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The plane was registered to John Tinthoff, of Peoria, Ill., who  
sheriff's officials said was aboard the aircraft. The identities of 
the three others were not immediately known. 
</P>
<P>
	Vero Beach is about 65 miles north of West Palm Beach.  
</P>
</TEXT>
