<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Mixed; Dow Up 85.33 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices were widely mixed Wednesday, with  
blue chips pushing higher as investors kept on buying big 
industrial stocks, but technology shares lower on profit-taking. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 85.33 at 10,917.04 after rising 113.12 Tuesday to a new closing 
high of 10,831.71. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
index was off 1.75 at 1,361.05, and the Nasdaq composite index, 
which is heavily weighted in technology stocks, was down 23.56 at 
2,578.85. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were back in a trading pattern that began last week.  
They were buying the previously ignored stocks of companies whose 
fortunes are closely tied to the economy, in response to growing 
signs that the global economy is recovering. 
</P>
<P>
	That pushed up the shares of industrial stalwarts like Dow  
component Alcoa, which was up 4 5/8 at 60. Another Dow stock, Goodyear 
Tire &AMP; Rubber, was up 1 5/8 at 55 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	The enthusiasm for manufacturing stocks was bolstered by this  
morning's Commerce Department report that orders to factories for 
big-ticket durable goods rose 2 percent in March after an 
end-of-winter slump. The increase followed a 3.9 decline in demand 
for durable goods in February, although revised figures released 
today pegged that drop at much lower than the 5.0 percent first 
estimated. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors were generally optimistic about corporate profits for  
the second half of this year. The current crop of earnings reports 
has generally been very positive, including some pleasant surprises 
like IBM's first-quarter results, and analysts said that bodes well 
for the rest of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	IBM, which has surged higher over the past week, was down 4 1/16  
at 207 15/16 today amid profit-taking. 
</P>
<P>
	Other technology stocks were falling as traders collected  
profits, and analysts reported lingering anxiety about Internet 
stocks that have soared in recent months. 
</P>
<P>
	Bryan Piskorowski, a market analyst with Prudential Securities,  
said there was some caution in the market today as investors 
awaited an earnings report from Amazon.com, scheduled to be 
released after the close of trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Amazon's results were being watched closely as a possible  
harbinger of what's to come for other online companies. The 
company's stock was down 8 3/4 at 197 1/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of America Online, which surpassed analyst expectations  
in an earnings report issued late Tuesday, were down 4 1/16 at 148 
15/16. Lycos, which runs an internet search engine, was down 2 
11/16 at 98 5/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil stocks were higher as crude prices rose on an unexpected  
decline in domestic supplies. Dow component Exxon was up 2 15/16 at 
81 3/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 13-to-9 margin on  
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 747.72 million 
shares, up slightly from Tuesday's pace. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
