<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Northeast, South Seek Milk Compacts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Regional dairy compacts that set prices for  
milk are stirring a new political war in Congress, with lawmakers 
from the Northeast and South uniting against the Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	``Establishing permanent dairy cartels is a poor legislative fix  
and bad precedent to deal with low milk prices,'' Sen. Russ 
Feingold, D-Wis., said Tuesday. Added Rep. John Boehner, R-Ohio, 
``Renewing and expanding these price-fixing regimes would be a 
devastating step backwards.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At issue are regional dairy compacts in which states band  
together and set what they consider a ``fair price'' for fluid 
milk. A commission funded with dairy producer contributions 
controls the operations and establishes a price higher than the 
federal government's price for the commodity. 
</P>
<P>
	Congress established the Northeast Dairy Compact as part of the  
1996 farm law, covering Connecticut, Maine, Massachusetts, New 
Hampshire, Rhode Island and Vermont. But it's due to expire Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	That compact's authorization is due to expire Oct. 1.  
</P>
<P>
	Legislation introduced Tuesday would make the Northeast compact  
permanent and add Delaware, New Jersey, New York, Pennsylvania, 
Maryland and Ohio to it. 
</P>
<P>
	It also would also establish a Southern Dairy Compact to include  
Alabama, Arkansas, Kentucky, Louisiana, Mississippi, North 
Carolina, South Carolina, Tennessee, Virginia, West Virginia. 
Florida, Georgia, Missouri, Oklahoma, Texas and Kansas also could 
join it. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill has 39 cosponsors in the Senate and more than 150 in  
the House. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters say the compacts shield already-struggling dairy  
farmers from fluctuating prices. Just last February, the government 
said the price producers received for milk would fall $6 to $10.27 
per hundred pounds of milk, the sharpest decline from one month to 
another in the industry's history. 
</P>
<P>
	``For us to stand by and do nothing is totally irresponsible,''  
said Sen. Mary Landrieu, D-La. ``This is a life and death issue for 
our family farms,'' added Rep. John E. Sweeney, R-NY. 
</P>
<P>
	Opponents argue that compacts serve the interests of a few,  
harming consumers and scores other producers. Lawmakers from the 
Midwest fear an overproduction in milk in compact areas would 
depress prices for Midwestern producers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Compact fever is being fueled by narrow, geographic  
self-interest,'' said Connie Tipton, senior vice president of the 
International Dairy Foods Association, which represents milk 
processors. 
</P>
<P>
	IDFA argues that higher prices for producers means higher prices  
when consumers go to buy a gallon of milk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
