<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> WNBA, Union Near Labor Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Although its union claims the sides are close to  
reaching the WNBA's first ever collective bargaining agreement, the 
league says there are unresolved issues. 
</P>
<P>
	After two days of negotiations, a union spokesman said the only  
issue separating the sides involves player appearances at charity 
events. 
</P>
<P>
	But WNBA spokesman Mark Pray said, ``There are a number of  
unresolved issues and we do not have a deal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	No formal talks were held Wednesday while the sides considered  
their positions. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an issue we shouldn't even be talking about,'' said  
Pam Wheeler, executive director of the union. ``Our position is 
that part of the draw and success of the WNBA has been the women 
participating and helping charitable events. The limit would 
prevent them from supporting these efforts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 10-week WNBA season is scheduled to begin June 10. The labor  
dispute forced the postponement of the player draft, scheduled last 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Players are now required to make 22 appearances, eight of them  
commercial sponsor spots for which they are paid, four unpaid team 
appearances and up to 10 unpaid promotional appearances. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue is the player association's right to do additional  
not-for-profit events using its logo. The WNBA owns marketing and 
licensing rights to the union logo. 
</P>
<P>
	The union is not allowed to use its logo for commercial purposes  
with the men or women, but is permitted to use it for up to eight 
not-for-profit events for the men. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier, the sides had reached and then abandoned a four-year  
agreement when eacj claimed the other injected new terms at the 
last minute. 
</P>
<P>
	The union and league had agreed on a four-year deal that would  
increase minimum salaries from $15,000 to $30,000 for veterans and 
$25,000 for rookies. Those figures would increase to $40,000 and 
$30,000, respectively, by 2002. 
</P>
<P>
	The benefits package was to include year-round health and dental  
benefits, pension, maternity benefits and life insurance. 
</P>
<P>
	That tentative agreement included a reopener option for the  
league or the union after three years, with both sides agreeing to 
no-lockout, no-strike clauses. That agreement called for 5 percent 
increases a year for draft picks. Players from the folded ABL would 
be treated as rookies for salary purposes this year but not subject 
to option clauses that teams hold on other rookies for their second 
seasons. Veterans would no longer be subject to such options. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
